• Introduction 介绍
    • Rule #001: You can choose which games to play, but not their rules 规则一：你可以选择玩哪些游戏，但不能选择游戏规则。

    • Problems are not solved by addressing their symptoms, but by addressing their root cause 解决问题的关键不在于缓解症状，而在于找出问题的根源。
    • Make a not-to-do list 列一份不做事项清单

    • The most important question 最重要的问题
    • Chapter conclusion 本章结论
  • Move forward 向前走
    • What got you here won’t get you there 让你走到今天的方法，并不能带你走到明天。
    • Get better at spotting busywork 提高识别无意义工作的能力
    • Other people’s expectations aren’t your problem 别人的期望与你无关。
    • use negative emotions as a trigger 利用负面情绪作为触发因素
    • Taking responsibility will make you grow, not the other way around 承担责任会让你成长，而不是让你成长。
  • Do not seek perfection 不要追求完美。
    • Do not seek the absence of fear 不要试图消除恐惧。
    • Do not seek perfect efficiency 不要追求完美效率
    • Do not seek control 不要试图控制
    • Seek momentum, not perfection 追求势头，而非完美。
    • Everything can be a step forward 一切皆可成为前进的一步。
  • Know what you want and what its costs are, then pay them 先弄清楚你想要什么以及它的成本，然后再付款。
    • acknowledge what is important for you 明白什么对你来说最重要。
    • Know the costs of what you want 了解你想要的东西的成本
    • Once you decide what you want, work on paying its costs 一旦你决定了想要什么，就开始着手支付它的费用。
    • Distinguish between the necessary and the sufficient 区分必要条件和充分条件
  • Start 开始
    • Action is the trick to break vicious circles 行动是打破恶性循环的关键。
    • If you cannot take a big step, take a smaller one 如果你不能迈出一大步，那就迈出一小步。
    • Stress comes from unaddressed problems 压力源于未解决的问题。
    • Play stupid games, win stupid prizes 玩愚蠢的游戏，赢愚蠢的奖品。
    • Choose objectives you can influence 选择你能影响的目标
    • Pick ambitious goals 选择远大的目标
    • If it hasn’t been written down, it hasn’t been planned 如果没有写下来，那就说明还没有计划好。
  • Make yourself a compass 自制一个指南针
    • Self-respect is the compass for change that matters 自尊是引领变革的指南针，而变革才是真正重要的。
    • Bad decisions in life arise from having optimized for the wrong variable 生活中糟糕的决策源于对错误变量的优化。
  • Learn to learn 学会学习
    • Metapractice 元实践
    • Learn by doing 在实践中学习
    • Maximize feedback loops 最大化反馈回路
    • Attribute feedback to the specific 将反馈归因于具体情况
    • Only the practice that is deliberate matters 只有刻意为之的练习才重要。
    • Learning is about seeing. If you cannot understand something, ask what is there to see 学习在于观察。如果你不理解某些东西，就问问自己：有什么可以观察的？
    • Find out the implicit rules 找出隐含规则
    • You will regret not sharing more than sharing 你会后悔没有多多分享。
  • Get help 获取帮助
    • Build a reputation for not wasting time 建立不浪费时间的良好声誉
    • Get good at sending cold emails 学会如何发送陌生开发邮件
    • Listen without projecting your worldview 倾听时不要强加自己的世界观。
    • Listen to the old 听听老歌
    • Do not trust anyone who insists on being part of the solution 不要相信任何坚持要成为解决方案一部分的人。
    • Trust incentives rather than people 信任激励机制而非人
    • Trust actions rather than words 信任靠行动而非言语。
  • Lead 带领
    • Lead with action, not words 以行动而非言语为先。
    • Communicate your values by embracing their inconveniences 通过接受不便之处来传达你的价值观
    • Delegate results, not methods 委托结果，而非方法
    • The 20% rule for providing feedback 提供反馈的20%规则
    • Leading requires doing things that do not scale 领导力需要做那些无法规模化的事情。
  • Adopt a long-term perspective 采取长远的视角
    • Avoid shortcuts 避免走捷径
    • Solving the root causes of your problems does not cost you time; it gives you time 解决问题的根本原因并不会浪费你的时间；相反，它会为你节省时间。
    • If it’s not sustainable, it didn’t happen 如果它不可持续，那就等于没发生过。
    • Put your ego into your future self 把你的自尊心融入未来的自己。
    • Work on your internal karma 努力改善你的内在业力。
    • Never misstep twice in a row 切勿连续两次犯错
    • Do not chase success; instead, become the kind of person that attracts success 不要追逐成功；相反，要成为吸引成功的人。
    • Play the long game 着眼长远。
  • Work on your habits 培养好习惯
    • The standards you have today determine the life you will have in a few years 你今天所秉持的价值观决定了你几年后的生活水平。
    • Discipline is freedom 自律即自由
    • Successful people, at some point in their life, committed to the hard choice 成功人士在人生的某个阶段，都会做出艰难的选择。
    • Taking a course of action makes it easier to take it again. For better or for worse 采取某种行动会使再次采取同样的行动变得更容易。无论好坏。
    • Willpower is useless, unless used for tweaking the environment 意志力本身毫无用处，除非它被用来改变环境。
  • Avoid the toxic 避免接触有毒物质
    • Need is toxic 需求是有害的。
    • Treat your addictions by getting options 通过多种方式来治疗你的成瘾问题。
    • Life is about cultivating independence. 人生在于培养独立自主的能力。
    • To win negotiations, build independence 要赢得谈判，就要建立独立性。
    • Success isn’t being on top of a hierarchy, it is standing outside all hierarchies 成功不是身居高位，而是超越所有等级制度。
    • Integrity is the highest form of loyalty 正直是忠诚的最高形式。
    • Extraordinary people are extraordinarily selective 杰出的人往往极具选择性。
    • Do not despise what you need 不要轻视你所需要的东西。
    • The Silver Rule is better than the Golden Rule 银律优于金律
  • Make yourself antifragile 让自己变得反脆弱
    • Trigger overcompensation 触发过度补偿
    • Secure survival before optimizing performance 确保生存后再优化性能
    • Hit the sweet spot 击中最佳点
    • Consider yourself a container 把自己想象成一个容器
  • Be fair 要公平。
    • Above all, be fair 最重要的是，要公平。
    • Too often, the real problem is not what happened but how it was communicated 很多时候，真正的问题不在于发生了什么，而在于如何传达这件事。
  • Be effective 有效
    • Working hard without checking assumptions is a form of laziness 不经核实就埋头苦干是一种懒惰的表现。
    • Pareto prioritize 帕累托优先级
    • Go via negativa 通过否定
    • Your problems aren’t different 你的问题也没什么不同。
    • you are the source of most of your problems 你自身的大部分问题都是根源。
    • Pick your environment 选择你的环境
  • Recondition yourself 重新调整自己
    • there is a space between stimulus and response 刺激与反应之间存在一个空间
    • It is your responsibility to recondition yourself to the situations which evoke negative emotions in you 你有责任重新调整自己，以适应那些会引发你负面情绪的情境。
    • For change to happen, incentives have to be changed 要实现变革，就必须改变激励机制。
    • Where incentives are encoded matters 激励机制的编码方式至关重要。
  • Learn to be happy 学会快乐
    • Happiness is a direction 幸福是一种方向
    • Happiness is self-respect 幸福就是自尊
  • Know yourself 了解自己
    • Know and accept your rules 了解并接受你的规则
    • Do not overcompensate 不要矫枉过正
  • Main principles 主要原则
    • Ruthlessly prioritize 无情地确定优先事项
    • Maximize compounding loops 最大化复利循环
    • Iterate 迭代
  • Conclusions 结论
    • Life is about resisting erosion 生命就是抵抗侵蚀。
    • Life is about becoming someone we respect 人生在于成为我们尊重的人。

Introduction

介绍

Rule #001: You can choose which games to play, but not their rules

规则一：你可以选择玩哪些游戏，但不能选择游戏规则。

Most frustration and unhappiness in your life will come from disrespecting the rules of whatever “game” you are a participant of – be it love, business, health, or social life.

生活中大多数的挫折和不快乐都来自于不尊重你参与的任何“游戏”的规则——无论是爱情、事业、健康还是社交生活。

Perhaps, you did not know about the existence of such rules because no one explained them to you. In this case, you might think that the world doesn’t make sense and that people are irrational. That’s what I thought when I was 14 and did not understand why some girls were so fond of the “bad boys” in my school.

或许你根本不知道有这样的规则，因为没人跟你解释过。在这种情况下，你可能会觉得这个世界毫无道理，人们也缺乏理性。我14岁的时候也是这么想的，当时我不明白为什么有些女生那么喜欢学校里的“坏男生”。

Or perhaps, you knew about some of such rules but chose to disrespect them because you didn’t like their implication. For example, everyone knows the two rules to lose weight: eat healthily and exercise. However, most do not act on them because they’re uncomfortable practicing them day after day or do not have the time or energy to do so.

或许，你明明知道其中一些规则，却因为不喜欢它们的含义而选择无视。例如，人人都知道减肥的两条规则：健康饮食和运动。然而，大多数人并没有付诸行动，因为他们觉得日复一日地坚持下去很不自在，或者根本没有时间和精力。

We cannot live happily wishing the world followed the rules we are comfortable with. Or, at least, we cannot do it for long. The universe relentlessly punishes those who do not follow its rules.

我们无法安心地希望世界遵循我们习以为常的规则。或者至少，我们无法长久如此。宇宙会无情地惩罚那些不遵守其规则的人。

Paraphrasing Paulo Coelho, failures are life’s way of teaching us its rules. In particular, those we do not want to learn.

套用保罗·科埃略的话来说，失败是生活教会我们规则的方式。尤其是那些我们不想学习的规则。

IN THIS BOOK,

本书中，

You will find 100 rules that apply to the most important areas of your life.

你会发现100条适用于你生活中最重要领域的规则。

I call them rules because breaking them has consequences. In the words of bestselling author Stephen Covey, while we are free to choose our actions, we cannot choose their consequences.

我称它们为规则，因为违反规则会带来后果。正如畅销书作家史蒂芬·柯维所说，虽然我们可以自由选择自己的行为，但我们无法选择行为的后果。

Apart from the few unfortunate cases in which something bad happened to one of my loved ones, every single time I felt hurt, it was because I broke one of the rules of life. Pain, sadness, and frustration result from not having learned the rules by which the world works or having chosen to disrespect them.

除了少数亲人遭遇不幸的情况外，我每次感到痛苦，都是因为我违反了生活中的某条规则。痛苦、悲伤和沮丧源于没有了解世界的运行规律，或者选择不尊重这些规律。

Over the years, learning from my mistakes, I internalized these rules. Now, I have a fulfilling life of which I’m proud and for which I highly respect myself.

多年来，我从错误中吸取教训，并将这些原则内化于心。如今，我拥有充实的生活，我为此感到自豪，也由衷地尊重自己。

With this book, I entrust you with the rules I learned through experience, allowing you to learn from them without first having to experience on your skin the consequences of breaking them.

通过这本书，我将我通过经验总结出的规则托付给你，让你能够从中学习，而无需先亲身经历违反这些规则的后果。

DISCLAIMER

免责声明

The content of this book consists of learnings I made based on my experience. While I genuinely think they might help most readers, they are very contextual. Only you know what’s best for you. Always use your common sense. None of what is written in this book is to be considered medical advice, financial advice, investment advice, or advice of any other kind. The author shall not be held liable for the consequences of the application or misapplication of the contents of this book.

本书内容是我根据自身经验总结出的感悟。虽然我真心认为这些感悟或许能对大多数读者有所帮助，但它们也具有很强的情境性。只有您自己才知道什么对您最有利。请务必运用您的常识。本书中的任何内容均不构成医疗建议、财务建议、投资建议或任何其他类型的建议。作者对因应用或误用本书内容而导致的任何后果概不负责。

Prioritize your growth

优先考虑你的成长

Rule 2

规则 2

The very important never feels urgent

非常重要的事情永远不会让人感到紧迫。

The most common regret people have on their deathbed is to have spent their life chasing the urgent, neglecting to do what was actually important.

人们临终前最常见的遗憾是，一生都在追逐紧急的事情，而忽略了真正重要的事情。

Family meals, drinks with friends, learning, and taking care of our health are all very important activities. And yet, we often skip them to attend meetings and other urgent errands.

家庭聚餐、与朋友小酌、学习以及照顾好自己的健康都是非常重要的活动。然而，我们却常常为了参加会议和其他紧急事务而忽略它们。

Because the very important does not have a deadline , we have the impression that we can delay it for a few days. It is a huge mistake. Delaying something once opens the door to delaying it forever.

因为非常重要的事情没有截止日期，我们便误以为可以拖延几天。这是个巨大的错误。拖延一次，就意味着以后永远无法挽回。

If you think about it, the very important never feels urgent. Instead, most of what feels urgent is important for someone else , not for you .

仔细想想，真正重要的事情往往不会让人觉得紧急。相反，大多数让你觉得紧急的事情，对别人来说很重要，对你来说却并非如此。

Why do people acknowledge the very important only on their deathbed? Because, finally, facing death, the very important has a deadline. On the verge of leaving this world, the very important becomes urgent.

为什么人们只有在临终之际才会意识到那些真正重要的事情？因为，最终面对死亡，那些真正重要的事情都有了期限。在即将离开这个世界的时候，那些真正重要的事情变得迫在眉睫。

ACTION

行动

You do not have to wait for your life to near its end. Make the very important urgent, now. Incorporate it within your schedule. Treat your family time, friends time, learning time, and workout time as if they were meetings with clients. Give them slots in your calendar and be inflexible about them. After all, your schedule is where your real priorities show up.

你无需等到生命即将走到尽头才行动。现在就把真正重要的事情变得紧迫起来，并将它们纳入你的日程安排。对待家人、朋友、学习和锻炼的时间，要像对待客户会议一样认真。在日历上为它们预留时间，并且严格执行。毕竟，你的日程安排才能真正体现你的优先事项。

Soon, you will respect yourself more for having done what is important. That will be the engine that will give you the motivation and energy to persist.

很快，你会因为做了重要的事情而更加尊重自己。这将成为你坚持下去的动力和能量的源泉。

#↩
Rule 3
规则 3

Problems grow TO the size they need for you to acknowledge them

问题会发展到你不得不正视它们的地步。

Jack Kent tells us the story of a little boy, Billy, who, one day, finds a dragon the size of a cat in his bedroom. Billy’s mother ignores it – after all, there is no such thing as a dragon. Day after day, the dragon keeps growing, ignored. One day, it grows so much that it wrecks Billy’s house with its size. Faced with a destroyed home, Billy’s mother acknowledges the dragon. Finally, it starts shrinking. At the end of the story, Billy’s mother asks: “Why did the dragon grow so big?” Billy answers: “I’m not sure, but I think it just wanted to be noticed.”

杰克·肯特给我们讲了一个小男孩比利的故事。有一天，比利在卧室里发现了一条猫大小的龙。比利的妈妈没理会它——毕竟，世上根本没有龙这种东西。日复一日，龙越长越大，却无人理会。有一天，它长得如此之大，以至于把比利的房子都毁了。面对被毁的家园，比利的妈妈终于注意到了龙的存在。最后，龙开始缩小。故事的结尾，比利的妈妈问：“为什么龙会长得那么大？”比利回答说：“我也不知道，但我认为它只是想引起我的注意。”

Problems grow to the size they need for us to acknowledge them.

问题发展到一定程度，我们才会意识到它们的重要性。

There are many reasons for which problems appear. However, there is a single reason for which they grow: if we ignore them.

问题出现的原因有很多，但问题滋生的原因只有一个：那就是我们忽视它们。

By acknowledging a problem and its consequences, the risks of letting it grow become clear and, therefore, urgent. You will be compelled to act immediately. Acknowledging problems is the first step toward solving them and regaining mental peace. Instead, if you ignore your problems, you deprive yourself of the very fuel you need to act.

正视问题及其后果，就能清晰地认识到放任问题恶化的风险，从而意识到问题的紧迫性。你会被迫立即采取行动。承认问题是解决问题、重获内心平静的第一步。相反，如果你忽视问题，就会失去采取行动所需的动力。

The simple act of taking a pen and writing down the list of problems affecting you and the ways they negatively impact your life will often be all you need. If this is too much, choose a single issue and write about that one only. But do write about it . Simply thinking about it will not be enough. Your unconscious mind needs material proof that you acknowledged the problem and its consequences.

拿起笔，把影响你的问题以及它们对你生活造成的负面影响都写下来，这通常就足够了。如果觉得太多，那就选择一个问题，只写这一个。但一定要写下来。光想是不够的。你的潜意识需要实际的证据来证明你已经意识到了问题及其后果。

ACTION:

行动：

Do it right now .

现在就去做。

Put down the book, take a pen, and write.

放下书，拿起笔，开始写。

What problems are you facing? How will your life be affected if you do not address them immediately?

你面临哪些问题？如果不立即解决这些问题，你的生活会受到怎样的影响？

You do not need to write about how you will solve the problem. Just write about the problem itself.

你不需要写如何解决这个问题，只需要写问题本身即可。

The goal of this exercise is not to figure out how to solve your problems but to acknowledge them. This is the first necessary step towards regaining control of your life and transforming it into the life you want to live.

这项练习的目的不是为了找到解决问题的方法，而是为了正视问题。这是重新掌控人生、将其转变为你想要的生活的必要第一步。

#↩
Rule 4
规则 4

Problems are not solved by addressing their symptoms,
but by addressing their root cause

解决问题的关键不在于解决表面症状，而在于找出问题的根源。

Look closely at some friend, relative, or colleague who has been struggling with the same problem for months. They are probably stuck because they spend their efforts relieving the symptoms of their problem rather than tackling the actual problem once and for all.

仔细观察一下你的朋友、亲戚或同事，他们可能几个月来一直被同一个问题困扰。他们之所以深陷困境，很可能是因为他们把精力都放在缓解问题的症状上，而不是彻底解决问题的根源。

…

A man in a sinking ship has a problem: water in the boat. However, taking a bucket and throwing the water overboard will not improve his situation. At least, not until he solves the root of that problem: the hole in the ship. Unless he fixes the hole, the water he throws away will be replaced by more water spilling in from it.

一艘正在下沉的船上，一个人遇到了一个难题：船里进水了。然而，仅仅用桶把水泼到海里并不能解决问题。至少，在他找到问题的根源——船底的破洞——之前，情况不会好转。除非他修补好破洞，否则他泼出去的水很快就会被从破洞里涌进来的更多水取代。

Similarly, solving a problem without solving its root cause will only improve your situation temporarily. Until you solve the root cause, you will constantly be presented with more (of the same) problems.

同样，如果不解决根本原因，仅仅解决问题只能暂时改善现状。在找到根本原因之前，你将不断面临更多（同样的）问题。

Solving a problem without solving its root cause is like taking a step forward and then one back. Many enjoy the dance but then complain it doesn’t bring them anywhere. Don’t be like them.

解决问题却不解决其根本原因，就像前进了一步又后退了一步。许多人享受这种忙碌的过程，却抱怨它毫无意义。不要像他们那样。

Solving the root causes of your problems might not feel urgent but is the only way forward.

解决问题的根本原因或许并不显得迫切，但却是唯一的出路。

…

Fact: you will have to face problems all your life.
事实：你一生中都会面临各种问题。
Also a fact: you can decide whether they will be the same ones over and over.
另一个事实：你可以决定这些问题是否会反复出现。

ACTION:

行动：

Think about a recurring problem of yours. What have you done so far to solve it? Will it prevent any further occurrence of such a problem? If not, you need to stop doing what you are currently doing to address that problem and do something else instead.

想想你反复遇到的一个问题。你目前为止都做了些什么来解决这个问题？这些措施能防止问题再次发生吗？如果不能，你就需要停止目前解决这个问题的方法，转而尝试其他方法。

Write down, NOW, what you will do to ensure that the problem will never show up again.

现在就写下你将采取哪些措施来确保问题不再发生。

If acting on what you wrote down would take less than half an hour, do it immediately. Put this book down and do it. Otherwise, take your calendar (do it now!) and schedule the action.

如果执行你写下的内容只需不到半小时，那就立刻行动。放下这本书，马上去做。否则，拿出你的日历（现在就做！），安排好行动时间。

#↩
Rule 5
规则5

Make a not-to-do list

列一份不做事项清单

Billionaire Warren Buffett used to give the following advice to his subordinates. Make a list of the top 25 actions you should take during the next three months, ordered from the most impactful to the least. Then, select the top 5 items: these become your to-do list. Finally, select the bottom 20 items: these become your not-to-do list. You are not allowed to work on your not-to-do list until the to-do list is completed.

亿万富翁沃伦·巴菲特过去常常给他的下属这样的建议：列出未来三个月内你应该采取的25项最重要的行动，并按重要性从高到低排序。然后，选出最重要的5项：这构成你的待办事项清单。最后，选出最不重要的20项：这构成你的不做事项清单。在待办事项清单完成之前，你不允许处理不做事项清单上的事情。

Without a not-to-do list, you might spend your time and energy on the most comfortable actions (busywork), not the most impactful ones. Instead, using the not-to-do list, you remain focused on what’s important.

如果没有“不做清单”，你可能会把时间和精力浪费在最轻松的事情（无意义的琐事）上，而不是最有意义的事情上。相反，有了“不做清单”，你就能始终专注于重要的事情。

The enemy of productivity isn’t laziness but busywork. Not-to-do lists are your solution to it.

生产力的敌人不是懒惰，而是无意义的忙碌。而“不做事项清单”正是解决之道。

ACTION:

行动：

Implement a not-to-do list for yourself:

给自己制定一份“不做清单”：

1. Make a list of the top 25 actions you should take during the next months.

1. 列出你在接下来的几个月里应该采取的最重要的 25 项行动。

2. Order the list items from the most impactful to the least impactful.

2. 将列表项按影响程度从大到小排序。

3. Then, select the top 5 items: these are your to-do list.

3. 然后，选择最重要的 5 项：这些就是你的待办事项清单。

4. Finally, select the bottom 20 items: these are your not-to-do list.

4. 最后，选择最后 20 项：这些是你的不做清单。

Once you’re done, pin both lists (the to-do one and the not-to-do one) somewhere you can regularly check them.

完成后，将这两个清单（待办事项清单和不做事项清单）贴在你经常可以查看的地方。

If you find yourself transgressing (by working on some of the not-to-do items before having finished the to-do ones), ask yourself: what should I tweak, in my environment or in my way of working, so that I will not transgress again?

如果你发现自己违反了规则（在完成待办事项之前就去做一些不该做的事情），问问自己：我应该在我的环境或我的工作方式中做出哪些调整，才能避免再次违反规则？

#↩
Rule 6
规则 6

Do your activities make your life better?

你的活动是否让你的生活更美好？

American History X is one of my favorite movies. Academy Award nominee Edward Norton plays the role of a young adult who spent years in gangs with toxic acquaintances and professing toxic political beliefs. A turning point in the movie, in which the main character begins to consider setting his life straight, is when his history teacher from high school asks him: “Did any of those things make your life better?”

《美国X档案》是我最喜欢的电影之一。奥斯卡奖提名者爱德华·诺顿饰演一位年轻男子，他多年来混迹于帮派，结交损友，并宣扬有害的政治观点。影片的一个转折点，也是主人公开始考虑走上正轨的时刻，是他的高中历史老师问他：“那些事让你的生活变得更好了吗？”

We often engage in activities that are not good for us, especially if done too much. Some examples include drinking, frequenting friends who are still fleeing from responsibilities even after their 20s, watching TV or playing video games until 2 AM on a weekday, complaining, and so on.

我们常常会做一些对我们不利的事情，尤其是过度沉迷其中的时候。例如，喝酒、经常和那些即使过了二十多岁仍然逃避责任的朋友聚会、工作日熬夜看电视或玩电子游戏到凌晨两点、抱怨等等。

The key question is: did any of these activities make your life better?

关键问题是：这些活动是否让你的生活变得更好了？

If not, it is time to stop. It is the landmark of addiction to repeat something bad for us knowing it is bad for us. Do not behave like an addict.

否则，就该停止了。明知有害却依然重复，这是成瘾的标志。不要像瘾君子一样行事。

ACTION:

行动：

What activity do you regularly engage with, even if it does not improve your life? Any chance you can substitute it with something more likely to improve your life?

你经常从事哪些活动，即使它对你的生活没有改善作用？你有没有可能用一些更有可能改善你生活的事情来替代它？

Do not focus on stopping the former. Focus on substituting it with the latter.

不要把重点放在阻止前者上，而要放在用后者来替代它上。

Which emotions do you regularly engage with, even though they worsen your life? Is there any activity you are undertaking that summons them (e.g., looking at your ex’s social media feed)?

你经常会陷入哪些情绪中，即使这些情绪会让你的生活变得更糟？你是否在进行某些活动时会唤起这些情绪（例如，浏览前任的社交媒体动态）？

#↩
Rule 7
规则7

Most mistakes are forms
of clinging to the past

大多数错误都是对过去的执着。

By examining myself and my story, I noticed the following .

通过审视自己和我的经历，我注意到以下几点。

Every mistake I ever made was a form of clinging to the past.

我犯过的每一个错误，都是对过去的一种执着。

Clinging:
执着：
- To who I was
- 执着于过去的自己，
- To what I was doing
- 执着于过去的所作所为，
- To what I knew how to do
- 执着于我所擅长的，
- To who I knew how to be
- 执着于我所熟悉的自己，
- To what made me feel good
- 执着于让我感觉良好的事物，
- To what made me feel safe
- 执着于让我感到安全的事物

You do not have to be your past. You can be someone else without anyone having to give you permission.

你不必成为过去的自己。你可以成为另一个人，无需任何人的许可。

Authorization to change is mostly an illusion. Most changes that last are bottom-up, initiated without someone else’s permission. The consent is usually formalized after the change takes place. Give yourself permission to change.

获得改变的授权大多是一种错觉。大多数持久的改变都是自下而上发生的，无需他人许可。通常情况下，只有在改变发生之后，才会正式获得授权。给自己一个改变的许可吧。

Yoga teacher Heeki Park used to conclude her lessons reminding her students that, as they leave the room, they don’t have to be the same person they were when they entered it. Similarly, as you walk through your day, you don’t have to be the same person you have been.

瑜伽老师朴熙琪（Heeki Park）过去常常在课程结束时提醒学生们，离开教室时，他们不必还是进来时的那个人。同样，你每一天的生活也不必总是做过去的自己。

ACTION:

行动：

What would you do if you didn’t feel obligated to act like the person you’ve been?

如果你不必再像以前那样行事，你会做什么？

#↩
Rule 8
规则8

The most important question

最重要的问题

“If you keep doing what you are currently doing, how will your life be in 10 years?”

“如果你继续做你现在做的事情，10年后你的生活会是什么样子？”

ACTION:

行动：

Answer the question above. Honestly.

请如实回答以上问题。

Then, if you are not satisfied with the contents of your answer, make the necessary adjustments to how you spend your days.

然后，如果你对答案的内容不满意，那就对你每天的安排做出必要的调整。

#↩

Chapter conclusion

本章结论

Prioritizing your personal growth is vital for your success and happiness. This is because, as you will eventually learn through experience, all long-lasting changes to your personal life occur indirectly.

重视个人成长对你的成功和幸福至关重要。这是因为，正如你最终会从经验中体会到的那样，所有对你个人生活产生持久影响的改变都是间接发生的。

You will not attract a great partner with a bold approach and some well-chosen words. Instead, you will attract them by having worked on yourself so that you have become a partner of value.

靠大胆的手段和几句甜言蜜语，你无法吸引到优秀的伴侣。相反，你需要不断提升自我，让自己成为一个有价值的伴侣，才能真正吸引到他们。

Nor will you get a great job by acing a job interview or asking a favor of the right person. Instead, you will get a great job by having worked on yourself so that you have become a professional worth being employed and sought out by great companies or great individuals.

你既不能靠面试成功，也不能靠求人帮忙找到好工作。相反，你只有不断提升自己，成为值得被优秀公司或优秀人才聘用的专业人士，才能获得一份好工作。

Shape yourself so that your world reshapes upon you in a way you like.

塑造你自己，让你的世界按照你喜欢的方式重塑你。

ACTION:

行动：

Look for an area of your life in which you feel some frustration. Then, ask yourself: what is it that the world keeps shouting, yet I am ignoring?

找出生活中让你感到沮丧的领域。然后问问自己：这个世界一直在呐喊什么，而我却视而不见？

Which implicit rule about how the world works are you failing to acknowledge?

你究竟忽略了世界运行的哪条不成文规则？

Which implicit rule do you wish were different?

你希望哪条不成文的规则有所不同？

Failing to acknowledge the implicit rules of this world will always be your largest obstacle.

忽视这个世界不成文的规则，永远是你最大的障碍。

#↩

Move forward

向前走

Rules 9-13

规则 9-13

Part of making your life better is about doing what would improve it. Another part is to stop doing what gets you stuck. Otherwise, it is like driving with the handbrake on.

改善生活的一部分在于去做那些能改善生活的事情，另一部分在于停止去做那些让你停滞不前的事情。否则，就像拉着手刹开车一样。

Here are five rules that will help you recognize what is slowing you down.

以下五条规则可以帮助你认识到是什么在拖慢你的速度。

Rule 9
规则9

What got you here won’t get you there

让你走到今天的方法，并不能带你走到明天。

Four years ago, over a cup of coffee, my colleague confided his doubts about one of his subordinates. “She’s working too hard.”

四年前，在喝咖啡的时候，我的同事向我吐露了他对一位下属的疑虑。“她工作太拼命了。”

I was puzzled. He continued: “She wants a promotion, but I cannot give it to her. So far, her solution to problems has been to work longer hours. If I give her another promotion and more responsibilities, she will either burn out juggling too many balls or let some drop.”

我感到困惑。他接着说：“她想要升职，但我不能给她。到目前为止，她解决问题的办法就是加班。如果我再给她升职，让她承担更多责任，她要么会因为同时处理太多事情而精疲力竭，要么会有所疏漏。”

Two lessons here. First, working harder only scales to a certain point. Second, what got you here won’t get you there. 1 Life is made of stages. What works in one stage often doesn’t work in the next one.

这里有两点启示。第一，努力工作的效果只能达到一定程度。第二，让你走到今天的方法未必能让你走到明天。人生是由不同的阶段组成的。在一个阶段行之有效的方法，在下一个阶段往往就行不通了。

People plateau when they abandon learning new things and instead focus on doing the old ones harder. What produced improvements in the past probably won’t keep delivering them indefinitely. 2

当人们放弃学习新事物，转而专注于更加努力地完成旧事物时，他们的进步就会停滞不前。过去行之有效的方法，未必能永远持续带来进步。

To get “promoted” to the next stage in life, do not do what got you to the current stage. Instead, do what people at the next stage do.

要想“晋升”到人生的下一个阶段，不要再做让你走到今天这一步的事情。相反，要去做那些已经处于下一个阶段的人所做的事情。

Careful not to skip any step by looking at what people multiple stages above you do, though: it might cause you to miss a step. And careful not to neglect your responsibilities at your current stage. That said, keep an eye on what the people at the stage above you do. What they are doing might show you how to join them in that next stage.

不过，切记不要因为观察比你高好几个阶段的人的做法而跳过任何步骤：这可能会导致你错过关键步骤。同时，也要注意不要忽视你当前阶段的职责。话虽如此，你还是应该密切关注比你高一个阶段的人的做法。他们的做法或许能为你指明如何迈向下一个阶段。

ACTION:

行动：

What is one habit or behavior of yours that proved beneficial in the past but is near useless for future growth?

你有哪些习惯或行为在过去被证明是有益的，但对未来的发展几乎毫无用处？

BONUS:

奖金：

If you work at a company and regularly work overtime, consider stopping at 5 PM sharp. Then, use the freed-up time to dedicate to your professional advancement – learn a new skill, shadow a senior employee, start a work-related side-project, and so on.

如果你在一家公司工作并且经常加班，不妨考虑下午5点准时下班。然后，利用省下来的时间专注于你的职业发展——学习一项新技能、跟随资深员工学习、开展与工作相关的副业等等。

Similarly, try to refuse projects and assignments which are “too much of the same of what you are already doing.” Instead, ask for responsibilities that would bring you in contact with that which people at the next stage of your career do.

同样地，尽量拒绝那些“与你目前所做工作过于雷同”的项目和任务。相反，要主动争取那些能让你接触到你职业生涯下一阶段所做工作的职责。

In general: strive to put an artificial limit to “your current stage’s work” and free up time to do “the next stage’s work.”

总的来说：努力人为地限制“你当前阶段的工作”，腾出时间来做“下一阶段的工作”。

#↩
Rule 10
规则 10

Get better at spotting busywork

提高识别无意义工作的能力

Writing an extra email update to your boss just to show that you’ve been working hard is a form of busywork – work that doesn’t add value. You probably know this already.

仅仅为了向老板表明自己一直在努力工作而额外写一封邮件汇报工作进展，这是一种无谓的忙碌——并不会增加任何价值。你可能早就明白这一点了。

But there is a subtler form of busywork: work that you do because you think it adds value (but doesn’t). Here are some examples:

但还有一种更隐蔽的忙碌形式：你做这些工作是因为你认为它们有价值（但实际上并没有）。以下是一些例子：

– A gym exercise that you keep repeating because you think will add muscle (but doesn’t).

– 你不断重复的健身房锻炼动作，因为你认为可以增加肌肉（但实际上并没有）。

– Networking at events attended by people who are there to suck value rather than provide it.

– 在那些只想榨取价值而不是提供价值的人参加的活动中建立人脉。

– Writing ten more cold emails with the same template that didn’t work.

– 用同样的模板又写了十封推销邮件，结果都没成功。

We cannot rely on examining our motivations to spot busywork because sincere motivations can still be ineffective. Hence the importance of spotting busywork by looking for the absence of results.

我们不能仅仅依靠审视自己的动机来识别无意义的忙碌，因为即使是真诚的动机也可能无效。因此，识别无意义的忙碌的关键在于观察其是否产生了实际效果。

ACTION:

行动：

Pick an area of your life where you feel stuck. Then, ask yourself the following two questions.

选择生活中你感觉停滞不前的领域。然后，问自己以下两个问题。

– What you’re doing right now, is it helping?

你现在所做的事情，对你有帮助吗？

– Is it something done by people who achieved your goals or merely by people who aspire to them?

——这是已经实现你目标的人所做的事情，还是仅仅是渴望实现你目标的人所做的事情？

#↩
Rule 11
规则 11

Other people’s expectations
aren’t your problem

别人的期望与你无关

Too often, people end up pursuing what they do not want because others expect them to do so. And too often, people avoid pursuing their dreams because others have different plans for them.

人们常常因为别人期望而去做自己不想要的事情。人们也常常因为别人另有安排而放弃追求自己的梦想。

But you do not have to live up to other people’s expectations.

但你不必满足别人的期望。

People’s expectations of you aren’t your problem. They are their problem. (Unless you entered an explicit agreement with them, such as a contract or an exchange. In this case, it’s your problem. But here, we’re talking about implicit expectations or imposed ones.)

别人对你的期望不是你的问题，而是他们的问题。（除非你和他们达成了明确的协议，比如合同或交换协议。在这种情况下，那就是你的问题。但这里我们讨论的是隐含的期望或强加的期望。）

Are your friends or parents disappointed you didn’t make the choice they wished? It is their problem. By choosing to expect, they chose the possibility of being disappointed – their choice, their responsibility. Your parents are justified in having reasonable expectations about how you should treat them but not about how you should live your life.

你的朋友或父母是否因为你没有做出他们希望的选择而感到失望？那是他们的问题。他们既然选择了期待，就等于选择了可能失望——这是他们的选择，也是他们的责任。你的父母有理由对你如何对待他们抱有合理的期望，但他们无权干涉你的生活方式。

When a family member has expectations for you, he is being narcissistic. He loves his perspective more than he loves you. Narcissism is their problem, and they must deal with its consequences.

当家人对你抱有期望时，他就是自恋的。他更看重自己的视角，而不是你的感受。自恋是他们的问题，他们必须承担其后果。

Someone who had learned how to love would love without expectations. If your friends and family members have not yet learned how to love unconditionally, it is their problem, not yours.

真正懂得爱的人会不求回报地去爱。如果你的朋友和家人还没有学会无条件地爱，那是他们的问题，不是你的。

Take responsibility for your problems, and let other people take responsibility for theirs.

为自己的问题负责，也让其他人为他们的问题负责。

ACTION

行动

Every time you feel someone’s expectations of you, think about the lines above. Then, remind yourself that their expectations are their problem, not yours.

每当你感受到别人对你的期望时，想想上面这些话。然后提醒自己，他们的期望是他们的问题，不是你的。

#↩
Rule 12
规则 12

use negative emotions as a trigger

利用负面情绪作为触发因素

Some negative emotions can help us diagnose problems in our life:

某些负面情绪可以帮助我们诊断生活中的问题：

– Frustration indicates a lack of understanding of some fundamental “rules of the game.”

挫败感表明对一些基本的“游戏规则”缺乏了解。

– Feeling ashamed to follow up on other people’s promises to you suggests that you should make clearer agreements. (The same applies if you are a manager and feel ashamed to tell someone he isn’t doing a good job. You are probably setting unclear objectives, which makes you feel partially responsible for your subordinates’ underperformance.)

——如果你不好意思兑现别人对你的承诺，说明你应该把约定说得更清楚一些。（如果你是管理者，不好意思指出别人工作做得不好，也是同样的道理。你可能设定的目标不够明确，这让你觉得自己要为下属的表现不佳承担部分责任。）

– Stress signals a problem you lack plans for.

压力表明你缺乏应对问题的计划。

– Chronic fatigue hints at a problem with your habits or environment.

慢性疲劳可能暗示你的习惯或环境存在问题。

– Jealousy signals that you’re engaging in zero-sum games.

嫉妒表明你正在进行零和博弈。

It is tempting to react to negative emotions with avoidance or denial. Yet, doing so won’t help you. Instead, use them as a signal of the need for change.

面对负面情绪，人们很容易选择逃避或否认。然而，这样做并不能帮助你。相反，你应该把这些情绪当作需要改变的信号。

ACTION:

行动：

When was the last time you felt any of the emotions described above? Does it indicate an underlying problem in your life? If so, what can you do to address it?

你上一次感受到上述任何一种情绪是什么时候？这是否表明你生活中存在潜在问题？如果是，你可以采取哪些措施来解决？

#↩
Rule 13
第13条规则

Taking responsibility will make you grow, not the other way around

承担责任会让你成长，而不是让你成长。

Teachers promoting you from primary to secondary school, from secondary to high school, and perhaps from high school to college. Parents giving you a bicycle, then some pocket money, then a mobile phone. Your coach moving you to the first team or telling you to sign up for the regional competition.

老师们把你从小学升入中学，从中学升入高中，或许还会从高中升入大学。父母先是给你买自行车，然后是零花钱，最后是手机。教练把你提拔到一线队，或者让你报名参加地区比赛。

During your childhood, adults have been giving you the green light to assume roles involving more responsibilities. You learned that, as you grow, responsibilities are assigned.

在你的童年时期，大人们就一直鼓励你承担更多责任。你也逐渐明白，随着年龄的增长，责任也会随之而来。

Then, one day, as an adult, you get a job. As time passes, your boss does not promote you. “He isn’t giving me a chance to take on more responsibility,” you might complain. “He isn’t letting me grow,” you sigh in frustration. You lose motivation. Your thinking shifts: “Why should I take any responsibility if he doesn’t promote me?” Now you avoid responsibilities. The situation worsens. You consider quitting, but you can’t – who will hire you, you think, if you did not get the chance to handle any responsibility at your current job?

然后，有一天，你长大成人，找到了一份工作。随着时间的推移，你的老板没有提拔你。“他不给我机会承担更多责任，”你可能会抱怨。“他不让我成长，”你沮丧地叹息。你失去了动力。你的想法发生了转变：“如果他不提拔我，我为什么要承担任何责任？”现在你开始逃避责任。情况越来越糟。你想辞职，但你做不到——你心想，如果你在现在的工作中没有机会承担任何责任，谁还会雇用你呢？

The way out of this nightmarish scenario is to realize that, in adulthood, opportunities follow taking responsibility. Take ownership of the problems you face. Opportunities will follow.

摆脱这种噩梦般困境的出路在于认识到，成年后，机遇往往伴随着责任感而来。勇于承担你所面临的问题，机遇自然会随之而来。

This is not limited to your career. Once you take responsibility for your life, partners, friendships, and opportunities will appear.

这不仅限于你的职业生涯。一旦你为自己的人生负责，伴侣、友谊和机遇就会出现。

“The sad news is, nobody owes you a career. You own it as a sole proprietor.” – Andy Grove, Former CEO of Intel

“令人遗憾的是，没有人有义务为你提供一份事业。作为个体经营者，你的事业完全属于你自己。”——安迪·格鲁夫，英特尔前首席执行官

ACTION:

行动：

If you were a friend of yours responsible for helping yourself grow professionally, what would you advise yourself to do?

如果你是自己的朋友，需要帮助自己实现职业发展，你会建议自己怎么做？

#↩

Do not seek perfection

不要追求完美。

Rules 14 to 18

规则14至18

Perfection is the enemy of both achievement and perfection itself.

完美主义既是成就的敌人，也是完美本身的敌人。

The more you seek perfection, the fewer pieces of your work you will share. And the fewer you show, the less feedback you’ll get. And the less feedback you get, the longer it will take you to walk the road to success and perfection.

你越追求完美，就越不愿意分享自己的作品。你展示的作品越少，得到的反馈就越少。而你得到的反馈越少，通往成功和完美的道路就越漫长。

This chapter examines four common obstacles you will find in your path to happiness and personal achievement.

本章将探讨你在通往幸福和个人成就的道路上会遇到的四个常见障碍。

#↩
Rule 14
规则14

Do not seek the absence of fear

不要试图消除恐惧。

Henry Fonda, the iconic Western actor, used to throw up before each stage performance, up to the age of seventy-five. He didn’t become successful because he was fearless but because he acted despite his fear. 3

西部片传奇演员亨利·方达，直到75岁高龄，每次登台演出前都会呕吐。他并非因为无所畏惧而获得成功，而是因为他克服恐惧，坚持表演。

The absence of fear is a myth. Sure, a few rare people cannot feel it. But for most of us, fear is a given. And there is no way around it, only through it. There is no escape, only coexistence.

恐惧不存在只是个神话。诚然，极少数人确实感受不到恐惧。但对我们大多数人来说，恐惧是与生俱来的。我们无法逃避它，只能与之共存。没有出路，只有与之共存。

ACTION:

行动：

What’s an action you would like to take but are too afraid to take?

你最想做但却因为害怕而不敢做的事情是什么？

Is your fear rational? If not, acknowledge that there won’t be a perfect moment in which you will not feel it. Accept that the fear is here to stay – the only question is whether you will act through it.

你的恐惧合理吗？如果不合理，那就承认你永远无法摆脱恐惧。接受恐惧会一直存在——唯一的问题是，你是否会采取行动来克服它。

Will you?

你会？

#↩
Rule 15
规则15

Do not seek perfect efficiency

不要追求完美效率

100% efficiency is the holy grail of team management. And yet, it is a mirage.

100% 的效率是团队管理的终极目标。然而，它只是一个海市蜃楼。

Sustained performance requires time spent recovering, learning, pondering, and other intangibles that pure measures of physical output cannot capture. Seeking perfect efficiency today leads to subpar work tomorrow.

持续的高绩效需要时间用于恢复、学习、思考以及其他无法用单纯的体力产出衡量的无形因素。追求今日的完美效率只会导致明日的低效工作。

This doesn’t mean that you shouldn’t be on the lookout for waste to eliminate. But it means that you shouldn’t define waste as “what doesn’t produce value today.” Instead, define it as “what won’t have mattered for your career.” (Or, if you want to adopt a more holistic view, “what won’t have mattered on your deathbed.”)

这并不意味着你不应该留意并消除浪费。而是说，你不应该将浪费定义为“今天不产生价值的东西”。相反，应该将其定义为“对你的职业生涯无关紧要的东西”。（或者，如果你想采取更全面的观点，可以这样定义：“在你临终时无关紧要的东西”。）

Having fun can be seen as wasteful if we measure “one-year work performance.” And yet, it is necessary for a high-performing career. Have you ever seen a high performer sticking for a whole career to a job he didn’t enjoy?

如果以“一年的工作绩效”来衡量，那么享受乐趣可能会被视为一种浪费。然而，对于一份高绩效的职业来说，享受乐趣却是必不可少的。你见过哪个高绩效人士会坚持一辈子做一份自己不喜欢的工作吗？

Taking care of your long-term performance means being okay with imperfect efficiency.

关注长期业绩意味着要接受效率并非完美。

ACTION:

行动：

What are actions that seem wasteful today but are invaluable for your long-term success?

哪些行为看似浪费时间，但对你的长期成功却至关重要？

Here are some common ideas of “wasteful” activities that are actually great investments: taking breaks, learning, looking for new ideas, trying something that might fail, building personal bonds, and having fun. Should any of these go into your schedule or to-do list?

以下是一些常见的“浪费时间”的活动，但实际上它们都是很好的投资：休息、学习、寻找新想法、尝试可能失败的事情、建立人际关系以及享受乐趣。这些活动应该加入你的日程安排或待办事项清单吗？

#↩
Rule 16
规则16

Do not seek control

不要试图控制

Do not seek control over other people. Not only is it impossible and ethically dubious, but often seeking it produces counterproductive results. For example, imagine asking your best friend to drive you to the nearest mall and then keeping your hands on the steering wheel he is using, in an attempt to control his movements. The results would be disastrous. Often, you’re better off communicating your needs and then letting go of your grip (providing some feedback and clarification here and there, if necessary, but never attempting to seize full control).

不要试图控制他人。这不仅不可能，而且在道德上也站不住脚，更重要的是，这种做法往往会适得其反。例如，想象一下，你请最好的朋友开车送你去最近的商场，然后你却一直把手放在他握着的方向盘上，试图控制他的驾驶。结果会很糟糕。通常情况下，你最好是先表达你的需求，然后放手（如有必要，可以偶尔提供一些反馈和解释，但千万不要试图完全掌控局面）。

The same applies to events. Do not try to control them. Instead, assume there will be unexpected circumstances. Then, position yourself so that the negative ones won’t hit you too hard, and yet you can benefit from the positive ones.

这同样适用于各种事件。不要试图控制它们。相反，要预料到可能会出现意想不到的情况。然后，调整自身位置，使负面事件对你的影响不至于过大，同时又能从正面事件中获益。

It’s not about giving up on your desired outcomes. It’s about realizing you need to give up on your exact vision of how they will be achieved.

这并非意味着放弃你想要的结果，而是意味着你需要放弃你对实现这些结果的具体设想。

People don’t want to be happy and successful. Instead, they want to be happy and successful in a particular way, thus ending up unhappy and unsuccessful.

人们并非渴望幸福和成功，而是渴望以某种特定的方式获得幸福和成功，最终却往往走向不幸福和失败。

…

Few successful people took a direct path to success. Most of them have been wandering for years, knowing that they would become successful but not knowing how. Steve Jobs stumbled on creating Apple. The iPhone itself, Apple’s most successful product, was created after 30 years of the company’s existence. And in a 2010 post on his blog, Uber founder Travis Kalanick dismisses the ride-hailing company as one of his many swings to success.

很少有成功人士走的是一条笔直的成功之路。他们中的大多数人都在摸索多年，虽然知道自己终将成功，却不知如何实现。史蒂夫·乔布斯创立苹果公司纯属偶然。苹果最成功的产品——iPhone，也是在公司成立30年后才问世的。而优步创始人特拉维斯·卡兰尼克在2010年的一篇博客文章中，将这家网约车公司视为他众多成功尝试之一。

Successful people know what they want but not what it will look like.

成功人士知道自己想要什么，但不知道最终会是什么样子。

This allows them both to have the clarity to take the next step and the flexibility to adjust their strategy when facing unexpected setbacks or opportunities.

这使得他们双方都能清晰地了解下一步该怎么做，并且在面临意想不到的挫折或机遇时，能够灵活地调整策略。

Someone inflexible on details might refuse good opportunities just because they do not look like the success they imagined. Instead, successful people check newfound opportunities against the principles underlying their vision. Then, if these new opportunities fit their principles, they embrace them.

那些在细节上固执己见的人，可能会因为机会看起来不符合他们想象中的成功模式而拒绝接受。相反，成功人士会用自己愿景背后的原则来检验新的机会。如果这些新机会符合他们的原则，他们就会欣然接受。

In fact, almost all successful people aren’t successful in the way they imagined they would be.

事实上，几乎所有成功人士的成功方式都与他们最初的设想不符。

…

The same applies to happy people. Happy people have values. They do not compromise on them and use them to guide their actions. But they do not have a precise idea of happiness. So, they accept and enjoy events that appear in their lives without rejecting them or being disappointed just because these events do not look exactly like the future they imagined.

这同样适用于快乐的人。快乐的人有自己的价值观，他们不会在价值观上妥协，并以此指导自己的行为。但他们对幸福并没有一个精确的定义。因此，他们接受并享受生活中发生的一切，不会因为这些事情与他们想象中的未来不完全一致而拒绝或失望。

ACTION:

行动：

Try to imagine what it would mean to you to be successful.

试着想象一下，成功对你来说意味着什么。

Avoid details. Instead, distill the values of yours that would feel realized.

避免纠缠于细节。相反，要提炼出那些你认为能够实现的价值观。

Then, base your choices upon them.

然后，根据这些结果做出你的选择。

Take actions both to materialize your vision and to materialize your values (what’s important for you). But if you have to choose between the two, choose the latter. The former will adapt.

采取行动，既要实现你的愿景，也要实现你的价值观（对你而言重要的东西）。但如果必须在两者之间做出选择，那就选择后者。前者会自行调整。

For example, “I want to have written a bestseller sci-fi book” might become “I want to be read by millions of people.” The latter is better because it does not fixate you on a specific genre or a specific medium.

例如，“我想写一本畅销科幻小说”可以改成“我想让数百万人读到我的作品”。后者更好，因为它不会将你局限于特定的类型或媒介。

As another example, “I want to marry a partner with [checklist of traits]” becomes “I want to have a fulfilling relationship with a partner that makes me happy.” This prevents you from missing some great people who might cross your life just because they lack one item on a long checklist of “needs” you think you know.

再举个例子，“我想找一个具备[一系列特质]的伴侣”可以改成“我想和一位能让我快乐的伴侣建立一段充实的感情”。这样就能避免你因为对方缺少你自以为了解的那一长串“需求”清单上的某一项而错过生命中可能出现的优秀人才。

#↩
Rule 17
规则17

Seek momentum, not perfection

追求势头，而非完美。

Everyone knows that it is impossible to be a beginner and not make mistakes.

大家都知道，新手不可能不犯错。

However, some forget this simple truth when thinking about their own situation. They set standards that are too high. Even if they manage to reach them, the experience is so stressful that they lose motivation and the pleasure of having achieved their desired result. This is counterproductive.

然而，有些人思考自身处境时却忘记了这个简单的道理。他们设定的标准过高。即便最终达成目标，过程也压力巨大，以至于他们失去了动力和成就感。这反而会适得其反。

Others expect perfection. Whatever they do, they manage to find something bad and punish themselves for it. As a result, they associate negative emotions with their practice. Eventually, they burn out or quit.

有些人追求完美。无论做什么，他们总能找到不足之处，并为此惩罚自己。结果，他们将负面情绪与练习联系起来。最终，他们精疲力竭或放弃练习。

Conversely, passionate people are ambitious in their growth rate but not in their absolute results. This ensures that they derive a constant flow of motivation from their practice. In each session, they spot improvement, and that feels good. The positive emotional association brings motivation and focus.

相反，充满热情的人追求的是进步的速度，而非最终的成果。这确保了他们能从练习中获得源源不断的动力。每次练习，他们都能发现自己的进步，这种感觉很棒。积极的情绪联想能带来动力和专注力。

Do not worry about perfection and effectiveness before having built motivation and momentum. Until then, only focus on starting, consistency, and making it a rewarding experience.

在建立起动力和势头之前，不要过分追求完美和效果。在此之前，只需专注于开始、坚持，并让它成为一段有益的经历。

Finally, perfection requires iteration – trial and error. Too often, amateurs think that achieving perfection is about refining one’s technique. Instead, it might be more about refining one’s taste. If you are an artist, do you really know what people want? More in general, do you really know what you want? The only way to know is to get started and see.

最后，完美需要反复迭代——不断试错。很多业余爱好者认为，达到完美就是精进技艺。但实际上，完美或许更多地体现在提升个人品味上。如果你是一位艺术家，你真的了解人们想要什么吗？更广泛地说，你真的知道自己想要什么吗？唯一的答案就是付诸实践，亲身感受。

ACTION:

行动：

Is there any goal of yours with which you feel stuck? Plan an action – no matter how small – that will get you started towards it.

你是否有什么目标感觉难以实现？制定一个行动计划——无论多么微小——来帮助你朝着目标迈进。

Don’t fall into the trap of thinking, “this is not enough,” and don’t make elaborate plans. Instead, aim for “doable.”

不要陷入“这还不够”的想法，也不要制定过于复杂的计划。相反，要以“可行”为目标。

#↩
Rule 18
第18条规则

Everything can be a step forward

一切皆可成为前进的一步。

I used to get anxious about my mistakes. For example, if I said something wrong while pitching a project to a client, I would spend the following night restless, feeling like an idiot and thinking about the squandered opportunity.

我以前总是很担心自己犯错。例如，如果我在向客户推销项目时说错了什么，我就会辗转反侧，第二天晚上睡不着觉，觉得自己像个傻瓜，后悔错失了良机。

I finally realized that any mistake that doesn’t kill me is a step forward – as long as I learned a lesson from it. This is because life is closer to a game of Mastermind or Battleship than one of chess – your job is to get closer to a winning combination, and mistakes are ways to gain information. In fact, it’s impossible to win without making mistakes – mistakes are the path to victory. 4

我终于意识到，任何没要了我命的错误都是进步——只要我能从中吸取教训。这是因为人生更像是“猜谜游戏”或“战舰游戏”，而不是国际象棋——你的任务是尽可能接近制胜组合，而错误正是获取信息的途径。事实上，不犯错就无法取胜——错误是通往胜利的道路。

ACTION:

行动：

Think about the last mistake that caused you anxiety. Can you learn anything from it? If so, did you become a stronger or more skillful person as a result?

想想上一次让你感到焦虑的错误。你能从中吸取什么教训吗？如果能，你是否因此变得更坚强或更有能力？

If you did learn something and are now a more effective person as a result, do you still think making the mistake was bad for your future and something you needed to worry about?

如果你从中吸取了教训，并因此变得更加高效，你是否仍然认为犯下的错误对你的未来有害，是你需要担心的事情？

#↩

Know what you want and what its costs are,
then pay them

知道你想要什么以及它的成本是多少，然后支付它们。

Rules 19 to 22

规则 19 至 22

My personal mantra is:

我的人生格言是：

“May I have the honesty to acknowledge what is important for me, the wisdom to know its costs, and the discipline to pay them.”

“愿我拥有诚实去认清对我而言重要的事物，拥有智慧去了解其代价，并拥有自律去承担这些代价。”

The inspiration came from comic artist Scott Adams (the creator of Dilbert), who wrote something similar. The first time I read it, I dismissed it as useless advice.

灵感来源于漫画家斯科特·亚当斯（《呆伯特》的作者），他写过类似的文章。我第一次读到时，觉得那只是些没用的建议，便不予理会。

A few years later, I tried implementing it. It literally changed my life. By itself, it allowed me to reach many of my goals. I now believe that it was the most impactful piece of advice I ever received. It is crazy how something so simple can be so effective.

几年后，我尝试实践了这个方法。它真的改变了我的生活。它本身就帮助我实现了许多目标。我现在相信，这是我收到的最有影响力的建议。难以置信，如此简单的方法竟然如此有效。

Over the following rules, I will clarify its relevance for you and provide a step-by-step guide for implementing it in your life.

我将通过以下规则阐明其对您的意义，并提供逐步指导，帮助您在生活中实施这些规则。

#↩
Rule 19
规则19

acknowledge what is important for you

明白什么对你来说最重要。

We, humans, are highly effective creatures. We explored the depths of the ocean and landed on the moon. We are the pinnacle of millions of years of evolution. Whatever we set our minds to, we achieve.

我们人类是高效的生物。我们探索过海洋深处，也登上过月球。我们是数百万年进化的巅峰。只要我们下定决心，就能实现任何目标。

We are so powerful yet sometimes feel so uncomfortable with ourselves. One of our most painful feelings is regret. It originates from not having understood, in the past, how something would have been important to us in the present (and thus not having done what needed to be done to obtain it). 5

我们如此强大，却有时对自己感到如此不自在。后悔是我们最痛苦的感受之一。它源于过去没有理解某件事在当下对我们的重要性（因此也没有去做那些需要做的事情去获得它）。

To avoid regret in the future, you need to understand now what it is that will be important to you. Unfortunately, most people are terrible at knowing what their future selves will value in 10 years.

为了避免将来后悔，你现在就需要明白什么对你来说才是最重要的。可惜的是，大多数人很难预知十年后自己会珍视什么。

The key is honesty. With yourself. Listening to your desires without judging them. Understanding that if you do not meet the expectations others have for you, it is their problem, not yours. And doing the same with your ego.

关键在于诚实。对自己诚实。倾听内心的渴望，而不加评判。明白如果你达不到别人的期望，那是他们的问题，不是你的。对待自己的自尊心也一样。

How to become more honest with yourself? Think about all the times you haven’t been, and ask yourself: “did it make life any better?” If you do this exercise intensely enough, your mindset will shift. Acknowledging the consequences of your mistakes is the path toward not making them again.

如何才能对自己更诚实？想想你所有不诚实的时候，然后问问自己：“那样做让生活变得更好了吗？”如果你认真练习，你的思维方式就会转变。承认错误带来的后果，才是避免重蹈覆辙的关键。

It is paramount to have the honesty to acknowledge your desires and needs. If you are not clear on what you want, you will not obtain it, barring benefiting from extreme luck.

诚实地承认自己的欲望和需求至关重要。如果你不清楚自己想要什么，除非运气极好，否则你将无法得到它。

ACTION:

行动：

Make a list of the things you desire for your life. Use a 10-year horizon.

列出你人生中想要的一切。时间跨度设定在十年之内。

Let your current self speak freely. Do not be afraid of betraying your past self.

让现在的你自由表达。不要害怕背叛过去的你。

Then, add the things that you imagine an average 80-years old (not your 80-years-old self) would tell you they enjoyed in their life. This ensures that you consider your current wishes and those of your future self – because you aren’t your future self yet, you might not know him or her as well as you think. 6

然后，添加一些你想象中一位普通的80岁老人（不是你80岁时的自己）会告诉你他们一生中喜欢的事情。这可以确保你既考虑到你现在的愿望，也考虑到未来自己的愿望——因为你现在还不是未来的自己，你可能并不像你想象的那样了解未来的自己。

The final version of this list will be used for the action item of the following rule.

此列表的最终版本将用于以下规则的操作项。

#↩
Rule 20
规则20

Know the costs of what you want

了解你想要的东西的成本

The second step in obtaining what you want is to write down its costs. This prevents you from committing a common mistake: spending energy and time doing things that do not bring you any closer to your objectives. For example, many employees work very hard yet do not get any promotion simply because they work on the wrong things.

实现目标的第二步是列出成本。这可以避免你犯一个常见的错误：把精力和时间浪费在对实现目标毫无帮助的事情上。例如，很多员工非常努力工作，却得不到晋升，仅仅是因为他们把精力放在了错误的事情上。

Each goal of yours can be described as a set of costs that must be paid. Such costs are seldom financial. Most often, they are actions: work done, practice sessions completed, conversations had, and so on. If you pay the costs, you will achieve the goal. If you do not, the goal will be missed. It’s as simple as that.

你的每个目标都可以被描述为一系列必须付出的代价。这些代价很少是金钱上的，通常指的是行动：完成的工作、完成的练习、进行的对话等等。如果你付出了这些代价，你就能实现目标；如果你不付出，目标就无法实现。就这么简单。

Success follows having paid all the right costs.

成功源于付出了所有正确的代价。

In the sentence above, the emphasis falls on two words. The first is “follows.” Success follows having paid its costs. You cannot wait to become successful before beginning to pay its costs. It simply doesn’t work that way. Any success achieved without paying its costs will be short-lived, and the inevitable reconciliation with reality will be painful – no exceptions.

上面的句子重点在于两个词。第一个是“付出代价”。成功源于付出代价。你不能等到成功之后才开始付出代价。事情并非如此。任何不付出代价就获得的成功都只是昙花一现，最终必然会痛苦地回归现实——没有例外。

The second word deserving emphasis is “right.” Success follows having paid the costs, but not just any costs, the right costs. Effort doesn’t matter. You do not get any medal for participation. This is not elementary school anymore. Either you paid the right costs, or you didn’t pay anything. You do not get to choose the costs you would like to pay. Remember the first rule of this book, you can choose the game to play, but you cannot choose its rules. The game determines the costs you must pay to achieve a given type of success.

第二个需要强调的词是“正确”。成功源于付出代价，但并非任何代价，而是正确的代价。努力本身并不重要。参与并不会给你任何奖牌。这已经不是小学了。要么你付出了正确的代价，要么你什么都没付出。你无法选择自己想付出的代价。记住本书的第一条规则：你可以选择玩什么游戏，但你无法选择游戏规则。游戏决定了你为了取得某种成功必须付出的代价。

You can choose whether you think the costs are worth the success and thus whether to pay them, but you cannot choose what the costs are.

你可以选择是否认为付出这些代价值得获得成功，从而决定是否支付这些代价，但你无法选择代价是什么。

Listing the costs you must pay to achieve your goal has three advantages.

列出为实现目标必须付出的成本有三个优点。

First, it brings clarity . You will know precisely what must be done. You can avoid unnecessary or wasteful actions and the frustration that comes with them.

首先，它能带来清晰的思路。你会确切地知道该做什么。你可以避免不必要的或浪费的行动，以及由此带来的挫败感。

Second, it brings motivation . Having a to-do list in front of you that, if completed, will bring you the results you want will instill a newfound purpose.

其次，它能激发动力。当你面前摆着一份待办事项清单，并且完成清单上的事项就能获得你想要的结果时，你会找到新的目标。

Third, if you discover that it would take much more work to reach your goals than what you’re willing to put in, you can say “no thanks” and put your mind at ease, with no regrets.

第三，如果你发现实现目标所需的努力远远超过你愿意投入的，你可以说“不，谢谢”，然后安心放弃，不会后悔。

To know the costs that must be paid to succeed at a given goal, you need experience. You can earn some experience by trying, failing, and adjusting your list of costs to be paid. Or you can borrow experience from someone else by looking at the costs paid by those who achieved the goals you chose. If you choose the latter, make sure that you only observe people who have been successful multiple times and for a long time: it’s too easy to take a shortcut and appear successful for a short time before crashing.

要了解实现特定目标所需付出的代价，你需要经验。你可以通过尝试、失败并调整所需付出的代价清单来积累经验。或者，你也可以借鉴他人的经验，看看那些实现你所选择目标的人付出了哪些代价。如果你选择后者，务必确保你只观察那些多次成功且长期保持成功的人：走捷径很容易，你可能短暂地取得成功，但很快就会失败。

Lastly, do not cherry-pick. These people had to give up many other things to achieve their goals. You cannot choose a single side of the tradeoffs they made, only the tradeoff as a whole. 7

最后，不要断章取义。这些人为了实现目标，不得不放弃很多其他东西。你不能只选择他们做出的权衡取舍中的某一方面，而只能考虑整体的权衡取舍。

ACTION:

行动：

Choose one of the items in your list from the previous rule. It should represent something you want to achieve in the next 1-5 years.

从你列出的上一条规则中选择一项。它应该代表你希望在未来1-5年内实现的目标。

Write out all the costs you will have to pay for your goal to become your reality. Make sure to include:

列出为实现目标所需付出的所有代价。务必包括：

– The skills you will have to acquire.

你需要掌握的技能。

– The work sessions you will have to participate in.

– 您需要参加的工作会议。

– The relationships you will have to cultivate.

——你需要培养的人际关系。

– The conversations you will have to have.

——你将要进行的对话。

– The things you will have to give up.

——你必须放弃的东西。

In particular, focus on listing the actions that will have to happen on a daily or weekly basis, rather than “one-offs.” For example, “learning to write marketing copy” becomes “read one book on marketing a month and write one page every Tuesday evening for six months.”

尤其要着重列出每天或每周必须完成的行动，而不是“一次性”行动。例如，“学习撰写营销文案”可以改为“每月阅读一本营销书籍，并在接下来的六个月里，每周二晚上撰写一页文案”。

After you write the list of costs, ask yourself: if you complete all of the items, will your goal certainly be realized? If not, what is missing?

列出所有费用清单后，问问自己：如果所有项目都完成，你的目标就一定能实现吗？如果不能，还缺少什么？

Let’s say that your goal is to become a published author. The list of costs to pay could include:

假设你的目标是成为一名出版作家。你需要支付的费用可能包括：

– Sitting down daily to write for three years.

——每天坚持写作，持续三年。

– At the end of each writing session, send everything you wrote to an audience via a blog post, an email to a friend, etc.

– 每次写作结束后，将你写的所有内容通过博客文章、电子邮件等方式发送给朋友等读者。

– Progressively move from writing short pieces to longer ones.

逐步从写短篇作品过渡到写长篇作品。

– Then, write a book.

然后，写一本书。

– Rewrite each chapter at least a couple of times. Then, give it to at least five people for feedback.

——每个章节至少要修改两遍。然后，至少给五个人征求反馈意见。

– Edit the book based on the feedback received.

根据收到的反馈意见修改书籍。

– Send the book to at least 20 publishers.

– 将书稿寄给至少 20 家出版社。

If these costs are paid, the chances are that your book will actually be published, possibly even becoming a success.

如果这些费用得到支付，你的书很有可能会被出版，甚至可能获得成功。

Do the exercise now. Pick one goal you want to achieve and list its costs. The list will be used for the action point of the following rule.

现在就开始练习。选择一个你想达成的目标，并列出它所需的成本。这份清单将用于以下规则的行动要点。

#↩
Bonus Rule
奖励规则

look at what accomplished people do not do ‬ ‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬ ‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬‬ ‬‬‬‬

看看成功人士不做什么

After having published the first edition of this book, I noticed that most readers, when thinking about the costs that they will have to pay to achieve their goals, only considered additional things they needed to do.

本书第一版出版后，我注意到大多数读者在考虑为实现目标需要付出的代价时，只考虑了他们需要做的额外事情。

However, there are also the costs that come in the form of things they will have to avoid doing. For example, you might decide that your goal is to become a great athlete. If so, you might have to give up eating pizza every weekend. Or, if you want to become a great entrepreneur, you will have to avoid caring about what your detractors say.

然而，这也会带来一些代价，比如你必须放弃一些事情。例如，你可能立志成为一名优秀的运动员。如果是这样，你可能就得放弃每个周末吃披萨的习惯。或者，如果你想成为一名成功的企业家，你就必须对批评者的言论置之不理。

Either way, acknowledge that you cannot achieve your goals only by adding things to your plate. You will also have to remove things.

无论如何，你要明白，光靠增加任务是无法实现目标的。你也必须有所取舍。

This is often hard to accept. But not doing it is perhaps the largest source of frustration and failure. Until we accept that sacrifices come in two flavors –doing what we were not yet doing AND giving up part of what we were already doing – we will be stuck in stagnation.

这往往难以接受。但或许，不去这样做才是挫败感和失败感的最大根源。除非我们接受牺牲有两种形式——去做我们之前没做过的事，以及放弃我们已经在做的一部分事——否则我们将永远停滞不前。

ACTION:

行动：

Is there anything you’re currently doing on a daily, weekly, or monthly basis that you will have to give up to achieve your goals? Is it worth giving this activity up to achieve your goals? Both a “yes!” and a “no!” are valid answers. But make sure you don’t postpone the decision and proceed to the next page with an “I’ll think about it later” attitude.

你目前每天、每周或每月都在做的事情，为了实现目标，你必须放弃哪些？为了实现目标，放弃这些事情值得吗？“值得！”和“不值得！”都是合理的答案。但请务必不要拖延决定，抱着“以后再考虑”的态度翻到下一页。

#↩
Rule 21
规则21

Once you decide what you want,
一旦你决定了想要什么，
work on paying its costs
就着手支付它的费用吧。

If you have been practicing the two previous rules, by now, you should have clarified what you want from your life and the costs you will need to pay for it to become a reality.

如果你一直践行前两条规则，那么现在你应该已经明确了你想要的生活以及实现目标需要付出的代价。

You can use this newfound clarity to work on paying the costs.

你可以利用这种新获得的清晰思路来解决支付费用的问题。

The rest of this chapter will contain advice on how to do that and how to address the common obstacles that might get in your way as you move towards achieving your goal.

本章剩余部分将提供一些建议，说明如何做到这一点，以及如何解决在实现目标过程中可能遇到的常见障碍。

Most of the costs of the goals you want to achieve can and must be broken down into weekly costs, daily actions, practice sessions, work sprints, and so on. Breaking the costs into small pieces that you can handle with regularity will ensure that you will eventually achieve what you desire.

实现目标的大部分成本都可以而且必须分解成每周的成本、每日行动、练习、工作冲刺等等。将成本分解成你可以定期执行的小部分，就能确保你最终实现目标。

Allow me to repeat the simplest yet most impactful advice I ever received:

请允许我重复一遍我曾收到过的最简单却也最有影响力的建议：

– Acknowledge what is important to you , honestly.

诚实地认清对你来说真正重要的东西。

– Research and list all the costs you must pay to achieve what is important to you.

– 研究并列出你为实现对你而言重要的目标必须付出的所有代价。

– With focus and discipline, work on paying such costs.

只要集中精力、自律，就能支付这些费用。

ACTION:

行动：

Immediately schedule on your calendar some “working sessions” in which you will pay at least some of the costs you listed in the previous rule’s action point.

立即在您的日历上安排一些“工作会议”，在这些会议中，您至少要支付您在上一条规则的行动要点中列出的一些费用。

Then, take your phone and add a reminder to review your performance in one week’s time. During your review, ask yourself, “did I pay the costs I said I would pay this week?” If not, what adjustments need to be made to your schedule and environment? Finally, set a new reminder for your review in a week.

然后，拿起手机，设置一个提醒，在一周后回顾你的工作表现。回顾时，问问自己：“我这周是否支付了我承诺的费用？”如果没有，你的日程安排和工作环境需要做出哪些调整？最后，再设置一个提醒，提醒你一周后进行回顾。

Do not underestimate the importance of this weekly reminder. It is what will ensure that, eventually, you will take effective action. It is the difference between a broken new year’s resolution and an actual habit.

千万不要低估每周提醒的重要性。它能确保你最终采取有效行动。它决定了你的新年决心是会破灭还是会养成真正的习惯。

#↩
Rule 22
规则22

Distinguish between the necessary
and the sufficient

区分必要条件和充分条件

My first book sold just 14 copies during the first few months after publication. I was puzzled: I wrote a great book 8 , yet it wasn’t selling. The answer, I would learn later, is that writing a great book is necessary but not sufficient for its success. There were many other things I should have done, for example, building an audience.

我的第一本书出版后的头几个月只卖出了14本。我百思不得其解：我写了一本很棒的书，却卖不出去。后来我才明白，写出一本好书固然必要，但并非成功的充分条件。我本应该做很多其他的事情，比如，建立读者群。

I learned that we often fail because we did something necessary but not sufficient to achieve our goal.

我了解到，我们常常失败是因为我们做了必要的事情，但这些事情还不足以实现我们的目标。

Thankfully, the lack of sales didn’t teach me the wrong lesson, such as that I was a bad writer or that writing books is useless. If I had learned those lessons, my other books, including this one, would never have seen the light of day.

幸好，销量不佳并没有让我吸取错误的教训，比如认为自己文笔不好或者写书毫无用处。如果我吸取了这些教训，我的其他作品，包括这本，恐怕永远都不会面世。

Hence the importance of asking yourself: is this activity sufficient to achieve my goal? If not, what’s missing?

因此，你需要问问自己：这项活动足以实现我的目标吗？如果不够，还缺少什么？

A common mistake is to imitate everything our idols do without differentiating between sufficient to success, necessary to success, and byproducts of success. As a result, we end up wasting our time doing just some of the necessary.

一个常见的错误是，我们盲目模仿偶像的一切行为，却不区分成功所需的条件、成功所必需的条件以及成功的副产品。结果，我们最终浪费时间只做了部分必要的事情。

If an action is sufficient to succeed at your goal, it should be your sole focus. If it is necessary but not sufficient, it should be one objective of many. And if it is a byproduct of success, it should be on your not -to-do list.

如果某项行动足以帮助你达成目标，那么它就应该是你唯一关注的重点。如果它是必要条件但并非充分条件，那么它应该只是众多目标之一。如果它是成功的副产品，那么它就应该被列入你的“不做清单”。

ACTION:

行动：

Pick a goal of yours, and list the actions that, if completed, will achieve that goal.

选择一个你的目标，并列出如果完成这些行动就能实现该目标的行动方案。

Then, ask yourself: if you lived in ten parallel worlds identical to this one, and in all ten worlds you completed the actions on the list, would you achieve that goal all ten times? Or is there any other bottleneck or external circumstance you need to address?

然后，问问自己：如果你生活在十个与这个世界完全相同的平行世界中，并且在所有十个世界里你都完成了清单上的所有行动，你能十次都实现这个目标吗？或者是否存在其他瓶颈或外部环境需要你解决？

For example, let’s say that you aspire to become a great painter. Your to-do list consists of attending an art academy, learning painting techniques, and painting a lot. Do you end up successful like Picasso in all ten parallel worlds in which you complete the to-do list? Or do you, in some, end up forgotten like Van Gogh, who only sold two paintings in his lifetime?

例如，假设你渴望成为一名伟大的画家。你的待办事项清单包括：进入艺术学院学习、学习绘画技巧以及大量练习绘画。在你完成待办事项清单的十个平行世界中，你最终会像毕加索一样获得成功吗？或者，在某些世界里，你会像梵高一样被人遗忘，一生只卖出了两幅画？

You only have one life. So, it’s worth spending a few minutes thinking about whether you’re doing everything you need to do to make your dream come true.

人生只有一次。所以，花几分钟时间思考一下，你是否已经竭尽全力去实现你的梦想，是值得的。

#↩

Start

开始

Rules 23 to 25

规则 23 至 25

As a young adult, I admired people like Warren Buffett, who consistently made good decisions. Later in life, I realized that people with great decision-making skills are much more common than I thought. What’s uncommon, is the capacity to act on them.

年轻的时候，我非常欣赏像沃伦·巴菲特那样总能做出正确决策的人。后来我才意识到，拥有出色决策能力的人其实比我想象的要多得多。真正稀缺的是能够将这些决策付诸行动的能力。

The distinction is essential. If you believe that you have a decision-making problem, your solution is to accumulate more knowledge and learn to make better decisions. But if your problem is taking action, then improving your decision-making skills won’t do a thing. Even worse, it will provide you with an excuse for not taking action.

这种区别至关重要。如果你认为自己存在决策问题，那么解决方案是积累更多知识，学习如何做出更好的决策。但如果你的问题在于行动力不足，那么提升决策能力毫无作用。更糟糕的是，它还会成为你不采取行动的借口。

As with everything in life, it is critical to correctly identify the bottleneck and act on that instead of anything else.

就像生活中所有事情一样，关键在于正确识别瓶颈并针对瓶颈采取行动，而不是采取其他任何行动。

…

Sometimes, you will find yourself with a problem on your hands. Often, it’s a good idea to pause and consider the best course of action. However, if action is not taken soon, you will discover you actually have two problems – the original problem and another one preventing you from taking action. You must address the latter first.

有时，你会遇到棘手的问题。通常，停下来思考最佳应对方案是明智之举。然而，如果不尽快采取行动，你会发现实际上存在两个问题——最初的问题以及阻碍你采取行动的另一个问题。你必须首先解决后者。

In this chapter, I won’t make the banal point that action is important. Instead, I will explain how to solve some of the most common problems preventing action.

在本章中，我不会老生常谈地强调行动的重要性。相反，我将解释如何解决一些阻碍行动的常见问题。

Rule 23
规则23

Action is the trick to break vicious circles

行动是打破恶性循环的关键。

Sometimes, people are stuck in vicious circles. The graduate who needs work experience to find a job, but also needs a job to get work experience. The freelancer who just started her own business and needs clients to build a portfolio but also needs a portfolio to get clients. The middle-aged person who wants to practice yoga to get more flexible, but thinks they are not flexible enough to do yoga.

有时，人们会陷入恶性循环。比如，毕业生需要工作经验才能找到工作，但同时也需要工作来积累工作经验；自由职业者刚开始创业，需要客户来建立作品集，但同时也需要作品集来获得客户；中年人想练习瑜伽来提高柔韧性，但又觉得自己柔韧性不够，无法练习瑜伽。

We often find ourselves stuck in vicious circles. Some are authentic (like the freelancer in the example above), and some are made up in our minds (being flexible is not a requirement for yoga; yoga is how you get flexible).

我们常常发现自己陷入了恶性循环。有些是真实的（比如上面例子中的自由职业者），有些则是我们自己臆想出来的（柔韧性并不是练习瑜伽的必要条件；瑜伽只是让你变得柔韧的一种方式）。

The bad thing about vicious circles is that, because they are made of obstacles that reinforce each other, they seem impossible to overcome. There’s no clear attack point where to focus our efforts.

恶性循环的弊端在于，由于它是由相互强化的障碍构成的，因此似乎无法克服。我们找不到明确的切入点来集中精力。

The good thing about vicious circles is that, because there is no clear attack point, any attack point is as good as it gets. Stop thinking and start acting.

恶性循环的好处在于，由于没有明确的攻击点，任何攻击点都是最好的选择。别再犹豫，立即行动。

And the great thing about vicious circles is that, whereas obstacles compound and reinforce each other, actions also compound and reinforce each other.

恶性循环的妙处在于，障碍会相互叠加、相互强化，而行动也会相互叠加、相互强化。

For example, if you start yoga with an inflexible body, few exercises will be available to you. However, after the first few classes, your flexibility will have improved enough to give you access to more poses (or will allow you to better perform the poses you have already learned). This, in turn, will make you more flexible, thereby creating a virtuous circle.

例如，如果你一开始练习瑜伽时身体柔韧性较差，那么你能做的体式就非常有限。但是，经过最初几节课后，你的柔韧性就会有所提高，足以让你尝试更多体式（或者让你更好地完成已经学过的体式）。反过来，这又会让你变得更加灵活，从而形成一个良性循环。

The moment you take action, vicious circles transform into virtuous ones.

当你采取行动的那一刻，恶性循环就会转变为良性循环。

Similarly, if you are a freelancer without a portfolio, building the first portfolio item will hopefully allow you to land your first client. This first client will allow you to add a second item to your portfolio, helping you find another client, and so on. By taking action, you progressively replace a vicious circle with a virtuous one.

同样，如果你是一名没有作品集的自由职业者，那么建立第一个作品集项目有望帮助你获得第一个客户。有了这个客户，你就可以添加第二个作品集项目，从而找到下一个客户，以此类推。通过行动，你就能逐步打破恶性循环，建立良性循环。

Stop thinking about how to better get unstuck, and just be in action. Taking action is how people get unstuck.

别再想着如何更好地摆脱困境，行动起来吧。行动才是摆脱困境的真正途径。

ACTION:

行动：

What is one vicious circle in which you are seemingly stuck?

你似乎陷入了哪种恶性循环？

List the 2-3 factors that are blocking you. For example, if you are a freelancer who just started your own business, it could be not having clients and not having a portfolio.

列出阻碍你前进的2-3个因素。例如，如果你是一名刚刚开始创业的自由职业者，那么阻碍因素可能是没有客户和没有作品集。

Then, assume that one of those factors was gone. What action would you take? (See the example below.)

假设其中一个因素消失了，你会采取什么行动？（参见以下示例。）

Add it to your to-do list. Have faith that if you do it, you will have transformed, if only a little bit, the vicious circle into a virtuous one.

把它添加到你的待办事项清单中。要相信，如果你做了这件事，即使只是略微改变一下恶性循环，你也能将其转变为良性循环。

For example: Mark is a freelancer without a portfolio and without a client (he just started). If he had a portfolio, he would begin to contact clients and tell them what he could do for them. Therefore, the solution is to go out there and start contacting clients anyway. That’s how he can break the vicious circle.

例如：马克是一名自由职业者，他没有作品集，也没有客户（他刚入行）。如果他有作品集，他就会开始联系客户，告诉他们自己能做什么。因此，解决办法就是无论如何都要主动联系客户。这样他才能打破恶性循环。

#↩
Rule 24
规则24

If you cannot take a big step,
take a smaller one

如果你不能迈出一大步，那就迈出一小步。

Sometimes, I struggle to do something I set myself to do. Often, this is because it’s a big step, one I’m not emotionally ready for. Training for a marathon? No way. Removing my daily croissant from my diet? Absolutely not.

有时候，我很难完成自己设定的目标。通常，这是因为目标太大，我还没做好心理准备。比如，备战马拉松？不可能。戒掉每天的牛角面包？绝对不行。

Often, we do not have a problem with the action itself, just with the dose. For example, I might not trust that I could run a marathon or that training for a marathon is worth the time and effort, but I could be comfortable with running a few kilometers. Or, while I might not be willing to let go of my dear croissants forever, I might be ready to reduce my croissant consumption to one every other day.

通常，我们并非对行为本身有意见，而是对剂量有意见。例如，我可能不相信自己能跑完马拉松，或者认为马拉松训练值得花费时间和精力，但我可以接受跑几公里。又或者，虽然我可能不愿意永远放弃我心爱的牛角面包，但我或许可以接受将牛角面包的食用量减少到隔天一个。

There is always a step small enough that our brain is willing to take. Getting unstuck is about finding that small step, taking it, and gaining momentum.

总会有一个足够小的步骤，我们的大脑愿意迈出。摆脱困境的关键在于找到这个小步骤，迈出它，并积累动力。

ACTION:

行动：

Pick a goal of yours – running three times a week, perhaps.

给自己设定一个目标——比如每周跑步三次。

Then, schedule in your calendar what you will do in the next week to accomplish it – for example, running 2km on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday.

然后，在你的日历上安排好接下来一周要做什么来完成这个目标——例如，在星期一、星期三和星期五跑 2 公里。

Finally, schedule a reminder for Sunday to review whether you took action. If you did act, great! You can schedule the same for next week or even raise the bar. For example, increase the distance to be run.

最后，设置一个提醒，在周日回顾一下你是否采取了行动。如果你采取了行动，那就太棒了！你可以为下周也设置同样的提醒，甚至可以提高目标。例如，增加跑步的距离。

Instead, if you couldn’t complete the action, no matter the reason, lower your bar. For example, go from running three times a week for 2km to running twice a week for 2km. Find a step small enough so that you maximize the chances of executing it. If you are still stuck, choose a smaller step. Even if it seems insignificant, like running 500 meters once a week. Once you gain momentum by taking that small step, you will be able to increase your habit to something more significant. Keep this virtuous circle going and soon, you will hit your original, desired goal. Without the momentum of a virtuous circle, thinking about effectiveness will get you nowhere.

相反，如果你因为任何原因无法完成目标，那就降低目标。例如，从每周跑三次，每次2公里，改为每周跑两次，每次2公里。找到一个足够小的步子，这样你完成它的几率就会最大程度地提高。如果你仍然卡住，那就选择更小的步子。即使它看起来微不足道，比如每周跑一次500米。一旦你通过迈出这小步获得了动力，你就能将这个习惯发展成更重要的事情。保持这种良性循环，很快你就能实现最初想要的目标。如果没有良性循环的动力，光想着效率是行不通的。

Momentum before impact; momentum to build impact.

冲击前的动量；积蓄冲击力的动量。

#↩
Rule 25
规则25

Stress comes from unaddressed problems

压力源于未解决的问题。

– Amazon’s founder Jeff Bezos

——亚马逊创始人杰夫·贝佐斯

Not all problems cause us stress, only the unaddressed ones.

并非所有问题都会给我们带来压力，只有那些未解决的问题才会。

They might be unaddressed because they cannot be addressed, or because we do not know how to address them, or because we chose not to address them.

这些问题可能因为无法解决、我们不知道如何解决，或者我们选择不解决而得不到解决。

If a problem is unaddressed, whatever the reason, it causes us stress.

如果问题得不到解决，无论原因是什么，都会给我们带来压力。

…

Here’s another thing I noticed about stress:

关于压力，我还注意到另一点：

You do not have to solve a problem to prevent it from causing stress. Just having a roadmap that you are confident can address the problem is enough.

你不必解决问题才能避免压力。只要制定一个你确信能够解决问题的方案就足够了。

That said, having a roadmap that you unconsciously know you will not follow is not enough . That problem will still be stressful, and rightfully so: your brain knows that the roadmap is just a pretense.

也就是说，即使你潜意识里知道自己不会遵循一份计划，这仍然不够。这个问题依然会让你感到压力，而且这种压力是理所当然的：你的大脑知道这份计划不过是个幌子。

It is your responsibility to devise a roadmap you are unconsciously willing to follow because you are confident it will be beneficial.

你有责任制定一个让你不由自主地愿意遵循的路线图，因为你确信它会给你带来好处。

If it is about unconsciously willing to follow it, how will you know if you believe in it enough? Simple: stress is a sign that your roadmap is not something you believe in. To eliminate the stress, develop a plan you can authentically embrace.

如果只是下意识地愿意遵循某个计划，你怎么知道自己是否足够相信它呢？很简单：压力表明你并不真正相信你的计划。为了消除压力，制定一个你能真心实意执行的计划。

ACTION:

行动：

Pick one problem that is causing you stress.

选择一个让你感到压力的问题。

Develop a roadmap with a set of tasks that, if completed, will lead to the problem being solved. Attach dates to these tasks.

制定一份包含一系列任务的路线图，这些任务如果完成，就能最终解决问题。为这些任务设定截止日期。

If you still feel stressed at the end of the exercise, it means that you do not believe that the tasks are achievable or that, if completed, they would be enough to solve the problem. In this case, revisit the roadmap until the stress disappears. That will be the sign that you have an effective roadmap.

如果练习结束后你仍然感到压力，这意味着你不相信这些任务能够完成，或者即使完成了，也不足以解决问题。在这种情况下，请重新审视你的计划，直到压力消失。这表明你的计划是有效的。

Then, of course, work on its execution.

当然，接下来还要着手执行。

#↩

Set useful goals

设定有意义的目标

Rules 26 to 29

规则26至29

Rule 26
规则26

Play stupid games,
win stupid prizes

玩愚蠢的游戏，赢愚蠢的奖品

Many unhappy people won the game they decided to play.

许多不快乐的人赢得了他们选择玩的游戏。

The successful entrepreneur who doesn’t have a life, the Olympic medalist whose knees are so damaged he has problems walking, the employee who gets promoted to a job with more responsibilities and fewer freedoms, or the Casanova who spent his 20s and 30s having fun and now can’t find a good spouse because all the agreeable people are already married.

事业有成却无所事事的企业家，膝盖严重受伤以至于行走困难的奥运奖牌获得者，升职后责任更大、自由更少的员工，或者在二三十岁时寻欢作乐，如今却找不到合适伴侣的情圣，因为所有合得来的人都已成家。

Careful not to choose games that hand you a loss even when you win.

要小心，不要选择那种即使赢了也会让你亏损的游戏。

ACTION:

行动：

List all the games you participate in. It could be proper games, societal games (who has the largest car?), professional ones (the corporate ladder), or in general, any competition where there’s a winner.

列出你参与的所有游戏。可以是正规比赛、社交游戏（比如谁的车最大？）、职业比赛（比如职场晋升），或者任何有胜负的竞赛。

Then, visualize what it would take to win (time, energy, or money – all things you could use elsewhere). Is the prize still worth it?

然后，想象一下赢得比赛需要付出什么（时间、精力或金钱——这些都是你可以用在其他地方的东西）。这个奖品还值得吗？

Perhaps the answer is yes. Ultimately, you decide what’s worth doing. But make sure it’s a deliberate decision.

或许答案是肯定的。最终，什么事值得做，由你自己决定。但务必确保这是经过深思熟虑的决定。

#↩
Rule 27
规则27

Choose objectives you can influence

选择你能影响的目标

A basic interpretation of this rule: do not choose goals you cannot influence. Unless you like frustration, that is.

这条规则的基本解释是：不要选择你无法掌控的目标。除非你喜欢挫败感。

A more advanced interpretation of this rule: deconstruct your goals into milestones you can influence and events you cannot influence. Focus on the former and mitigate the impact of the latter. Then, forget about them.

这条规则的进阶解读是：将你的目标分解为你可以掌控的里程碑和你无法掌控的事件。专注于前者，并尽可能降低后者的影响。然后，就把它们抛诸脑后吧。

A third interpretation of this rule: proactively choose goals you can influence. And for your career, choose goals that you can influence and that are easily measurable – so that the value you provide is evident and thus appropriately rewarded. 9

这条规则的第三种解读是：主动选择你能掌控的目标。对于你的职业生涯，选择那些你能掌控且易于衡量的目标——这样你创造的价值才能显而易见，从而获得相应的回报。

ACTION:

行动：

Pick a goal of yours. Is it something you can influence?

选择一个你自己的目标。这个目标你能掌控吗？

Now, deconstruct it into a set of actions and milestones. Which ones can you control? Which ones can you influence? And which ones you cannot control nor influence?

现在，将它分解成一系列行动和里程碑。哪些是你能控制的？哪些是你能影响的？哪些是你既不能控制也不能影响的？

About the latter – can you substitute them with actions and milestones that you can control or at least influence?

关于后者——你能用你能控制或至少能影响的行动和里程碑来代替它们吗？

Rule 28
规则28

Pick ambitious goals

选择远大的目标

“Pick ambitious goals” is a piece of advice I have received from many people. Yet, for the longest time, I resisted taking it. Ambition comes with the possibility of failure and the certainty of stress. Isn’t it better to follow a process-focused approach, where I just focus on the next step?

“设定远大的目标”是很多人都给我的建议。然而，很长一段时间以来，我一直抗拒接受这个建议。因为雄心壮志意味着失败的可能性和必然的压力。难道专注于过程，只关注下一步，不是更好吗？

The two are not exclusive. I’ve come to believe that on a day-to-day basis, it’s indeed better to focus on systems, processes, and iteration. However, in addition to this approach , it’s good to also have some ambitious goals. If not to inspire oneself, at least to inspire others.

两者并非互斥。我逐渐意识到，在日常工作中，专注于系统、流程和迭代的确更为重要。然而，除了这种方法之外，设定一些远大的目标也很有益处。即便不是为了激励自己，至少也能激励他人。

In fact, ambitious goals help with recruiting, selling, financing, and so on. The more ambitious your goals, the more likely others will help you (this is especially true if you’re looking for the help of very successful people).

事实上，远大的目标有助于招聘、销售、融资等等。你的目标越远大，就越有可能得到他人的帮助（如果你想寻求成功人士的帮助，这一点尤其如此）。

ACTION:

行动：

Is there any objective of yours for which you are having trouble getting enough support? If so, consider being more ambitious with the ultimate impact you wish to have.

你是否有某个目标在获取足够支持方面遇到困难？如果是这样，不妨考虑一下你希望最终产生的影响要更加远大一些。

Of course, do not lie or promise the impossible. It’s not, “I think I can achieve X, so I’ll tell others I am aiming for ten times X.” Instead, it’s “With my current plan, I can achieve X. How should I change my plan to achieve 10X?”

当然，不要撒谎或做出不可能的承诺。不要说：“我认为我能达到X，所以我告诉别人我的目标是X的十倍。”相反，应该说：“按照我目前的计划，我可以达到X。我应该如何修改我的计划才能达到10倍？”

#↩
Rule 29
规则29

If it hasn’t been written down,
it hasn’t been planned

如果没有写下来，就说明还没有计划。

Here is another lesson that took me ages to internalize (and, honestly, one which I still forget from time to time): I am not serious about a plan of mine unless I write it down.

这是我花了很长时间才领悟的另一个教训（老实说，我有时还会忘记）：除非我把计划写下来，否则我不会认真对待它。

Writing plans down in ink on paper (or on a screen) has two advantages. First, it makes you notice opportunities. Writing down a plan keeps it fresh in your mind. Just as asking you, “how many yellow cars do you see every day?” would make you notice yellow cars while commuting, writing down a plan will make you notice opportunities you would not have otherwise seen.

把计划用笔写在纸上（或屏幕上）有两个好处。首先，它能让你注意到机会。把计划写下来能让它牢记于心。就像问你“你每天能看到多少辆黄色汽车？”会让你在通勤路上注意到黄色汽车一样，把计划写下来也会让你注意到那些你原本不会注意到的机会。

Second, writing plans down makes it easier to change them. This is counterintuitive. Isn’t a written plan harder to change? No. Usually, people change a plan only after they notice something is wrong with it. If you do not write a plan down, you may remain under the impression it is working even if it isn’t. Instead, writing down your plan makes it easier to notice when things are going off-track. For example, when I started my independent career, I did not write a plan to grow my business – I just did what I thought was to be done. For months, I was under the impression that I was on the right path. It was only after one year that I noticed that what I was doing was not enough and that I should take a different approach. Had I written a plan, I would have known that after the first few weeks.

其次，把计划写下来更容易修改。这听起来似乎有悖常理。难道写下来的计划不是更难修改吗？并非如此。通常情况下，人们只有在发现计划出现问题后才会修改。如果你不把计划写下来，即使它行不通，你可能仍然会误以为它有效。相反，把计划写下来能让你更容易注意到事情何时偏离了轨道。例如，当我开始独立创业时，我没有制定发展业务的计划——我只是做了我认为应该做的事情。几个月来，我一直以为自己走在正确的道路上。直到一年后，我才意识到我所做的还不够，我应该采取不同的方法。如果我当时制定了计划，那么在最初几周后我就会知道这一点。

ACTION:

行动：

Pick a project of yours and write down a plan. It should include a clear description of what success looks like and what actions you will take to ensure it gets realized.

选择一个你正在做的项目，并制定一个计划。计划中应该清晰地描述成功是什么样子，以及你将采取哪些行动来确保成功实现。

Then, write down a detailed list of actions you will take over the next two weeks and their desired outcome .
