然后，详细列出你在接下来的两周内将采取的行动及其预期结果。

Finally, set a reminder in two weeks to check your plan and see if any adjustments are needed.

最后，设置两周后的提醒，检查你的计划，看看是否需要进行任何调整。

If you do write down the plan, you’ll be setting yourself up for success.

如果你把计划写下来，你就为成功奠定了基础。

If you do not write the plan down, you won’t have any excuse if your goals do not materialize.

如果你不把计划写下来，当你的目标没有实现时，你就没有任何借口了。

#↩

Make yourself a compass

自制一个指南针

Rules 30 to 31

规则 30 至 31

One of the defining moments of my life that finally got me unstuck from where I was and progressed my journey to who I wanted to become was when I realized that there was no map. My only tools to move forward were trial-and-error and a compass made of values and long-term objectives. The compass is what transforms trial-and-error from a random walk into a set of steps forward.

我人生中一个决定性的时刻，让我终于摆脱了困境，朝着理想自我迈进，那就是我意识到没有现成的路线图。我前进的唯一工具是不断试错，以及由价值观和长期目标构成的指南针。正是这指南针，将漫无目的的试错转化为清晰明确的前进方向。

The algorithm is simple. Look at your compass and take a step in that direction. Then, look at where you landed and check whether you got closer to where you want to be. If so, keep walking. If not, your compass is misaligned, and you should use a different one.

这个方法很简单。看看你的指南针，朝着那个方向走一步。然后，看看你走到哪里，检查一下你是否更接近目的地。如果更近了，就继续走。如果不是，说明你的指南针没对准，你应该换一个。

Of course, you might wonder: can’t I just know whether my compass is correct by checking whether it points towards where I want to be? Well, life is not that simple. For example, if your goal is to retire early, stopping working at 20 won’t do you any good – the path to early retirement passes through hard work first.

当然，你可能会想：难道我不能通过检查指南针是否指向我想去的地方来判断它是否正确吗？嗯，生活并非如此简单。例如，如果你的目标是提前退休，那么20岁就停止工作对你没有任何好处——通往提前退休的道路首先要经过艰苦的工作。

A good compass isn’t one that simply points at the ultimate reward you seek; it’s one that points out the path you must take such that if you followed that track, you would get closer to your desired destination.

好的指南针不仅仅是指向你所追求的最终目标；它还能指出你必须走的路，如果你沿着这条路走，你就会离你想要的目的地更近一步。

That said, sometimes compasses bring you to a dead end. They work until they don’t. Hence, the importance of re-evaluating every now and then whether your compasses are still right. On the other hand, you don’t want to evaluate your compasses too often – values, for example, make for great compasses even though they often create small steps back and should be evaluated for their long-term contributions.

话虽如此，指南针有时也会把你引向死胡同。它们或许曾经有效，但终究会失效。因此，时不时地重新评估你的指南针是否仍然正确至关重要。另一方面，你也不应该过于频繁地评估你的指南针——例如，价值观本身就是很好的指南针，尽管它们常常会带来一些小小的倒退，但我们应该从长远角度来评估它们的影响。

Evaluating compasses is itself a skill with no map, only trial and error and regular checks on whether you’re getting closer to where you want to be, or you need to recalibrate

评估指南针本身就是一门技能，没有地图，只能通过反复试验和定期检查来判断你是否正在接近目的地，或者是否需要重新校准。

To sum it up: you need compasses, but you cannot just decide which ones are the good ones for you. Instead, you must try and recalibrate as much as needed.

总而言之：你需要指南针，但你不能直接决定哪些指南针适合你。相反，你必须根据需要不断调整和校准。

That said, in the following pages, you’ll find some of what, in my experience, are the most effective compasses for most people.

也就是说，在接下来的几页中，你会发现一些根据我的经验，对大多数人来说最有效的指南针。

Rule 30

规则30

Self-respect is the compass
for change that matters

自尊是引领真正重要变革的指南针。

“Do one thing per day that will increase your self-respect.”

每天做一件能提升你自尊心的事。

I don’t remember who I heard this advice from, but it has served me well.

我不记得是谁给我这个建议的了，但它对我的帮助很大。

Striving to do, each day, at least one thing that will increase my self-respect is great:

每天努力做至少一件能提升自尊的事情，这很棒：

– First, it gives me something to be proud of and happy for, even if the rest of my day was terrible.

首先，即使我当天其他时间过得很糟糕，这件事也能让我感到自豪和快乐。

– Second, it keeps me on the path of self-improvement. It helps me retain motivation because I never entirely abandoned my path.

其次，它让我坚持自我提升的道路。它帮助我保持动力，因为我从未完全放弃这条路。

– Third, it is impactful. Things that increase your self-respect tend to be good for you, at least for your future self.

第三，它确实会产生影响。提升自尊的事情往往对你有益，至少对未来的你有益。

– And fourth, things that increase your self-respect usually compound and transform vicious circles into virtuous ones.

第四，提升自尊的事情通常会产生累积效应，将恶性循环转变为良性循环。

ACTION:

行动：

Practice the advice. Strive to do at least one thing per day that will increase your self-respect.

实践这些建议。努力每天至少做一件能提升你自尊的事情。

If one day you fail, do a post-mortem: think about what prevented you from taking the action; then, address that problem so that you’ll never face it again. Slowly but steadily, your actions will compound.

如果有一天你失败了，那就进行事后分析：想想是什么阻碍了你采取行动；然后，解决这个问题，这样你就不会再遇到同样的问题。慢慢地，你的行动就会产生累积效应。

#↩
Rule 31
规则31

Bad decisions in life arise from having optimized for the wrong variable

生活中糟糕的决策源于对错误变量的优化。

We often use criteria established by others to make our choices. For example, we might use our parents’ perception of what a good career is to decide which degree to pursue.

我们常常会参考他人制定的标准来做选择。例如，我们可能会根据父母对好职业的看法来决定攻读哪个学位。

Unfulfillment arises from using metrics chosen by others to estimate personal success (e.g., the car we own as a measurement of our success).

不满足感来自于使用他人选择的指标来衡量个人成功（例如，用我们拥有的汽车来衡量我们的成功）。

Sustainability problems arise from using short-term success to estimate long-term one (e.g., boosting sales this quarter by delivering false promises to customers).

可持续性问题源于用短期成功来估计长期成功（例如，通过向客户做出虚假承诺来提高本季度的销售额）。

Failed relationships arise from choosing a partner using widely desirable traits instead of personally desirable ones.

失败的感情关系源于选择伴侣时，看重的是普遍受欢迎的特质，而不是个人喜欢的特质。

In general, regretful choices arise from using widely accepted metrics for success instead of personally defined ones.

一般来说，令人后悔的选择源于使用广泛接受的成功标准，而不是个人定义的成功标准。

…

Humans are extremely good at succeeding at their priorities but extremely dishonest about them. Many spend their lives succeeding, yes, but succeeding at goals chosen by others. And some spend their lives failing, because they embarked on pursuits chosen by others, with their subconscious having decided the pursuit isn’t worth it and thus passively sabotaging it. For example, if our analytical mind thinks that studying law might be the right choice but our subconscious thinks it would expose us to a career of long working hours and tedious bureaucracy, the latter will cause us to be demotivated in our studies. This phenomenon is called commitment to failure .

人类非常擅长实现自己的优先事项，但却极不诚实。许多人一生都在取得成功，没错，但他们实现的却是别人选择的目标。而有些人一生都在失败，因为他们选择了别人选择的事业，潜意识却认为这些事业不值得，从而暗中破坏了它。例如，如果我们理性的头脑认为学习法律可能是正确的选择，但我们的潜意识却认为这会让我们面临长时间的工作和繁琐的官僚程序，那么后者就会让我们失去学习的动力。这种现象被称为“失败承诺”。

I believe that every time we fail at something we have the resources to succeed at, it is because we considered an internal success to fail at it (i.e., we were uncomfortable with the consequences of succeeding at it). 10 For example, many teenagers are shy about asking girls on dates because they’re afraid of the pressure in case she said yes. Paradoxically, they’re not (just) afraid of the consequences of failure but rather of those of success.

我认为，每次我们明明有能力成功却失败，都是因为我们把失败本身视为一种内在的成功（也就是说，我们无法接受成功带来的后果）。例如，很多青少年不敢约女孩出去，因为他们害怕女孩答应后的压力。矛盾的是，他们害怕的并非仅仅是失败的后果，而是成功的后果。

…

Even when we choose a metric that is initially correlated with the ultimate outcome we desire, we often forget that optimizing for a metric reduces its correlation with the ultimate outcome. 11 As an example, imagine an author in the business of selling books online. He discovers that 2% of his Twitter followers bought his book. Therefore, he decides to run an advertisement to get more followers (because the number of followers correlates with book sales). Such an ad tends to select people interested in following the author on Twitter, regardless of whether they are interested in buying his books. As a result, if before the advertisement 2% of followers ended up as customers, after the ad, it is possible that only 1% will. Optimization (running an ad optimized to get new followers) dilutes the correlation between a metric and the ultimate outcome (the percentage of followers buying the book).

即使我们选择的指标最初与我们期望的最终结果相关，我们也常常忘记，对某个指标进行优化会降低它与最终结果的相关性。例如，假设一位作家在线销售书籍。他发现只有 2% 的 Twitter 粉丝购买了他的书。因此，他决定投放广告来吸引更多粉丝（因为粉丝数量与书籍销量相关）。这样的广告往往会选择那些对关注这位作家感兴趣的人，而不管他们是否真的想买他的书。结果，如果在投放广告之前有 2% 的粉丝最终购买了他的书，那么在投放广告之后，可能只有 1% 的粉丝会购买。优化（投放旨在吸引新粉丝的广告）会削弱指标与最终结果（购买书籍的粉丝比例）之间的相关性。

If there is a way you could maximize the metric without contributing to your ultimate goal, it will happen. Metrics are not chosen because they are more impactful; they are chosen because they are easier to measure or to influence. And the reason they are easier to influence is usually that there is a population of low-hanging fruits that contribute to the proximate metric but not to the ultimate metric. Collecting these is a waste: they do not do anything to improve your ultimate goal. Optimizing for a proxy often brings a dilution in quality.

如果存在一种方法，可以在不提升最终目标的情况下最大化某个指标，那么这种方法就会出现。选择指标并非因为它们更具影响力，而是因为它们更容易衡量或影响。而它们之所以更容易影响，通常是因为存在大量“唾手可得”的指标，这些指标对直接指标有贡献，但对最终指标却没有贡献。收集这些指标是浪费：它们对提升最终目标没有任何帮助。为了追求某个指标而进行优化，往往会导致质量下降。

Proxies promote unwanted behavior. It is the same thing that happens when you are not specific in rewarding someone. For example, let’s say that you told your son, “Congratulations on having gotten an A on the test!” without knowing that he cheated. By rewarding a proxy (the mark) instead of the real thing (the study), you would have reinforced an unwanted behavior (the cheating).

替代指标会助长不良行为。这与奖励方式不明确的情况类似。例如，假设你对儿子说“恭喜你考试得了A！”，却不知道他作弊了。你奖励的是替代指标（分数）而不是真正重要的内容（学习成果），这实际上强化了不良行为（作弊）。

…

Philosopher and entrepreneur Naval Ravikant once said: “A cockroach is just as evolved as we are, just across different fitness functions.”

哲学家兼企业家纳瓦尔·拉维坎特曾说过：“蟑螂和我们一样进化，只是进化方式不同而已。”

What metric you choose to define success, i.e., your fitness function, matters. It will apply evolutionary pressure on your behaviors & personality traits and will shape you. It will reinforce those traits that led to progress on your chosen metric and weaken those that did not.

你选择用什么指标来定义成功，也就是你的适应度函数，至关重要。它会对你的行为和人格特质施加进化压力，并塑造你。它会强化那些在你所选指标上取得进步的特质，削弱那些没有取得进步的特质。

Choose your proxies wisely; don’t become a cockroach.

谨慎选择代理；不要成为蟑螂。

…

Another reason not to use proxies is that circumstances change over time. It might sound useful to choose a proxy to focus on what appears to be the most beneficial sub-objective now. However, it might lead to tunnel vision or to a lack of periodic reevaluation to determine whether the current proxy is still beneficial to follow.

不使用代理指标的另一个原因是情况会随时间变化。选择一个代理指标来专注于当前看似最有利的子目标，这听起来似乎很有用。然而，这可能会导致视野狭窄，或者缺乏定期重新评估，从而无法确定当前的代理指标是否仍然有效。

What got you here won’t get you there. 12 For example, memorizing concepts might be a useful skill to get your degree, but it is a terrible one for a successful career (other than in acting). Money is great for increasing your life quality when you’re poor, but it doesn’t do much once you’re rich. What looks like an excellent proxy now will almost invariably be a bad proxy in the future.

让你走到今天的方法未必能让你走到明天。例如，记忆概念或许是获得学位的一项有用技能，但对于成功的事业（演艺事业除外）来说却毫无用处。金钱在你贫穷时能极大地提升你的生活质量，但一旦你富有，它的作用就微乎其微了。现在看起来极好的指标，在未来几乎必然会变成糟糕的指标。

Moreover, proxies bring noise (because they are partially decoupled from the ultimate metric, which is what we ultimately want to measure). And they also bring cognitive dissonance (for the same reason; if we ever take an action that is good from the point of view of the proxy but not of the ultimate metric, we might end up asking ourselves, “Why did I do it?”).

此外，代理指标会带来噪声（因为它们与最终指标（也就是我们最终想要衡量的指标）部分脱钩）。而且它们还会带来认知失调（原因相同；如果我们采取的行动从代理指标的角度来看是好的，但从最终指标的角度来看却不是，我们最终可能会问自己，“我为什么要这样做？”）。

Following proxies instead of the real thing is similar to drug addiction. Addicts become reactive to cues (proxies).

用替代品代替真品，这与毒瘾类似。成瘾者会对各种线索（替代品）产生反应。

Living a diverse life increases happiness because it avoids addiction and tolerance due to repetitively associating rewards to the same cues. 13 14

丰富多彩的生活方式能提升幸福感，因为它能避免因反复将奖励与相同线索联系起来而产生的成瘾性和耐受性。

ACTION:

行动：

Prioritization is the art of spotting proxies and excluding them from our to-do list. Proxies are fought with not-to-do lists (rule #5). 15

优先级排序的艺术在于识别代理并将其从待办事项列表中排除。对抗代理的方法是建立“不做事项列表”（规则 5）。

Some heuristics on how to spot proxies and get rid of them:

以下是一些识别和清除代理服务器的实用技巧：

- Everything which causes addiction is a proxy.

所有导致成瘾的因素都是成瘾的替代品。

- Any metric which is not weighted by the impact it generates is a proxy . (And any metric whose correlation/impact to your ultimate goal is approximated to be static in time, is a proxy.)

任何未根据其产生的影响进行加权的指标都是代理指标。（任何与最终目标的关联性/影响在时间上近似保持不变的指标也是代理指标。）

- If a proxy is chosen because it is easier to improve rather than easier to measure, don’t choose it.

- 如果选择某个代理指标是因为它更容易改进而不是更容易衡量，那就不要选择它。

- If a process describes what it is rather than what it is for, it has been optimized for a proxy.

- 如果一个过程描述的是它是什么，而不是它的用途，那么它就是针对代理程序优化的。

- If it won’t be important in five years, it is a proxy.

- 如果五年后它不再重要，那么它就是一个替代品。

- If it wasn’t important for people one thousand years ago, it is a proxy .

- 如果一千年前的人们不重视它，那么它就只是一个替代品。

- Doubt everyone whose core competency is a proxy (students whose competency is to pass exams, which are a proxy for knowledge; teachers whose competency is to get papers published, which are a proxy for teacher quality; financial advisors whose competency is looking trustworthy; speakers whose competency is to use words rather than choosing them; and so on) 16 .

- 怀疑所有以某种代理能力为核心能力的人（例如，学生以通过考试为能力，而考试只是知识的代理；教师以发表论文为能力，而论文只是教师素质的代理；财务顾问以看起来值得信赖为能力；演讲者以使用词语而不是选择词语为能力；等等）。

These heuristics won’t always be accurate, but you’ll be better off acting as if they are (that’s the point of heuristics).

这些经验法则并不总是准确的，但你最好还是按照它们的准确性来行事（这就是经验法则的意义所在）。

#↩

Learn to learn

学会学习

Rules 32 to 39

规则 32 至 39

Mediocre performers learn skills. Great performers learn how to learn them.

平庸的表演者学习技能，优秀的表演者学习如何学习技能。

The latter is not only indispensable to achieving mastery, but it also makes the process of learning easier and more enjoyable.

后者不仅是掌握技能的必要条件，而且还能让学习过程变得更容易、更有趣。

This chapter is about learning how to learn.

本章讲述的是如何学习。

Rule 32

规则32

Metapractice

元实践

Why do some people become masters at their craft while others seem never to improve?

为什么有些人能成为技艺精湛的大师，而有些人却似乎永远无法进步？

People who achieve mastery do two things differently: they practice more, and they adjust their practice more frequently. During each session, not only do they work to improve their skills but also to improve their practice.

那些技艺精湛的人有两个共同点：一是练习更多，二是更频繁地调整练习方法。每次练习中，他们不仅致力于提升技能，也致力于改进练习方式。

Metapractice – the ability to tweak one’s practice to maximize its effectiveness – is the most underrated skill of them all. After all, if one is bad at metapractice, he will have trouble learning any other skill.

元练习——即调整自身练习以最大程度提升其效果的能力——是所有技能中最被低估的。毕竟，如果一个人不擅长元练习，那么他学习其他任何技能都会很困难。

Do not just practice your skill – practice your practice.

不要只是练习你的技能——要练习你的练习。

ACTION:

行动：

The next time you practice a skill – playing basketball, cooking, selling a product, filing a report, publishing a blog post, whatever – think about how you can modify your practice to get more feedback out of it.

下次当你练习一项技能时——无论是打篮球、做饭、销售产品、撰写报告、发表博客文章等等——想想如何改进你的练习方法，以便从中获得更多反馈。

– When playing basketball, after each shot, try noticing where the ball hits the rim. Or observe the position of your feet as you jump. In general, focus on specific aspects of the task at hand and see how they influence outcomes.

打篮球时，每次投篮后，试着观察球击中篮筐的位置。或者观察起跳时双脚的位置。总之，专注于当前动作的特定方面，看看它们如何影响结果。

– When cooking, try applying a variation to the recipe (perhaps a new spice? Higher oven temperature?) and see how it changes the taste.

– 烹饪时，尝试对食谱进行一些变化（比如添加新的香料？提高烤箱温度？），看看味道会有什么变化。

– When publishing a blog, try focusing on a different aspect of each post. For example, for one post, focus on being interesting. For the next one, focus on being crystal clear. And for the one after that, focus on writing as your favorite author would.

发布博客文章时，尝试每篇文章侧重不同的方面。例如，一篇可以专注于引人入胜，下一篇可以专注于清晰易懂，再下一篇则可以尝试模仿你最喜欢的作家的写作风格。

More importantly, internalize the habit of asking yourself, after each session, “How could the practice have been better?” . Should you prepare a written plan (one or two bullet points) of what to focus on before each practice? Should you record yourself? Should you look for a mentor? Should you take more breaks, using them to absorb what you just learned? Should you take notes?

更重要的是，养成每次练习后都问自己“这次练习如何才能做得更好？”的习惯。你是否应该在每次练习前准备一份书面计划（一两点要点）来记录重点？你是否应该录音？你是否应该寻找一位导师？你是否应该多休息，利用休息时间来消化刚刚学到的东西？你是否应该做笔记？

Finally, should you ever skip a practice session, get into the habit of asking yourself: what is the root cause that made me miss the session? How should I address it? What should I change, in my habits or my environment, to ensure that I will never skip a practice session for the same reason again?

最后，如果你错过了一次训练，要养成习惯问自己：导致我错过训练的根本原因是什么？我应该如何解决这个问题？我应该改变哪些习惯或环境因素，以确保我以后不会再因为同样的原因错过训练？

Improve your practice, and you’ll improve yourself.

提高你的练习水平，你就能提高自己。

Rule 33
规则33

Learn by doing

在实践中学习

“A decent proxy for your success will be your ratio of sweating to watching others sweat.” – Scott Galloway

“衡量你成功的一个不错指标，就是你自身流汗与旁观他人流汗的比例。”——斯科特·加洛韦

Many people neglect the importance of frequent practice. They believe that practice is something to be performed after they are ready. Instead, practice is how we become ready .

许多人忽视了经常练习的重要性。他们认为练习是在准备好之后才需要进行的。然而，练习恰恰是我们做好准备的途径。

Reading only puts knowledge in front of us. Practice ensures we internalize it. If we do not take action right after reading something, the know-how will stay with the book rather than with us.

阅读只是将知识呈现在我们面前，实践才能确保我们真正内化这些知识。如果我们读完后不立即付诸行动，这些知识就只会留在书本上，而不是留在我们心中。

Practice is how our mind takes notes so that we do not forget when it matters.

练习就像我们的大脑记笔记一样，这样我们才不会在关键时刻忘记。

…

“Building products, writing, and painting are not mental exercises but physical ones. Reading to improve is like watching someone else work out – it does almost nothing for you. To run better, run. To paint better, paint. To write better, write. To build better, build.” – Gumroad founder Sahil Lavingia

“产品开发、写作和绘画并非脑力活动，而是体力活动。通过阅读来提升自己，就像观看别人锻炼一样——对你几乎没有任何帮助。想跑得更好，就去跑；想画得更好，就去画；想写得更好，就去写；想做出更好的产品，就去做出来。”——Gumroad创始人Sahil Lavingia

Mental output is only valuable in the measure it affects your reality by the intermediation of practical work.

精神产出的价值仅在于它通过实际工作对你的现实产生的影响。

Think too long, and you become detached from reality, limiting your future potential to affect it.

思考时间过长，你会脱离现实，从而限制你未来影响现实的潜力。

ACTION:

行动：

Avoid reading two nonfiction books in a row. Instead, read one and immediately apply its learnings in practice. It has to be something whose output is a physical product or a physical interaction. Only afterward, read a second book. Then, again, use your newly acquired knowledge to produce something. Keep going.

避免连续阅读两本非虚构类书籍。相反，先读一本，然后立即将书中的知识付诸实践。实践的成果必须是实物或实际互动。之后再读第二本书。然后，再次运用你新获得的知识去创造一些东西。坚持下去。

The same applies to YouTube videos, online courses, and so on. Never take one “theoretical learning course” right after another. Always put to practice what you’ve learned before taking the next course.

这同样适用于YouTube视频、在线课程等等。千万不要连续学习一门“理论课程”后紧接着学习另一门。在学习下一门课程之前，一定要先将所学知识付诸实践。

#↩
Rule 34
规则34

Maximize feedback loops

最大化反馈回路

David Bayles and Ted Orland tell us the story of a ceramics teacher who, on the first day, divided his class into two groups. One would be graded solely on the quantity of works produced and the other solely on their quality. Finally, on the final day, the teacher graded the works. Surprisingly, he noticed that the group that made the most pots also produced the higher quality ones.

大卫·贝勒斯和泰德·奥兰德讲述了一个陶艺老师的故事。第一天，老师把学生分成两组。一组只按作品数量评分，另一组只按作品质量评分。最后一天，老师给作品评分。出乎意料的是，他发现制作数量最多的那组作品质量也更高。

Who iterates the most also learns the most.

迭代次数最多的人学到的东西也最多。

The Wright brothers are a great example of this principle. In 1903, multiple groups were competing to invent the airplane. Some had ample funds and personnel. The Wright brothers had neither. Why did they succeed? They tried a new prototype almost every day, whereas their competitors only tested once a month or so.

莱特兄弟是这一原理的绝佳例证。1903年，许多团队竞相发明飞机。有些团队资金雄厚、人员充足，而莱特兄弟却两者都缺乏。他们为何成功？因为他们几乎每天都在测试新的原型机，而他们的竞争对手一个月才测试一次左右。

It takes practice to assimilate insights – to transition from knowing what makes sense to knowing what works and why.

吸收见解需要练习——从知道什么有意义到知道什么有效以及为什么有效，这需要转变。

Of course, knowledge and planning are important. That said, knowledge and planning that aren’t alternated to practice quickly become detached from reality and thus unusable. The number of useful things you will learn is limited by the amount of feedback you receive from your practice.

当然，知识和计划固然重要。然而，如果知识和计划不付诸实践，很快就会脱离实际，从而失去实用价值。你最终能学到多少有用的东西，取决于你从实践中获得的反馈有多少。

To maximize your learning capability, you should aim to get feedback as frequently as possible. The trick is to divide your work into the smallest bits possible. For example, publishing three blog posts is faster than publishing a book and is likely to provide you with more feedback (as people tend to give the same amount of feedback regardless of the length of the content).

为了最大限度地提高学习效率，你应该尽可能频繁地获取反馈。诀窍在于将工作分解成尽可能小的部分。例如，发布三篇博客文章比出版一本书更快，而且更有可能获得更多反馈（因为人们往往会给出与内容长度无关的反馈）。

Therefore, do not wait for your project to be finished to collect feedback . Instead, send out small bits to your friends and ask them what they think. You will get more information and quicker. As a result, you will be able to catch your mistakes earlier and improve your skills and project faster.

因此，不要等到项目完成才去收集反馈。相反，可以先发布一些小片段给朋友，询问他们的想法。这样可以更快地获得更多信息。如此一来，你就能更早地发现错误，更快地提升技能，改进项目。

Of course, who you send your work to matters. I will cover this later. For now, the point is: share your work as much as possible. Not with everyone, but with someone.

当然，你把作品发给谁很重要。这一点我稍后会详细讲解。现在，重点是：尽可能多地分享你的作品。不必分享给所有人，但至少要分享给一些人。

– If you are an employee, do not wait for the annual review to collect feedback. Instead, at least monthly, ask your boss and colleagues what they think of your work and what you could do to improve.

如果您是员工，不要等到年度考核才收集反馈。相反，至少每月一次，询问您的老板和同事对您工作的看法以及您可以改进的地方。

– If you are a restaurant chef, change how you cook your dishes as frequently as possible, and collect feedback. If you are an artist, do the same with your artwork.

如果你是餐厅厨师，就尽可能频繁地改变菜肴的烹饪方法，并收集反馈。如果你是艺术家，也应该对你的作品进行同样的调整。

– If you are an athlete, do not wait for the coach to give you feedback. Instead, analyze each of your movements. What can you do differently next time? Also, do not wait to be asked to try something new. The earlier you try it, the earlier you know whether it works better than what you are already doing.

如果你是一名运动员，不要等着教练给你反馈。相反，你应该分析自己的每一个动作。下次可以做出哪些改变？此外，不要等到别人要求你尝试新方法。你越早尝试，就越早知道它是否比你目前的方法更有效。

…

The advice of maximizing feedback loops by reducing the time between each “feedback event” does not apply only to learning but also to investing, selling, and to many other domains. In this case, “feedback” is not only knowledge but everything that a customer or consumer can give you back. Make these return loops as fast as possible.

缩短每次“反馈事件”之间的时间间隔，从而最大化反馈循环的建议不仅适用于学习，也适用于投资、销售以及许多其他领域。在这种情况下，“反馈”不仅指知识，还包括客户或消费者能够给予你的所有反馈。务必尽可能缩短这些反馈循环。

If you are an entrepreneur, improve inventory velocity. The faster you get money, and the faster you can reinvest it, the faster it will produce returns (this is a feedback loop too).

如果你是一名创业者，就要提高库存周转率。资金到账越快，再投资速度越快，就能越快产生回报（这也是一个良性循环）。

Important note: there is a limitation to the advice in this paragraph. Only consider the feedback that builds the assets that will help you succeed. Instead, neglect feedback that points you to shortcuts. It’s not worth it.

重要提示：本段建议存在局限性。请只考虑那些能帮助你积累成功所需资源的反馈。相反，请忽略那些指向捷径的反馈，因为它们得不偿失。

ACTION:

行动：

What is the smallest bit you can divide your work into?

你可以把你的工作分成多少个最小的部分？

Collect feedback on each such small piece of output of yours. Feedback does not have to be formal (e.g., people filling out feedback forms). You can observe the reaction of people – are they clapping? Are they sharing your work? Which pieces of your work do they applaud, and which are they indifferent to? Why?

收集你每一份小作品的反馈。反馈不必是正式的（例如，让人们填写反馈表）。你可以观察人们的反应——他们会鼓掌吗？他们会分享你的作品吗？他们赞赏你的哪些作品，对哪些作品漠不关心？为什么？

The more variations you try and the more feedback you receive, the more you will learn.

你尝试的变体越多，收到的反馈越多，你学到的东西就越多。

Some people are reluctant to receive feedback. They might be afraid of what it will say about them or their work. Or they might be afraid to share something which isn’t perfect yet. You can avoid being like them by internalizing that feedback is a necessary piece of success.

有些人不愿接受反馈。他们可能害怕反馈会如何评价自己或自己的作品。也可能害怕分享尚未完善的作品。你可以通过认识到反馈是成功不可或缺的一部分，来避免成为他们那样的人。

Every time you receive feedback, focus on the fact that you are receiving a part of your future success. Likewise, every time you openly engage with someone and share a piece of your work with them, visualize the fact that you just completed one of the necessary steps towards achieving your dreams. This will help you keep motivated and absorb feedback better.

每次收到反馈时，都要专注于你正在获得未来成功的一部分。同样地，每次你与他人坦诚交流并分享你的作品时，都要想象自己刚刚完成了实现梦想的必要步骤之一。这将有助于你保持动力，并更好地吸收反馈。

#↩
Rule 35
规则35

Attribute feedback to the specific

将反馈归因于具体情况

“Be bored with a book, not with the act of reading.” – Nassim Nicholas Taleb

“对书感到厌倦，而不是对阅读本身感到厌倦。”——纳西姆·尼古拉斯·塔勒布

In your journey of personal growth, you will experience many setbacks. For example, you might read a book that is boring or reveals itself to be useless to you. If you associate the feeling (boredom or uselessness) with the broad activity you were performing (reading), you will sabotage your future chances of growth (reading useful books).

在个人成长的道路上，你会遇到许多挫折。例如，你可能会读到一本枯燥乏味或对你毫无用处的书。如果你把这种感觉（枯燥或无用）与你当时正在进行的活动（阅读）联系起来，你就会阻碍自己未来的成长机会（阅读有用的书籍）。

Conversely, being very specific (associating boredom to the book) ensures that you will still be motivated to perform the self-improvement activity (reading other books) again in the future.

相反，如果能非常具体地描述（将无聊与这本书联系起来），就能确保你将来仍然有动力进行自我提升活动（阅读其他书籍）。

This phenomenon also applies to interactions with other people. For example, if someone says that the story you just told at dinner was boring, do not see it as a personal attack. Instead, see it as a signal that the story you told was not relevant to the attendees or that your storytelling abilities have to be improved. Perceiving the feedback as a personal attack will do nothing good for you. Conversely, perceiving it as a signal that a mental pattern of yours is a burden will set you on a new, faster trajectory towards personal fulfillment.

这种现象也适用于人际交往。例如，如果有人说你刚才在晚餐时讲的故事很无聊，不要把它看作是人身攻击。相反，你应该把它看作是一个信号，表明你讲的故事与听众无关，或者你的讲故事能力需要提高。把这种反馈视为人身攻击对你没有任何好处。相反，如果你把它看作是某种思维模式成为你负担的信号，你就会走上一条新的、更快的实现自我价值的道路。

When you receive a piece of negative feedback, never perceive it as directed to you (broad); instead, redirect it to a specific mental pattern of yours (specific) .

当你收到负面反馈时，不要把它看作是针对你的（宽泛的）；相反，要把它指向你自身的某种特定思维模式（具体的）。

…

It is possible to redirect feedback to one of your mental patterns only if you do not identify with your mental patterns but with the container of your mental patterns.

只有当你认同的不是你的思维模式，而是你的思维模式的容器时，才有可能将反馈重新导向你的某种思维模式。

Just as an executive might fire the employees who act against the company’s interests, you should do the same with your mental patterns. Train your mental patterns. Promote them. Fire them. But do not identify with them.

就像高管会解雇那些损害公司利益的员工一样，你也应该对自己的思维模式采取同样的做法。训练你的思维模式，提升它们，摒弃它们，但不要认同它们。

People whose ego identifies with specific mental patterns of theirs prevent those mental patterns from learning from feedback. They limit their own development. They shackle their own brain.

如果一个人的自我认同与特定的思维模式相契合，这些思维模式就无法从反馈中学习。他们限制了自身的发展，束缚了自己的大脑。

Don’t be like them. Do not attach your ego to any specific mental pattern. Instead, attach your ego to being someone who learns from feedback.

别学他们。不要把你的自尊心与任何特定的思维模式捆绑在一起。相反，要把你的自尊心与成为一个能够从反馈中学习的人联系起来。

ACTION:

行动：

Try to remember the last piece of negative feedback you received. Which mental pattern of yours was it directed to?

试着回忆一下你最近收到的负面反馈。它针对的是你哪种思维模式？

Now, try to remember the last time you felt bored or frustrated with an activity meant to improve you. Towards which particular aspects of that activity was the feeling directed?

现在，试着回想一下你上一次对旨在提升自我的活动感到厌倦或沮丧是什么时候？这种感觉具体指向该活动的哪些方面？

…

(I wrote a whole book on how to use feedback to grow, and in particular, on how to manage your population of mental patterns. The book is called “The Power of Adaptation” and can be found at gum.co/powerofa ).

（我写了一整本书，讲述如何利用反馈来成长，特别是如何管理你的一系列思维模式。这本书名为《适应的力量》，可以在 gum.co/powerofa 上找到。）

#↩
Rule 36
规则36

Only the practice that is deliberate matters

只有刻意为之的练习才重要。

“You can generate learning by creating situations where you’re not sure about the outcome.” – Modern philosopher Michael Mayer

“你可以通过创造结果不确定的情境来促进学习。”——现代哲学家迈克尔·梅耶

We learn our skills by practicing them. However, some people seem to practice and yet not improve their abilities, especially after having achieved some basic proficiency. They feel frustrated. They do not understand why their continued efforts do not seem to matter.

我们通过练习来学习技能。然而，有些人似乎一直在练习，却始终无法提高能力，尤其是在达到一定基本水平之后。他们感到沮丧，不明白为什么自己的持续努力似乎毫无效果。

Only the practice which is deliberate matters. Deliberate practice consists of trying something new, something whose outcome is unknown. Because the outcome is unknown, it represents new information: learning.

只有刻意练习才有效。刻意练习是指尝试一些新的、结果未知的事物。正因为结果未知，它才代表着新的信息：学习。

The practitioner who only practices what he knows will soon reach a limit past which he cannot progress. The limit is made of the unknown. Only the practitioner who ventures into the unknown can advance past the limit.

只修习已知领域的修行者，很快就会达到无法超越的极限。这极限源于未知。唯有勇于探索未知的修行者，才能突破这极限。

That said, practice cannot be chaotic. What is not known (yet) has to be practiced with intention. It’s not about “randomly testing something new.” Instead, it’s about proactively formulating hypotheses and then testing them. For example, “I think that if I do X, Y happens. Let’s try.”

也就是说，练习不能杂乱无章。对于未知的事物，必须有意识地进行练习。这并非“随意尝试新事物”，而是主动提出假设并进行验证。例如，“我认为如果我做X，就会发生Y。我们来试试。”

For signal to emerge, practice cannot be noisy.

要想产生信号，练习中不能有噪音。

ACTION:

行动：

The next time you practice a skill of yours, try something new – something whose outcome you do not know.

下次练习技能时，尝试一些新的东西——一些你不知道结果如何的东西。

Before you try, make a hypothesis about what will happen.

在尝试之前，先对将会发生什么情况做出假设。

Then, try it.

然后，试试看。

Did what you expected happen? Why or why not? Make a new hypothesis and test it again.

你预期的结果出现了吗？为什么？提出一个新的假设并再次验证。

This is how learning happens.

这就是学习的过程。

#↩
Rule 37
规则37

Learning is about seeing.
If you cannot understand something,
ask what is there to see

学习在于观察。如果你不理解某件事，就问问自己：有什么可看的？

Imagine my mother and Michael Jordan watching a video recording of a basketball game. (Michael Jordan is one of the greatest players of all time 17 . My mother never watched a single basketball game.)

想象一下我妈妈和迈克尔·乔丹一起看篮球比赛录像的场景。（迈克尔·乔丹是有史以来最伟大的球员之一。我妈妈从来没看过一场篮球比赛。）

When Michael Jordan observes the game, he sees how players dash to separate from their opponents and the angles their elbows make while shooting the ball. He probably even “sees” what each player is thinking to do next.

当迈克尔·乔丹观看比赛时，他会观察球员如何冲刺摆脱对手，以及他们在投篮时肘部的角度。他甚至可能“看穿”了每个球员下一步的意图。

When my mother sees a basketball game, she doesn’t see any of that. She only sees people running around in shorts. Perhaps, she notices how one of the players didn’t tuck his shirt properly into his shorts.

我妈妈看篮球比赛的时候，根本不会注意到这些。她看到的只是穿着短裤跑来跑去的人们。或许，她会注意到某个球员的衬衫没塞进短裤里。

People only see what is made of things they understand.

人们只能看到由他们理解的事物构成的事物。

Why is this important? Because…

为什么这很重要？因为……

People only learn from what they can see.

人们只能通过亲眼所见来学习。

After watching the game, because he could observe the players’ movements and infer their purpose, Michael Jordan will have a deep understanding of the tactics used by the two teams (their patterns of movement).

观看比赛后，由于迈克尔·乔丹能够观察球员的动作并推断他们的目的，因此他对两队使用的战术（他们的移动模式）会有深刻的了解。

Conversely, after watching the game, because she only saw men randomly running around, my mother would not have learned a thing about the tactics played by the two teams. Tactics are patterns of player movements, each executed for a specific purpose. If my mother is unable to see and understand such movements and their purpose, she is unable to learn about patterns made of them.

相反，如果我母亲看完比赛后，只看到球员们漫无目的地跑动，她就无法了解两队的战术。战术是指球员移动的模式，每个动作都有其特定的目的。如果我母亲无法看到并理解这些动作及其目的，她就无法了解由这些动作构成的战术模式。

This brings us to what I call the fundamental principle of learning:

这就引出了我所说的学习的基本原则：

Learning is about making connections. We can only learn connections between pieces of information that we have already learned.

学习的本质在于建立联系。我们只能学习已掌握信息之间的联系。

This might seem obvious, so let’s look at the non-obvious implication:

这似乎显而易见，所以我们来看看它背后不太明显的含义：

In learning and in teaching, the focus should be on supplying the right pieces of information given what the student already knows rather than providing pieces of information regardless of whether they are understandable .

在学习和教学中，重点应该是根据学生已有的知识提供正确的信息，而不是不顾学生是否能够理解而提供信息。

In the case of self-learning, you are your own teacher. Focus on looking for the right pieces of information given what you already know.

自学时，你就是自己的老师。专注于根据你已有的知识寻找正确的信息。

A way-too-common mistake is consuming educational content above your current level. Or observing interactions in an environment whose fundamental rules you do not know. If you do not have the tools to understand its contents fully , everything will seem chaotic, and you will learn little. Even worse, you might miss some information and internalize the wrong conclusions.

一个非常常见的错误是学习超出自身水平的教育内容，或者观察自己不了解其基本规则的环境中的互动。如果你没有充分理解内容所需的工具，一切都会显得混乱不堪，你也学不到什么东西。更糟糕的是，你可能会错过一些信息，甚至内化错误的结论。

Better to take a step back and learn about the fundamental patterns that compose the information you’re trying to decode.

最好退后一步，了解一下构成你试图解码的信息的基本模式。

Note: I plan to publish a book on the mechanics of learning and how to learn (almost) anything. To avoid missing it, you can subscribe to updates on my future books on gumroad.com/dellannaluca or luca-dellanna.com/newsletter .

注：我计划出版一本关于学习机制以及如何学习（几乎）任何事物的书。为了不错过这本书，您可以订阅我的新书更新信息，网址是 gumroad.com/dellannaluca 或 luca-dellanna.com/newsletter。

ACTION:

行动：

Pick one area for which you consumed educational content over the last year but failed to make visible improvements. It could be a sport, a hobby, cooking (you read some recipes or watched some videos), investing, a new task at work, a self-help book, and so on.

选择一个你在过去一年中接触过学习资料但却没有取得明显进步的领域。它可以是运动、爱好、烹饪（你读过一些食谱或看过一些视频）、投资、工作中的新任务、一本自助书籍等等。

Then, find someone who is an expert in that area. It could be a coach, a friend, a colleague, or a teacher. If you do not know any such expert, email or call one you do not know (I will explain how in the chapter on “getting help”).

然后，找到该领域的专家。可以是教练、朋友、同事或老师。如果你不认识这样的专家，可以给一位你不认识的专家发邮件或打电话（我会在“寻求帮助”一章中解释具体方法）。

Once you find such an expert, tell him what you are trying to understand or learn and ask him, “what is the pattern or principle that I can’t see but that you, as an expert, do see?” Use precisely those words. He will understand, and he will help you.

找到这样的专家后，告诉他你想要理解或学习的内容，然后问他：“我看不见但你作为专家却能看到的模式或原理是什么？” 务必用这些话。他会理解，也会帮助你。

He will likely recommend you read a classic book on the matter. Your first reaction might be, “I already know that,” “It is too boring,” or “I can do better.” In this case, be humble, remember who the expert is, and follow his instructions. It will be worth it.

他很可能会建议你读一本关于这个领域的经典著作。你的第一反应可能是：“这些我早就知道了”、“太枯燥了”或者“我能做得更好”。在这种情况下，请保持谦逊，记住谁是专家，并听从他的指导。这样做绝对值得。

#↩
Rule 38
规则38

Find out the implicit rules

找出隐含规则

On your first day at your new job, your boss will likely enumerate your responsibilities. Perhaps, he will even give you a written list of tasks. During the months that follow, you put your heart and soul into fulfilling them to the best of your abilities, motivated by the possibility of earning a promotion.

在你新工作的第一天，你的老板很可能会列举你的职责。或许，他还会给你一份书面的任务清单。在接下来的几个月里，你全心全意地尽职尽责地完成这些任务，希望能获得晋升。

Then, one day, your colleague gets promoted instead. “Why?” you might wonder in disbelief. You were clearly better than him at the tasks in your list of duties. It must have been office politics, you might think. Or perhaps, the boss played favorites. Either way, you get frustrated.

然后，有一天，你的同事却升职了。“为什么？”你可能会难以置信地问。你明明比他更胜任自己的工作。你或许会想，这一定是办公室政治作祟。又或许，老板偏袒了某些人。不管怎样，你都感到很沮丧。

However, the chances are that your boss thought it was a fair decision. He promoted the one who demonstrated being a better candidate. Perhaps, this wasn’t you. Perhaps the list of duties you were given wasn’t the only area where your performance was to be evaluated. Perhaps there were other things to be done that were not written there but you should have known nevertheless.

然而，你的老板很可能认为这是一个公平的决定。他提拔了表现更优秀的候选人。或许，这个人并不是你。或许，你被分配的职责清单并非评估你绩效的唯一标准。或许还有其他未列明但你理应知晓的事情需要完成。

You might think it is unfair to be evaluated on criteria you weren’t aware of. However, it can be unfair only if you believe that the rules of the “game” of success must be revealed at the beginning of the game. Regardless of what you might believe, this is not a given. In fact, one of the rules of the game is that you have to discover its rules.

你或许会觉得，根据你事先毫不知情的标准来评判自己是不公平的。然而，只有当你认为成功的“游戏”规则必须在游戏开始时就全部揭晓时，这才会显得不公平。无论你的想法如何，这都不是理所当然的。事实上，游戏规则之一就是你必须自己去发现它。

In other words, it is one of your tasks to discover what your implicit tasks are – the untold ones. And similarly, it is a rule that you have to discover the rules.

换句话说，你的任务之一就是发现你那些隐性的任务——那些未被言明的任务。同样，你也必须发现规则。

You might refuse to acknowledge the above. After all, most people act as if it weren’t true. Feel free to do the same. But do not complain if, later, things do not go as you expected.

你或许会拒绝承认上述事实。毕竟，大多数人都会装作事不关己。你也可以这样做。但如果日后事情没有如你所愿，就不要抱怨了。

ACTION:

行动：

Schedule on your calendar some actions whose results would help you discover the implicit rules of the career you chose. This could include reading books, meeting senior colleagues, etc.

在日程安排中安排一些活动，这些活动的结果将有助于你发现所选职业的潜在规则。这些活动可以包括阅读书籍、会见资深同事等等。

Then, take those actions as you scheduled them. And if you find the implicit rules still elude you, consider asking a mentor – someone who has played that game before.

然后，按照计划执行这些行动。如果你发现自己仍然不明白其中的隐含规则，不妨向一位导师请教——一位曾经参与过类似游戏的人。

#↩
Rule 39
规则39

You will regret not sharing
你会后悔没有分享
more than sharing
比分享更多

When I started writing, I did not share my work with anyone. “It isn’t perfect yet” and “it is not relevant to them” were the two most common justifications I gave myself.

我刚开始写作的时候，从不跟任何人分享我的作品。“它还不完美”和“它跟他们无关”是我给自己找的两个最常见的理由。

In that period, my writing improved very slowly, if at all.

在那段时间里，我的写作水平几乎没有提高，进步非常缓慢。

Then, I began sharing my work – even if it wasn’t perfect, and even if it wasn’t relevant. Suddenly, my writing improved. It has kept improving ever since.

然后，我开始分享我的作品——即使它们并不完美，甚至与主题无关。突然间，我的写作水平提高了。而且从那以后，我的写作水平一直在不断提高。

The mere fact of knowing that my work would be shared with others made my writing better and more relevant to my audience. Moreover, sharing my work would generate feedback. That improved my writing skills and increased my confidence.

仅仅是知道我的作品会被分享，就让我写作水平提高，文章也更贴近读者。此外，分享作品还能获得反馈，这不仅提升了我的写作技巧，也增强了我的自信心。

Always share your work. Choose your audience to make sure it’s relevant to them (you don’t want to punish your readers’ attention; you want to reward it). Then, get your work out there.

一定要分享你的作品。选择目标受众，确保作品与他们相关（你不想浪费读者的注意力，而是要让他们觉得你的作品有意义）。然后，把你的作品发布出去。

The more you share, the better you get.

分享越多，进步越大。

I do not regret ever having shared any of my works. I do regret, however, having waited so long before sharing them.

我不后悔分享过我的作品。但我后悔的是，我等待了这么久才分享它们。

The reason I did not show my work? Narcissism. I cared more about what my work said about me than about the work itself. Therefore, my work was mediocre, and I got stuck there. There is no way to achieve excellence without feedback, and collecting useful feedback requires caring about the work more than oneself.

我为什么不展示自己的作品？因为自恋。我更在意作品反映出的自我形象，而不是作品本身。因此，我的作品平庸无奇，我也止步于此。没有反馈，就无法达到卓越；而要获得有用的反馈，就需要对作品本身的关注胜过对自身的关注。

ACTION:

行动：

Whatever your craft, find something that can be shared and valuable to others.

无论你从事什么行业，都要找到一些可以与他人分享、对他人有价值的东西。

It could be something you could write on your blog, an email you could send to your friends, customers, or colleagues, something you could draw, paint, or cook, something you could teach face-to-face…

它可以是你在博客上写的东西，你可以发给朋友、客户或同事的电子邮件，你可以画画、烹饪，也可以面对面地教一些东西……

Then, set yourself a regular schedule to perform the sharing activity – at least once a month, better, once a week.

然后，给自己制定一个定期进行分享活动的计划——至少每月一次，最好每周一次。

Do not worry about your craft being perfect before sharing it. Even for masters, their craft never exceeds 90% perfection, at least in their eyes. Even if they work one more week on it, it will still only be 90% perfect. There is no such thing as 100% perfect. Perfect is like the horizon. As you move towards it, it moves further away. You never get there.

不要担心你的作品在分享前是否完美。即使是大师，他们的作品也永远不会超过90%的完美度，至少在他们自己看来是这样。即使他们再花一周时间打磨，作品也仍然只有90%的完美。世上没有100%的完美。完美就像地平线，你越是靠近它，它就越是远离你，你永远也到不了那里。

Finally, stick to your schedule. The first time will be both terrifying and terrific. But it will be worth it, just for the feeling of liberation that you will feel the day after having done that.

最后，一定要坚持你的计划。第一次尝试既会让人害怕又会让人兴奋。但这一切都是值得的，仅仅为了第二天那种解脱的感觉。

If you can stick to your schedule for at least four sharing sessions, I guarantee your craft will improve.

如果你能坚持参加至少四次分享会，我保证你的技艺会有所提高。

#↩

Get help

获取帮助

Rules 40 to 46

规则 40 至 46

Whenever I asked for help for the right thing, the universe provided. Whenever the universe didn’t, it meant I was asking for the wrong thing.

每当我向宇宙寻求正确的帮助时，宇宙都会回应。而当宇宙没有回应时，则意味着我寻求的并非正确的帮助。

In this chapter, I will describe how to ask for help effectively. Nevertheless, do not forget the above. No amount of help will do anything for you if you are asking for it to avoid doing the work that has to be done.

本章我将介绍如何有效地寻求帮助。但是，请记住以上几点：如果你寻求帮助是为了逃避必须完成的工作，那么再多的帮助也无济于事。

Only ask for help for you to be able to accomplish the work that has to be done.

只有在你需要完成特定工作时才寻求帮助。

Rule 40

规则40

Build a reputation for not wasting time

建立不浪费时间的良好声誉

Building a reputation for wasting time is the easiest way to ensure no one will help you – Sean Rose

给人留下浪费时间的印象，是确保没人愿意帮助你的最简单方法——肖恩·罗斯

Most people love to give advice. These people also hate if such advice is not followed. They might have helped you for free, but they did not help you for nothing. Not following their advice would deprive them of the personal satisfaction of having been helpful.

大多数人都乐于给人提建议。如果别人不听取他们的建议，他们也会感到很失望。他们或许是免费帮助你的，但他们的帮助并非毫无意义。不听取他们的建议会让他们失去帮助他人的成就感。

Here are the four rules of asking for help:

以下是寻求帮助的四条规则：

1. If you ask someone to help you achieve some result, and they do help you, make damn sure that you achieve that result. You do not want them to feel like their advice was useless.

1. 如果你请别人帮忙达成某个目标，而他们也确实帮了你，那就一定要确保你最终达成目标。你肯定不想让他们觉得自己的建议毫无用处。

2. Never ask a person for a second bit of help before having shown you made use of the first bit. Demonstrate you’re not wasting their time.

2. 在证明你已经充分利用了第一次帮助之前，千万不要向别人寻求第二次帮助。要让他们看到你没有浪费他们的时间。

3. Ask people for help that only the y can provide. People like to feel important and give a unique contribution. They hate being asked to do someone else’s job. If you really must ask for a form of help that anyone can provide, at least have the courtesy of making clear that their contribution would feel unique to you. Also, never ask anything you could have googled.

3. 只向那些只有他们才能提供的帮助寻求帮助。人们都喜欢被重视，并渴望做出独特的贡献。他们讨厌被要求去做别人的工作。如果你真的需要寻求任何人都能提供的帮助，至少要礼貌地表明，他们的贡献对你而言是独一无二的。此外，永远不要问那些你完全可以在网上搜索到的问题。

4. If you ask someone for advice, be prepared to follow it. Of course, it doesn’t mean that you should follow anyone’s advice. It means that, before asking for advice, you should vet the person you’re asking for advice to ensure that they will provide advice that is actually good for you . For example, probing whether their values and incentives are aligned with yours and ensuring that they have a complete picture of your situation. Then, once you’ve decided that a particular person is the right one to ask for advice, do them and yourself a favor and follow what they will prescribe. Otherwise, why ask for advice in the first place? (You were looking for advice that is good for you, right? Not advice that you would like, right?)

4. 如果你向别人寻求建议，就要做好接受建议的准备。当然，这并不意味着你应该接受任何人的建议。而是说，在寻求建议之前，你应该先了解一下对方，确保他们提供的建议真正对你有益。例如，探究他们的价值观和动机是否与你一致，并确保他们全面了解你的情况。然后，一旦你确定某个人是合适的咨询对象，为了他们也为了你自己，请采纳他们的建议。否则，你当初又何必寻求建议呢？（你想要的是对你有益的建议，对吗？而不是你喜欢听的建议，对吗？）

ACTION:

行动：

Who can you ask for help? What can you ask them?

你可以向谁寻求帮助？你可以问他们什么问题？

#↩
Rule 41
规则 41

Get good at sending cold emails

学会如何发送陌生开发邮件

A “cold email” is an unsolicited request you send to someone you do not know. It is one of the most underused and most “bang for your back” instruments to generate the support you need to achieve your professional or social goals.

“陌生邮件”是指你主动发送给陌生人的请求。它是最容易被忽视，但又最有效的工具之一，可以帮助你获得实现职业或社交目标所需的支持。

Of course, I’m not talking about spam emails or selfish demands for something of high material value. Instead, I am talking about asking for introductions or advice, proposing partnerships, or asking for something that would be a small inconvenience for the donor but of great value to you.

当然，我说的不是垃圾邮件或自私地索要高价值的物品。我指的是请求引荐或建议、提议合作，或者请求一些对捐赠者来说可能有点不方便但对你来说价值很大的东西。

If you have an ambitious goal, a well-targeted cold email might get you there faster than doing it all by yourself. Hence the importance of learning to write great cold emails and, well, vanquishing the fear of sending them out.

如果你有一个远大的目标，一封精心撰写的陌生开发邮件或许比单打独斗更快地助你达成目标。因此，学习如何撰写优秀的陌生开发邮件，以及克服发送邮件的恐惧至关重要。

Here are some characteristics of a good cold email:
以下是一些优秀陌生开发邮件的特点：
- It is personal. Your email wouldn’t make sense if you copied/pasted the text and sent it to someone else just by changing the recipient’s name.
- 个性化。如果您只是复制粘贴邮件内容，更改收件人姓名就发送给其他人，那您的邮件就失去了意义。
- It goes to the point without wasting the recipient’s time.
- 直奔主题，不浪费收件人的时间。
- It is actionable. If the recipient wants to help, the next step is evident and frictionless.
- 可操作。如果收件人想要提供帮助，下一步操作清晰明了，操作过程也十分便捷。
- It is risk-free. If the recipient wants to help, they can do so with no risk.
- 无风险。如果收件人想要提供帮助，他们可以零风险地进行。
- It is impactful. If the recipient wants to help, something good will happen – either to them or to those that your project will impact positively.
- 有影响力。如果收件人想要提供帮助，将会发生一些好事——无论是对他们自己，还是对您的项目将产生积极影响的人。
- It is well written. You should spend at least 15 minutes, probably 30, researching the recipient, ensuring that they are the right person to help you, writing the email, ensuring it covers the points above, proofreading it, editing it for brevity, and sending it. Never copy/paste text.
- 文笔流畅。你至少应该花15分钟，最好是30分钟，来研究收件人，确保他们是能帮到你的合适人选，然后撰写邮件，确保邮件内容涵盖以上要点，校对邮件，精简内容，最后发送。切勿复制粘贴文本。

ACTION:

行动：

Pick a goal of yours, preferably one that, if successful, will have a positive impact on others.

选择一个你自己的目标，最好是那种如果成功，会对他人产生积极影响的目标。

Then, ask yourself if there’s any form of external help that could help you achieve that goal faster or impact more people – for example, an introduction, a personal connection, a piece of advice, etc.

然后，问问自己是否有任何形式的外部帮助可以帮助你更快地实现目标或影响更多的人——例如，介绍、建立人脉、提供建议等等。

Afterward, think about who could be uniquely positioned to give you that piece of help. Then, research them and validate that they are a good fit.

之后，想想谁可能具备独特的优势，能够为你提供所需的帮助。然后，对他们进行调查，确认他们是否合适。

Finally, write them an email covering all the points described on the previous page.

最后，给他们写一封电子邮件，内容涵盖上一页描述的所有要点。

If they help you, great!

如果他们能帮到你，那就太好了！

If they decline respectfully, also great! It probably means that your email was crafted well enough to deserve a reply – they just could not help you, perhaps for a reason that doesn’t have anything to do with you. Just ask someone else.

如果他们礼貌地拒绝了，那也很好！这可能意味着你的邮件写得足够好，值得回复——他们只是帮不上忙，也许原因与你无关。那就再找其他人问问吧。

But if they do not even reply, you should revisit how you’re writing cold emails. Perhaps yours was too long? Too impersonal? Too cumbersome to act upon?

但如果他们连回复都没有，你就应该重新审视一下你的陌生开发邮件的写作方式。也许你的邮件太长了？太没有人情味了？或者太繁琐，让人难以采取行动？

Research another person worth asking for help, craft a better email, and send it out. If you genuinely care about being a person of value worth helping and ask in a way that makes the other person feel good about helping you, you will soon receive the help you seek.

寻找其他值得求助的人，精心撰写一封更得体的邮件，然后发送出去。如果你真心希望自己成为一个有价值的人，值得帮助，并且以一种让对方感到乐于助人的方式提出请求，你很快就会得到你想要的帮助。

Just make sure you write an email worth being replied to.

务必确保你写的是一封值得回复的邮件。

#↩
Rule 42
规则 42

Listen without projecting your worldview

倾听时不要强加自己的世界观。

When I was in my early 20s, I read an article about “how to listen.” It contained advice such as “nod frequently” and “do not look at your mobile phone.”

我二十出头的时候，读过一篇关于“如何倾听”的文章。文章里有一些建议，比如“经常点头”和“不要看手机”。

That’s good advice, but that’s not “how to listen.” That’s “how to look like you are listening.”

这是个好建议，但这并不是“如何倾听”，而是“如何看起来像在倾听”。

Proper listening is about abstaining from using our worldviews to interpret what the speaker is saying. It consists of accepting everything our interlocutor says and, if something seems surprising or false, assuming that we might lack context and asking ourselves, “what might cause them to say that?”

正确的倾听在于避免用我们自身的世界观去解读说话者所说的话。它包括接受对话者所说的一切，如果某些内容听起来令人惊讶或不真实，则假设我们可能缺乏背景信息，并问自己：“是什么原因导致他们这么说？”

Proper listening involves offering our interlocutors a blank canvas on which to paint their thoughts – not painting them ourselves.

正确的倾听方式是给对话者提供一张空白的画布，让他们自由地描绘自己的想法——而不是我们自己去替他们描绘。

Proper listening involves withholding our judgment.

真正的倾听在于克制自己的判断。

ACTION:

行动：

The next time you find yourself listening to someone, withhold judgment.

下次当你倾听别人讲话时，请不要妄下评判。

Assume they are right, and you lack some context.

假设他们是对的，而你缺乏一些背景信息。

If you ask questions, never phrase them as “explain to me why you are not wrong”; instead, “explain to me how you feel (and why).”

如果你要问问题，千万不要这样问：“请解释一下你为什么没错”，而应该这样问：“请解释一下你的感受（以及原因）。”

If you manage to do this genuinely, you will instantly become one of the top listeners they have ever met. Your interlocutor will likely mention how “few people listened to them this way.” Enjoy the moment and enjoy your friend’s thoughts. They might be just as beautiful as yours.

如果你能真心实意地做到这一点，你立刻就会成为他们遇到过的最棒的倾听者之一。你的谈话对象很可能会说“很少有人这样认真地听他们说话”。享受这一刻，聆听你朋友的想法。它们或许和你的想法一样美好。

#↩
Rule 43
规则43

Listen to the old

听听老歌

If someone came back from the future and told me that in 200 years, between the bicycle and the car, only one would still be in use, I would bet on the bicycle.

如果有人从未来回到现在，告诉我200年后，自行车和汽车中只有一种会继续使用，我会赌自行车会继续使用。

At the moment of writing, the bicycle has been in use for about double the amount of time as the car (roughly two centuries for the bicycle and one century for the car). It is double its age and has therefore double its life expectancy. This is called “The Lindy Effect”: the older something not perishable, the longer it is expected to be relevant. (Nassim Nicholas Taleb explains this effect in his book, “Antifragile.”)

截至撰写本文时，自行车的使用时间大约是汽车的两倍（自行车大约有两个世纪，汽车大约有一个世纪）。它的年龄是汽车的两倍，因此预期寿命也是汽车的两倍。这被称为“林迪效应”：对于不易腐烂的事物，其历史越悠久，人们预期它还能保持相关性的时间就越长。（纳西姆·尼古拉斯·塔勒布在他的著作《反脆弱》中解释了这种效应。）

There is a rational explanation for the Lindy Effect. The longer something has survived, the fewer assumptions it relies upon. The bicycle is 200 years old. It does not rely on petrol or electronics (younger technologies). There are fewer ways in which a bicycle can break than a car. Moreover, it is easier to repair and under fewer assumptions (a bicycle does not necessarily need parts to be shipped from the manufacturer as certain cars do; also, the share of the population able to repair a bicycle is much larger than that able to fix a car).

林迪效应有合理的解释。事物存在的时间越长，其所依赖的假设就越少。自行车已有200年的历史。它不依赖汽油或电子设备（较新的技术）。自行车的故障方式比汽车少得多。此外，自行车更容易维修，而且所依赖的假设也更少（自行车不像某些汽车那样需要从制造商那里运送零件；而且，能够修理自行车的人口比例远高于能够修理汽车的人口比例）。

Similarly, a movie that has been popular for a week might have been so for two reasons: either it is a masterpiece, or it is relevant to the now (for example, it touches on a “hot” topic). Let’s say that only 1% of movies popular during their first week are masterpieces. It follows that 99% of movies popular in their first week are likely to be fads. Conversely, a movie that has been popular for a decade cannot have been popular just because it touched on a hot topic. It must have been a masterpiece, something relevant regardless of its context. Therefore, it is likely to stay relevant even over the next ten years, when the context will have changed again.

同样，一部电影上映一周后走红可能有两个原因：要么它是杰作，要么它与当下息息相关（例如，它触及了某个“热门”话题）。假设首周走红的电影中只有1%是杰作，那么99%的首周走红电影很可能只是昙花一现。相反，一部持续走红十年的电影不可能仅仅因为触及了热门话题而走红。它一定是杰作，无论时代背景如何，它都具有现实意义。因此，即使未来十年时代背景再次发生变化，它也可能依然保持其意义。

To sum it up, the older something is, the more it will probably be relevant in the future. But why would this matter to you?

总而言之，事物越古老，未来就越有可能具有相关性。但这跟你有什么关系呢？

It matters because it means the following. When someone old says something you disagree with, perhaps it is because it’s wrong, or maybe because it applies to a broader context than the limited one you have experienced so far . You want to take the latter possibility into account. Older people have experienced more. You should always at least consider the idea that the present context might revert to what they experienced. You shouldn’t rule out what has been experienced by someone else. It might happen again.

这很重要，因为它意味着以下几点。当一位长者说出你不认同的话时，或许是因为他说的是错的，或许是因为他所处的境况比你目前所经历的更为广阔。你应该考虑到后一种可能性。老年人经历更丰富。你应该始终至少考虑一下，当前的境况可能会与他们曾经经历过的类似。你不应该排除他人曾经经历过的事情。同样的事情可能会再次发生。

An experienced fund manager having invested for 30 years saw two financial crashes; an analyst who has only been in the business for five years might never have seen one. The younger analyst’s data sample is much smaller. When the older manager says that a crash is a possibility to take into account, he is likely to be dismissed by the younger one who has never experienced a crisis.

一位拥有30年投资经验的资深基金经理经历过两次金融危机；而一位从业仅5年的分析师可能从未经历过。年轻分析师的数据样本量要小得多。当年长的基金经理指出金融危机是一种需要考虑的可能性时，年轻的分析师很可能因为从未经历过危机而对此不屑一顾。

Don’t make the same mistake. Before dismissing the advice of an elder just because “the times have changed,” ask yourself, “could they change back?”

不要犯同样的错误。在仅仅因为“时代变了”就否定长辈的建议之前，请问问自己，“时代会变回去吗？”

ACTION:

行动：

What is one piece of advice that someone older than you gave that you dismissed? What are the assumptions under which he gave you that advice? Could such assumptions become true for you one day?

曾经有一位比你年长的人给你一条建议，但你却置之不理。他给你这条建议是基于哪些假设？这些假设有一天会变成现实吗？

#↩
Rule 44
规则44

Do not trust anyone who insists on being part of the solution

不要相信任何坚持要成为解决方案一部分的人。

If a doctor insists that you need surgery, they are (perhaps) doing their job. However, if they insist that they must be the ones performing the surgery, then they might be thinking about their wallet’s welfare more than your own.

如果医生坚持认为你需要做手术，他们（或许）是在尽职尽责。但是，如果他们坚持必须由他们来做手术，那么他们可能更关心的是自己的钱包，而不是你的健康。

If someone offers to solve a problem of yours, great! However, if they insist on being part of the solution, beware! They might be trying to help themselves rather than you.

如果有人主动提出帮你解决问题，那太好了！但是，如果他们坚持要参与解决方案，就要小心了！他们可能只是想帮自己，而不是帮你。

ACTION:

行动：

The next time someone proposes a solution that would benefit them, consider acknowledging the solution but proposing that someone else execute it. For example, if they are doctors recommending a surgery, thank them for the advice and mention that you will get the surgery at another hospital.

下次如果有人提出对他们有利的解决方案，不妨表示感谢，但建议由其他人来执行。例如，如果是医生建议做手术，感谢他们的建议，并说明你会去另一家医院做手术。

Then, observe their reaction. Do they insist on being the ones operating you? If so, you might want to consider what their real incentives are.

然后，观察他们的反应。他们是否坚持要由他们来操控你？如果是这样，你或许应该考虑一下他们真正的动机是什么。

#↩
Rule 45
规则45

Trust incentives rather than people

信任激励机制而非人

Every single time I got screwed up was because I trusted someone rather than trusting their incentives.

我每次出差错都是因为我信任了别人，而不是信任他们的动机。

Sometimes, I got screwed by people good at faking trustworthiness. For example, I knew that car mechanics make money from repairing cars and sometimes insist on providing services that are not needed, but I trusted the technician who lived on my street. I thought he was different. I thought he was trustworthy. He wasn’t. He might have looked different, but his incentives were the same as other car mechanics. The chances are that he might have just been acting nicely towards me to get more business.

有时候，我会被那些擅长伪装信任的人坑骗。比如说，我知道修车工靠修车赚钱，有时会坚持提供一些根本不需要的服务，但我信任住在我家附近的那个修车工。我以为他不一样，以为他值得信任。结果并非如此。他或许看起来与众不同，但他的动机和其他修车工一样。很有可能他只是为了招揽生意才对我这么客气。

Of course, this doesn’t mean that all car mechanics are dishonest. It just means that unless you have proof that a given car mechanic is honest, it is worth assuming he isn’t, because his incentives are the opposite of yours.

当然，这并不意味着所有修车工都不诚实。这只是意味着，除非你有证据证明某个修车工诚实，否则最好假设他不诚实，因为他的利益与你截然相反。

Unless you and they both live in the same tiny village where everyone knows everyone else, for example. In this case, the nature of repeated interactions is such that their incentives are to act nicely towards another community member. (Unless they are the only technicians.)

除非你和他们都住在同一个小村庄里，村里人人都互相认识。在这种情况下，反复的互动会促使他们友好对待其他村民。（除非他们是村里仅有的技术人员。）

Other times, I got screwed by people who had been trustworthy in the context of previous interactions, but whose context changed, and their behavior followed. In other words, in the past, they acted trustworthy because their old incentives dictated that it was beneficial for them to do so. When their incentives changed, so did their behavior. For example, a good friend of mine joined an investment company after graduation and tried to sell me some terrible financial products. He was trustworthy when we were both university students. However, when his job depended on himself selling products to clients, he began to screw people. (To be clear, I do not believe that all brokers screw people. I think that those who need to sell crap products do. Those who have a product good enough to call each sell a “win-win” or enough financial security to refuse to sell bad products might behave ethically.)

有时候，我会被一些在以往交往中值得信赖的人欺骗，但随着情况的变化，他们的行为也随之改变。换句话说，过去他们之所以值得信赖，是因为之前的利益驱动着他们这样做对他们有利。当他们的利益发生变化时，他们的行为也随之改变。例如，我的一位好朋友毕业后加入了一家投资公司，试图向我推销一些糟糕的金融产品。我们还是大学生的时候，他很值得信赖。然而，当他的工作需要他向客户推销产品时，他就开始坑害别人。（需要澄清的是，我并不认为所有经纪人都会坑害别人。我认为那些需要推销劣质产品的人才会这样做。而那些拥有足够好的产品，能够实现“双赢”销售，或者拥有足够的经济实力拒绝推销劣质产品的人，他们的行为可能更符合道德规范。）

Long story short: if a person’s incentives suggest they should not be trusted, do not trust them.

简而言之：如果一个人的动机表明他不可信，那就不要相信他。

This does not imply “do not interact with them.” It just means that you should think about the ways they can screw you and make sure you’re not too vulnerable if they do that.

这并不意味着“不要和他们来往”。这只是意味着你应该考虑他们可能会用哪些方式坑害你，并确保万一他们那样做，你不会太容易受到伤害。

ACTION:

行动：

Think about a person you interacted with recently whose incentives are opposite yours.

想想你最近接触过的某个人，他的动机与你相反。

The next time you interact with them, think: is there a way to align their risks with yours? For example, if they try to sell you some product or service, can you ask for a written warranty? If they do not want to do that, what does it tell you about them?

下次与他们互动时，想想：有没有办法让他们的风险与你的风险保持一致？例如，如果他们试图向你推销某种产品或服务，你能要求他们提供书面保证吗？如果他们不愿意这样做，这说明了什么？

#↩
Rule 46
规则46

Trust actions rather than words

信任靠行动而非言语。

The old adage goes, “do not trust people’s words but their actions.” This is sound advice, and most people know to apply it to others. But few apply it to themselves. Instead, we should treat our unconscious as we do with other people: trust its actions, not its words.

俗话说，“不要相信人的言语，而要相信他们的行动。” 这句忠告不无道理，大多数人也懂得如何将其应用于他人。然而，很少有人能将其应用于自身。事实上，我们应该像对待他人一样对待自己的潜意识：相信它的行动，而非它的言语。

It’s not that our unconscious lies or deceives. It’s just that our brain is made of multiple regions, 18 and the one responsible for conscious thinking is not the one responsible for deciding what our muscles will do next. We cannot notice if the two diverge observing our thoughts alone. This is because conscious thoughts are the domain of the conscious part of our brain only, and at most, it can guess what the rest of the brain thinks. Therefore, the only way to listen to the rest of our brain is to observe our feelings and actions.

并非我们的潜意识会说谎或欺骗我们。而是我们的大脑由多个区域组成，负责意识思考的区域并不负责决定我们肌肉的下一步动作。仅仅观察我们的想法，我们无法察觉这两者之间的差异。这是因为意识思考仅限于我们大脑的意识部分，它最多只能猜测大脑其他部分的想法。因此，了解我们大脑其他部分想法的唯一途径就是观察我们的感受和行为。

ACTION:

行动：

Imagine that in your skull, instead of our brain, there were two people. One is you, the conscious you that is reading these lines in his mind. You are the one thinking, planning, and strategizing. The other one – your unconscious – controls the levers that activate your muscles and cannot speak. The only way to know what it thinks is to observe its actions. What do you think its character is? What does it long for? What is it afraid of doing?

想象一下，你的头骨里不是大脑，而是两个人。一个是你，有意识的你，正在脑海中阅读这些文字。是你思考、计划、制定策略。另一个——你的潜意识——控制着激活你肌肉的杠杆，它不会说话。了解它想法的唯一方法就是观察它的行为。你认为它的性格是怎样的？它渴望什么？它害怕做什么？

Is there any way in which you can help your unconscious instead of asking it for help as usual?

有没有什么方法可以帮助你的潜意识，而不是像往常一样向它寻求帮助？

#↩

Lead

带领

Rules 47 to 51

规则 47 至 51

Everyone is required at some point in their life to lead. Managers and politicians, sure, but also teachers, parents, salespeople, engineers proposing a new idea, citizens requesting some change, and so on.

每个人一生中都会在某个阶段需要承担领导角色。管理者和政治家当然需要，但教师、家长、销售人员、提出新想法的工程师、要求变革的公民等等也都需要。

It turns out that to lead, you do not need authority or charisma. Instead, you need initiative and consistency.

事实证明，领导力并不需要权威或魅力，而是需要主动性和持之以恒。

Initiative is the capacity to take action and responsibility even when no one else does. And consistency is the ability never to contradict your words and values with your actions. These two are both necessary and sufficient for leadership. 19

主动性是指在无人采取行动和承担责任时也能挺身而出的能力。而一致性是指言行一致，始终言行一致。这两点对于领导力而言都是必要且充分的。

This chapter will help make you a better leader by developing your ability to take the initiative and to be consistent.

本章将通过培养你的主动性和一致性能力，帮助你成为更优秀的领导者。

Rule 47
规则47

Lead with action, not words

以行动而非言语为先。

In movies, motivational speeches can rally a group of people to take on great challenges. In real life, however, no one will take action on your motivational speech unless you have a long history of personal undertakings yourself.

在电影里，励志演讲可以激励一群人去迎接巨大的挑战。然而在现实生活中，除非你本人有着长期的行动记录，否则你的励志演讲不会有人付诸行动。

What people rally around, instead, is action. If they see you do something, they might do the same. Hence, lead with action, not words.

人们真正支持的是行动。如果你做了某件事，他们可能也会效仿。因此，要以行动而非言辞来领导。

…

Why don’t people take action? Sometimes, they believe that the action is unlikely to bring anything good. However, most often, the problem is that although they do think that the action will bring something good, they do not think it is worth the effort. For example, as a teenager, I did believe that cleaning my room would be beneficial; I just didn’t believe it was worth the effort.

为什么人们不采取行动？有时，他们认为行动不太可能带来任何好处。然而，大多数情况下，问题在于尽管他们认为行动会带来好处，但却觉得不值得付出努力。例如，我十几岁的时候，确实认为打扫房间会有好处；但我就是觉得不值得。

You, as a leader, will find it extremely difficult to convince someone that a result is worth the effort. People won’t trust your words. However, they might trust your actions. This is because your actions are a costly signal that you truly believe that what you want them to do is worth the effort.

作为领导者，你会发现很难说服别人相信付出努力是值得的。人们不会相信你的言语，但他们或许会相信你的行动。这是因为你的行动本身就是一个重要的信号，表明你真心相信你希望他们做的事情是值得的。

If you want to drive change, lead with action, not words.

如果你想推动变革，就要以行动而非言辞来领导。

ACTION:

行动：

Think about one time you tried to convince others to take action but failed. Were you practicing your own advice? If so, did they see you practicing your own advice? If they didn’t, that’s your bottleneck. Start with visible action.

想想你曾经试图说服别人采取行动却失败的经历。你当时是否身体力行地践行了自己的建议？如果是，他们是否看到了你的行动？如果没有，那就是你的瓶颈所在。从可见的行动开始。

#↩
Rule 48
规则48

Communicate your values
通过接受不便之处来传达你的价值观
by embracing their inconveniences

My father taught me the importance of honesty. However, he didn’t teach it by lecturing me or behaving honestly when easy to do so – for example, by not stealing from shops, where he could be easily arrested. Instead, he taught it by behaving honestly when it was hard to do it. For instance, looking for the owner of the wallet he found on the street instead of pocketing the money within.

父亲教会了我诚实的重要性。然而，他并没有用说教的方式教导我，也没有在容易做到的时候——比如不去商店偷东西（那样很容易被抓）——就身体力行地践行诚实。相反，他是在困难的时候以身作则，身体力行地教导我诚实。例如，他在街上捡到钱包后，没有把里面的钱据为己有，而是先寻找失主。

There are two lessons here. The first is that values are not taught by acting accordingly when it’s easy but when it’s hard to do so. Of course, because being law-abiding in front of a cop is an expression of common sense, not of honesty.

这里有两个教训。第一，价值观的培养并非在于顺境时的行为规范，而在于逆境时的行为规范。当然，因为在警察面前守法是常识的体现，而非诚实的体现。

The second lesson is that we can communicate values by embracing their inconveniences. This is because values carry short-term costs and long-term benefits. By willfully incurring their short-term costs, we signal that we believe that they are, in fact, investments. For example, “I act honestly even when inconvenient because I believe that honesty brings long-term gains.” Or “I know that honesty isn’t a switch that we can turn on and off at will; so, I behave honestly today even though I could get away with it so that I am more likely to behave honestly the time it will bring dividends.”

第二个教训是，我们可以通过接受价值观带来的不便来传达这些价值观。这是因为价值观会带来短期成本和长期收益。通过自愿承担这些短期成本，我们表明我们相信它们实际上是一种投资。例如，“即使会带来不便，我也会诚实行事，因为我相信诚实会带来长期的收益。”或者“我知道诚实不是一个可以随意开关的开关；所以，即使我今天可以逃避惩罚，我也会诚实行事，这样在诚实能够带来回报的时候，我更有可能继续诚实行事。”

ACTION:

行动：

The next time you want to teach someone a value, do not focus too much on giving a great speech. Instead, find ways to take a costly action that shows your belief that acting accordingly to values is a long-term investment – and that you expect others to make that investment too. Do not manufacture opportunities to show this; simply wait for them to happen, and when they do, act accordingly.

下次你想向别人传授某种价值观时，不要过于注重发表一番精彩的演讲。相反，要找到机会采取一些代价高昂的行动，以此表明你相信践行价值观是一项长期的投资——并且你也希望其他人做出同样的投资。不要刻意制造机会来证明这一点；只需静待机会出现，一旦机会来临，就采取相应的行动。

#↩
Rule 49
规则49

Delegate results, not methods

委托结果，而非方法

Imagine asking an employee or a contractor to fulfill a task for you. You give them the details of how they should proceed. Then, you send them to work. One month later, you are not satisfied with the results. They reply: “Not my fault, boss. I did just as you said.”

想象一下，你让员工或承包商为你完成一项任务。你详细地告诉他们应该如何进行，然后派他们去工作。一个月后，你对结果不满意。他们回复说：“这不是我的错，老板。我完全按照你说的做了。”

By detailing the steps to follow, you shifted the goal from obtaining a satisfactory result to following an instruction list.

通过详细说明步骤，你将目标从获得满意的结果转变为遵循操作指南。

The more you delegate the methods to be used, the less your employee or contractor is accountable for the results. 20

你越是委派工作方法，你的员工或承包商就越不需要对结果负责。

The solution is to restrain yourself from telling your employees or contractors how a task is to be done. 21 Only tell them the result you want. Paint a detailed picture of what a successfully completed task looks like, 22 but not how completing it looks like.

解决方法是，不要告诉员工或承包商任务的具体完成方式。 21 只告诉他们你想要的结果。详细描述任务成功完成后的样子， 22 但不要告诉他们完成任务的过程。

Delegate the results, not the methods. If you are crystal clear on what successfully completed tasks look like, you will be surprised by the results your employees and contractors will produce.

把结果交给别人，而不是方法。如果你对成功完成的任务有非常清晰的定义，你会对你的员工和承包商最终取得的成果感到惊讶。

ACTION:

行动：

The next time you delegate a task, delegate the result, not the method.

下次委派任务时，请委派结果，而不是方法。

Focus on being crystal clear . Use visual descriptions. Describe how you want the final product to make the observer feel. Validate understanding by asking them to repeat the result to achieve in their own words. 23

务必做到清晰明了。使用视觉描述。描述你希望最终产品带给观察者的感受。通过让他们用自己的语言复述结果来验证他们的理解。

What if your employee is new to the task? Shouldn’t you also explain to them how to perform the task? Yes, you probably should. But be very clear: their work will still be judged on the final result, not on whether they followed the method you suggested.

如果你的员工是第一次接触这项工作呢？你是不是也应该向他们解释如何完成这项任务？是的，你很可能应该这样做。但一定要明确一点：他们的工作最终会根据结果来评判，而不是根据他们是否按照你建议的方法操作。

#↩
Rule 50
规则50

The 20% rule for providing feedback

提供反馈的20%规则

The first way to kill an idea is by criticizing it. “It will never work.”

扼杀一个想法的第一种方法就是批评它。“这绝对行不通。”

The second is by giving a suggestion. For example, “Good idea, but here is how it could be better.”

第二种方法是提出建议。例如，“好主意，但可以这样改进。”

Both are highly demotivating. People are motivated by being the ones bringing an idea to life, rather than by seeing their idea brought to life by someone else. Providing a suggestion that isn’t critical deprives them of the prize of having been the ones solving the problem.

这两种情况都非常打击积极性。人们的动力来自于亲手将想法付诸实践，而不是看到自己的想法被别人实现。提出不具批判性的建议会剥夺他们解决问题的成就感。

Bestselling author Marshall Goldsmith formulated the 20% rule for giving ideas, which I would summarize as follows: “Unless you have a suggestion that brings at least a 20% improvement, shut up.”

畅销书作家马歇尔·戈德史密斯提出了“20%法则”来指导人们提出想法，我将其概括如下：“除非你的建议能带来至少20%的改进，否则就闭嘴。”

If you follow this rule, not only your colleagues and friends will like you much more, but you will also have more successful and motivated associates.

如果你遵循这条规则，不仅你的同事和朋友会更喜欢你，而且你还会拥有更多成功且积极进取的合作伙伴。

ACTION:

行动：

Think about the last time someone gave you a suggestion you didn’t ask for. How did you feel?

想想上一次有人给你提建议，而你并没有要求，你当时是什么感觉？

Now, think about the last time you gave someone a suggestion they didn’t ask for. How do you think they felt?

现在，想想你上一次给别人提建议，而他们并没有要求你提建议的时候。你觉得他们当时是什么感受？

#↩
Rule 51
规则51

Leading requires doing things
that do not scale

领导力需要做一些无法规模化的事情。

Our heart pumps blood into our arteries. But then, the arteries divide into vessels and the vessels into tiny capillaries. Why? Because blood cells can only exchange oxygen with the muscle cells that are close by.

我们的心脏将血液泵入动脉。然后，动脉会分支成血管，血管又会分支成细小的毛细血管。为什么呢？因为血细胞只能与附近的肌肉细胞进行氧气交换。

The same applies to leadership: it requires closeness. People won’t follow someone they do not trust, and trust requires spending time together. I do not mean time spent drinking beers. I mean time spent talking about work or doing work together.

领导力也是如此：它需要亲近感。人们不会追随他们不信任的人，而信任需要花时间相处。我指的不是一起喝酒的时间，而是指一起谈论工作或一起工作的时间。

Similarly, people won’t follow you if they do not trust that you know and understand their problems. This requires closeness too. They need to see you with them. Moreover, you cannot really learn what their problems really are and how they really impact them using information tools that scale, such as reading reports or surveys. These only contain superficial information. Instead, you need to spend time where the people you want to lead spend their work time. Only this way will you really know what’s going on.

同样，如果人们不相信你了解并理解他们的问题，他们就不会追随你。这也需要建立亲密关系。他们需要看到你与他们同在。此外，你无法通过阅读报告或调查等规模化的信息工具真正了解他们的问题所在以及这些问题对他们的真正影响。这些工具只能提供表面信息。相反，你需要花时间与你想要领导的人们一起工作。只有这样，你才能真正了解情况。

You cannot lead by only doing things that scale; you also need to do some things that do not scale.

你不能只做那些可以规模化的事情来领导；你还需要做一些不能规模化的事情。

ACTION:

行动：

Who do you want to lead?

你希望谁来领导？

How can you spend more time with them in the environment you want to lead them? Example: spending your Tuesday mornings at their workplace.

如何才能在你想要领导他们的环境中花更多时间陪伴他们？例如：每周二上午去他们的工作场所。

#↩

Adopt a long-term perspective

采取长远的视角

Rules 52 to 59

规则52至59

Taking one positive, short-term-focused action after another won’t get you very far over the long term. This is because what’s needed to succeed in the long term is never optimal for the short term. Therefore, it doesn’t get done unless special attention is given to it.

一味地采取积极的、着眼于短期利益的行动，从长远来看并不会带来多大进展。这是因为，实现长期成功所需的要素，从来都不是短期内最理想的。因此，除非给予特别的关注，否则这些要素永远无法实现。

Hence the need to adopt a long-term perspective. It’s the only way to get us to take the actions required to get good long-term health, happiness, and life.

因此，我们需要采取长远的眼光。只有这样，我们才能采取必要的行动，从而获得长期的健康、幸福和美好的生活。

This doesn’t mean that our day-to-day should become one of long-term sacrifices – not at all. If we only live for the long-term, we will soon lose motivation, or sink too many efforts into a plan that made sense when we formulated it but isn’t appropriate anymore due to changed circumstances and goals. On the other hand, if we only live for the short term, after a time, we will plateau, and later, we will lack the fundamental ingredients for a good life as adults first and seniors later (because we never built them).

但这并不意味着我们的日常生活就应该变成长期牺牲——完全不是。如果我们只着眼于长远，很快就会失去动力，或者把太多精力投入到一个当初制定时看似合理，但如今却因环境和目标改变而不再适用的计划中。另一方面，如果我们只着眼于短期，一段时间后，我们会停滞不前，最终，我们会缺乏美好生活的基本要素，无论是成年后还是老年时期（因为我们从未真正构建过这些要素）。

Therefore, our day-to-day should be a mix of actions that make sense in the now and actions that only make sense with a longer time horizon.

因此，我们的日常行动应该兼顾当下有意义的行动和从长远角度来看有意义的行动。

This chapter will help you with the latter.

本章将帮助你解决后者的问题。

Rule 52
规则52

Avoid shortcuts

避免走捷径

Sometimes, on our way to success, we are tempted to take shortcuts: to cure the symptoms of our problems with a “quick fix” that leaves the root problem unaddressed.

有时，在通往成功的道路上，我们可能会想要走捷径：用“快速修复”来缓解问题的症状，却忽略了根本问题。

Here are some examples of shortcuts or “quick fixes:” memorizing the contents of a test or presentation, using authority to compel action, lying, omitting, ingurgitating an energy drink, drinking alcohol to “facilitate” social situations, taking painkillers to solve the consequences of behavioral problems (e.g., bad posture) – the list is long.

以下是一些捷径或“快速解决方法”的例子：记住考试或演讲的内容，利用权威强迫他人采取行动，撒谎，隐瞒，一口气喝下能量饮料，喝酒来“促进”社交场合，服用止痛药来解决行为问题（例如，不良姿势）的后果——这样的例子不胜枚举。

The first issue with shortcuts is that they allow you to “borrow” strength. As with any loan, such debt must be repaid. Therefore, it is only useful if the amount borrowed has been invested into a productive asset. (It rarely is, because the kind of person who likes to borrow strength is almost inevitably the kind of person who uses it for consumption rather than production.)

捷径的首要问题在于，它们允许你“借用”精力。如同任何贷款一样，这种债务必须偿还。因此，只有当借来的精力被投资于生产性资产时，捷径才有用。（这种情况很少发生，因为喜欢借用精力的人几乎必然是那种将精力用于消费而非生产的人。）

The second issue with shortcuts is that they reduce the urgency to take resolutive action. Meanwhile, the root problem keeps growing. When, inevitably, the shortcut doesn’t work anymore, the problem will have grown so much that it will look insoluble.

捷径的第二个问题在于，它们会降低采取解决方案的紧迫性。与此同时，根本问题却在不断恶化。当捷径最终失效时，问题已经发展到看似无法解决的地步。

For example, it is a terrible idea to use pills to reduce chronic back pain caused by a lifestyle disorder. Eventually, your body will adapt to the pills to the point that you will need to ingurgitate a few of them to receive any relief, at which point their side effects will wreck your body and mind. The alternative – stopping using them after they become ineffective – will leave you with a worse back pain problem than the one you started with.

例如，用药物来缓解由生活方式疾病引起的慢性背痛是一个糟糕的主意。最终，你的身体会对药物产生耐受性，以至于你需要吞服好几片才能获得缓解，而此时药物的副作用会严重损害你的身心健康。另一种选择——在药物失效后停止服用——只会让你的背痛问题比最初更加严重。

A more effective approach is to say no to shortcuts. By refusing to take shortcuts, you leave yourself with no option but to tackle the root problem.

更有效的办法是拒绝走捷径。拒绝走捷径，你就别无选择，只能着手解决问题的根源。

Great lives are made of tackled problems.

伟大的人生是由解决问题的过程构成的。

ACTION:

行动：

Take a sheet of paper and trace a horizontal line, dividing it into two halves.

取一张纸，画一条水平线，将纸分成两半。

In the bottom half, write down a list of shortcuts or “quick fixes” you took so far.

在下半部分，写下你目前为止采取的捷径或“快速解决方法”清单。

Done?

完毕？

Now, in the top half, write down the following words in big characters: “The list of shortcuts I pledge never to take again.”

现在，在上半部分，用大字写下以下文字：“我发誓再也不会走的捷径清单。”

Finally, pin the list somewhere where you will read it frequently. (If you have no such physical space, take a picture of it with your phone; then, download a to-do list app and add a weekly reminder to look at the list).

最后，把清单贴在你经常会看到的地方。（如果没有这样的地方，可以用手机拍张照片；然后下载一个待办事项应用，设置每周提醒查看清单。）

Inevitably, you will eventually relapse into taking a shortcut. When it happens, don’t be disappointed with yourself. Instead, think: “How should I modify my habits, environment, and incentives so that I will never relapse again?”

你最终难免会再次走捷径。当这种情况发生时，不要对自己失望。相反，你应该思考：“我应该如何改变我的习惯、环境和激励机制，才能确保我永远不会再次走捷径？”

Remember: the first step to growth is to realize that there is no shortcut.

记住：成长的第一步是认识到没有捷径。

#↩
Rule 53
规则53

Solving the root causes of your problems does not cost you time; it gives you time

解决问题的根本原因并不会浪费你的时间；相反，它会为你节省时间。

Every problem has a root cause. For example, you might suffer from chronic back pain due to a sedentary lifestyle. Or you might suffer from stress and late nights at work because you’re not good at prioritizing (including saying “no” to your boss & colleagues 24 ).

每个问题都有其根本原因。例如，你可能因为久坐不动的生活方式而患上慢性背痛。或者，你可能因为不善于安排优先事项（包括对老板和同事说“不”）而承受工作压力和熬夜之苦。

Addressing the symptoms of a problem is faster and easier than addressing its root cause. Therefore, we trick ourselves into believing that if today we solve the symptoms of our problem, perhaps, perhaps , tomorrow its root cause will stop throwing problems at us. It seems rational to try the fastest and easiest way.

解决问题的症状比解决问题的根本原因要快得多也容易得多。因此，我们常常自欺欺人地认为，如果今天解决了问题的症状，或许明天问题的根源就会消失。选择最快捷、最简单的方法似乎合情合理。

It is often a bad idea. Side-stepping the root cause of a problem is not a shortcut but a detour. It’s not how we save time but how we waste time.

这通常是个糟糕的主意。回避问题的根本原因并非捷径，而是绕弯子。这非但不能节省时间，反而会浪费时间。

Addressing a symptom of a problem might only take one minute, whereas solving its root cause might require one hour, but if you face the same problem daily, it will have stolen 6 hours of your life in one year. Much better to roll your sleeves up and solve the root cause directly, ignoring the seemingly urgent problem at hand.

解决问题的表象或许只需一分钟，而找出问题的根源可能需要一小时。但如果你每天都面临同样的问题，一年下来就会浪费你六个小时。与其纠结于眼前看似紧急的问题，不如撸起袖子直接解决根本原因。

Solving the root cause of problems should always be more urgent than solving any problem it produces. This is because addressing the root cause of problems never costs time; instead, it always gives time.

解决问题的根本原因永远比解决由此产生的任何问题都更为紧迫。这是因为解决问题的根本原因从来不会浪费时间；相反，它总是能节省时间。

Remember: feeling stuck in life is a signal that you didn’t acknowledge and address the root cause of your problems yet. Whenever you feel stuck, think: “what have I been avoiding?”

记住：感到生活停滞不前，说明你还没有意识到并解决问题的根源。每当你感到停滞不前时，想想：“我一直在逃避什么？”

ACTION:

行动：

Pick a problem you face at least weekly, which takes time and energy away from other activities. What is its root cause?

选择一个你每周至少会遇到的问题，这个问题会占用你用于其他活动的时间和精力。它的根本原因是什么？

To find out, ask yourself, “If I solve this, could the problem resurface? Why?” Keep asking it until you find a cause for which you are confident that, once you take care of it, the problem won’t come back ever again. That’s the root cause.

为了找到答案，问问自己：“如果我解决了这个问题，它会不会再次出现？为什么？” 反复问自己这个问题，直到找到一个你确信一旦解决，问题就不会再出现的根本原因。这就是问题的根源。

Then, write down what you will do to solve it. For example, while checking my email, I used to lose a few seconds every day going over all the promotions and deals and other spam. The root cause: every time I received one such email, I would archive it (one click) instead of unsubscribing from it (two clicks). Last year, I decided to meticulously unsubscribe from all email lists I did not expressly want to be a part of. The benefit: my inbox is now one-third the size it used to be. I am now much more motivated to read its contents and take action on the emails that require it.
