然后，写下你打算如何解决这个问题。例如，我以前每天查看邮件时，都会浪费几秒钟浏览所有的促销、优惠和其他垃圾邮件。根本原因在于：每次收到这类邮件，我都会把它归档（只需点击一下），而不是取消订阅（需要点击两次）。去年，我决定仔细地取消订阅所有我明确不想加入的邮件列表。好处是：我的收件箱现在只有以前的三分之一大小了。我现在更有动力阅读邮件内容，并处理那些需要处理的邮件。

#↩
Rule 54
规则54

If it’s not sustainable, it didn’t happen

如果它不可持续，那就等于没发生过。

Let me make an example that might or might not apply to you.

我举个例子，这个例子可能适用于你，也可能不适用。

It’s the 1st of January. You realize you’re overweight. You decide to eat more healthily. You start a diet, which lasts two days. Then, you eat normally (i.e., too much) for a few days. On Monday, you start your diet again. You eat healthily. Lunch. At dinner, you already relapsed.

今天是1月1日。你意识到自己超重了。你决定健康饮食。你开始节食，坚持了两天。然后，你恢复正常饮食（也就是吃得太多）几天。星期一，你再次开始节食。你吃得很健康。午餐。晚餐时，你已经破戒了。

It’s okay; that’s how people take the first steps out of an unhealthy habit.

没关系；人们就是这样迈出戒除不良习惯的第一步。

What is not okay is if, when your friends comment on your eating habits, you reply with, “You know, I recently began a diet.” This is not okay. You did not begin a diet. You ate healthily for a couple of meals in a row. That’s not a diet. It’s like someone who says, “I stopped smoking cigarettes. 20 minutes ago.”

如果朋友评论你的饮食习惯时，你回答说：“你知道吗，我最近开始节食了。” 这就不对了。你并没有开始节食，你只是连续几顿饭吃得很健康而已。这根本不是节食。这就好比有人说：“我20分钟前戒烟了。”

You are on a diet only if you have been sustainably on it for at least a few weeks. If it’s not sustainable, it didn’t happen.

只有持续节食至少几周，才能算作节食成功。如果不能持续，那就不能算成功。

By deluding yourself that you are on the right path to solving one of your problems, you ensure that it will never be solved.

如果你自欺欺人地认为自己正走在解决问题的正确道路上，那么你注定这个问题永远不会得到解决。

When you face a problem that requires sustained action to be solved, don’t assume that you solved it until you have demonstrated the capacity to sustain over time the action you decided to undertake.

当你面临一个需要持续行动才能解决的问题时，不要以为你已经解决了这个问题，直到你证明自己有能力长期坚持你所决定采取的行动。

Deluding yourself that what you are doing is enough is how you ensure that a problem will never go away.

自欺欺人地认为你所做的一切就足够了，只会让你的问题永远无法解决。

You’re not working out unless you completed at least two sessions a week for one month in a row.

如果你没有连续一个月每周至少完成两次锻炼，那就不能算作锻炼。

You’re not eating healthily unless you managed to sustain your “diet” (whichever diet you decided to follow) for at least one month in a row.

除非你能够连续至少一个月坚持你的“饮食计划”（无论你选择遵循哪种饮食计划），否则你就不能算是健康饮食。

You haven’t mastered your craft unless you have produced a few great works in a row.

只有连续创作出几部优秀作品，才能真正掌握你的技艺。

As some famous athlete once said, “I do not train until I succeed – I train until I cannot fail.”

正如某位著名运动员所说：“我训练不是为了成功，而是为了避免失败。”

…

The rule addressed in this chapter, “if it isn’t sustainable, it didn’t happen,” also applies to the evaluation of habits, people, and companies. For example, “I volunteered once” doesn’t tell us whether someone is kind-hearted.

本章提到的原则——“如果不能持续，那就等于没发生过”——同样适用于评估习惯、个人和公司。例如，“我做过一次志愿者”并不能说明这个人是否心地善良。

Similarly, “we sold this product to thousands of customers” doesn’t tell us much about sustainable demand for a company’s product unless it has been sold profitably. Any product can have high demand if sold at a low enough price. The challenge is not to sell a product but to sell it profitably and sustainably.

同样，“我们把这款产品卖给了成千上万的客户”这句话并不能告诉我们太多关于该公司产品可持续需求的信息，除非该产品已经盈利。任何产品如果价格足够低，都可能拥有很高的需求。真正的挑战不在于卖出产品，而在于如何盈利且可持续地销售产品。

When judging someone, only consider the subset of their actions that is sustainable.

评判一个人时，只考虑他/她行为中可持续的部分。

ACTION:

行动：

Is there some accomplishment of yours you still talk about, even though it wasn’t sustainable?

你有没有一些成就，即使它未能持续下去，你至今仍津津乐道？

Is there any way to make it sustainable? Did you know, at the time, whether it could have been sustainable?

有没有办法让它可持续发展？当时你是否知道它是否可以可持续发展？

What does this tell you about your motivations?

这说明你的动机是什么？

#↩
Rule 55
规则55

Put your ego into your future self

把你的自尊心融入未来的自己。

There is no difference between ego investment and addiction: in both cases, we outsource decision-making to what has been good to us in the past – drugs, people, social circles…

自我投资和成瘾之间没有区别：在这两种情况下，我们都将决策权外包给过去对我们有利的事物——毒品、人际关系、社交圈……

That which we believe is essential to us, is the criteria we use for making decisions. Our ego is the sum of the entities to which we have outsourced our decision-making.

我们认为至关重要的东西，就是我们做决定的标准。我们的自我，是我们把决策权外包给的各种实体的总和。

Where our ego is invested determines who will benefit from our actions. Some examples:

我们的自尊心投入到哪里，就决定了谁会从我们的行为中受益。例如：

– If our ego is invested in things, we will make decisions that benefit these things (and their producers) . We won’t make decisions that benefit our self.

如果我们的自我执着于某些事物，我们就会做出有利于这些事物（及其生产者）的决定，而不会做出有利于自身的决定。

– If our ego is invested in people, we will make decisions that benefit these people . Moreover, they will only benefit from our decisions in the short term: our friends, families, and partners have more to gain from a version of our self that reached its own potential rather than from a hollow version of our self whose development got compromised by our “selfless” actions.

如果我们的自我价值感寄托于他人，我们就会做出有利于这些人的决定。而且，他们只能从我们的决定中获得短期利益：我们的朋友、家人和伴侣会从一个充分发挥自身潜能的自我中获益，而不是从一个因我们“无私”的行为而阻碍自身发展的空洞自我中获益。

– If our ego is invested in our membership in social groups, we will make decisions that benefit our membership, not our self. Moreover, we will end up empty-handed if, in the future, the group proves itself false (if it reveals not good as we used to believe, or if its attitude towards us changes).

如果我们将自我价值感寄托于社会群体成员身份上，我们就会做出有利于群体而非自身的决定。此外，如果将来群体被证明是虚假的（如果它不像我们过去认为的那样好，或者如果它对我们的态度发生了变化），我们最终将一无所获。

– If our ego is invested in our present self, we will make short-term decisions , which will ephemerally fulfill our present self but also prevent the development of a solid foundation for our future self.

– 如果我们的自我执着于现在的自己，我们就会做出短期的决定，这些决定虽然能暂时满足我们现在的自己，但也会阻碍我们为未来的自己奠定坚实的基础。

Instead, if our ego is invested in our future self, we make long-term decisions. Moreover, we will not suffer from present outcomes, for they are not final; we will only care about our long-term growth. 25

相反，如果我们把精力放在未来的自己身上，我们就会做出长远的决定。此外，我们不会为眼前的结果而痛苦，因为它们并非最终结果；我们只会关注自身的长期发展。

Investing our ego in our future self is the way out of addictions (towards things, people, and identities).

将我们的自我投入到未来的自己身上，是摆脱成瘾（对事物、人、身份的成瘾）的出路。

Investing our ego in our future self is the way to ensure our long-term development and happiness.

将我们的自尊心投资于未来的自己，是确保我们长期发展和幸福的途径。

ACTION:

行动：

Write down a vision for your future self. What does it do? What does it look like? What does it feel like? What does a day in its life look like?

写下你对未来自己的愿景。它会做什么？它会是什么样子？它会感觉如何？它的一天会是什么样子？

Every day, read your vision for your future self. Then, talk to other people about it. Invest some ego into it.

每天阅读你对未来自己的愿景。然后，与他人分享。投入一些自信和热情。

Be careful not to invest your ego into the things your future ego will possess or the specific people it will spend time around – if you do, you will make decisions that benefit those things, not your future self.

要小心，不要把你的自我投入到你未来将拥有的东西或你将要与之相处的特定人群中——如果你这样做，你就会做出有利于这些东西而不是你未来自己的决定。

Instead, invest your ego into the skills and capacities your future ego will possess. No one can take those away from you, and the chances are that they will benefit you no matter what.

相反，你应该把精力投入到培养未来自身所需的技能和能力上。没有人能夺走这些，而且无论如何，它们都可能让你受益匪浅。

If you manage to do the above, you will naturally begin to make better, more fulfilling decisions.

如果你能做到以上几点，你自然就会开始做出更好、更令人满意的决定。

#↩
Rule 56
规则56

Work on your internal karma

努力改善你的内在业力。

Karma is generally considered a mystic concept. I, on the other hand, consider it a natural manifestation of how people and systems react to actions and events.

人们通常认为因果报应是一种神秘的概念。而我则认为它是人和系统对行为和事件做出反应的自然表现形式。

Karma is what happens when the ripples of our actions coalesce into waves that hit us. For example, we might be rude to someone on our way to work, only to discover that evening that he works in the restaurant we wanted to get a table at, and he retributes our rudeness by bouncing us. However, this is an example of external karma. Instead, I am more interested in internal karma. 26

因果报应是指我们行为产生的涟漪汇聚成波浪，最终冲击我们自身。例如，我们可能在上班路上对某人无礼，结果晚上发现他竟然在我们想去的那家餐厅工作，于是他以牙还牙，把我们拒之门外。然而，这是外在因果的例子。我更感兴趣的是内在因果。

Internal karma is the concept that our behavior conditions our mind’s future actions. For example, smoking a cigarette brings us bad karma because it makes it more likely that we will smoke a second cigarette, and then a third, until thirty years down the road, we end up hospitalized. Similarly, cheating on a high school exam brings us bad karma because it makes us more likely to cheat in future situations, thereby preventing us from doing the hard work that develops our skills (see Rule #52). 27

内在业力是指我们的行为会影响我们未来的心理活动。例如，吸烟会带来恶业，因为它会增加我们吸第二支、第三支烟的可能性，直到三十年后我们最终住院。同样，高中考试作弊也会带来恶业，因为它会增加我们未来作弊的可能性，从而阻碍我们努力学习，提升自身技能（参见规则#52）。

Too many people make decisions based on how their actions will change the world. Too few people make decisions based on how their actions will change them.

太多人做决定时考虑的是他们的行为会如何改变世界，而很少有人做决定时考虑的是他们的行为会如何改变自己。

“Every action you take is a vote for or against the type of person you wish to become.” – bestselling author James Clear

“你的每一个行动都是在投票，决定你想成为什么样的人。”——畅销书作家詹姆斯·克莱尔

ACTION:

行动：

When you make a decision, do not (only) think about how it will change things for you.

当你做决定时，不要（只）考虑它会如何改变你自身的情况。

Think about how it will change you.

想想它会如何改变你。

#↩
Rule 57
规则57

Never misstep twice in a row

切勿连续两次犯错

What defines great partnerships – in love and business – is how its members react to their partner’s misstep. Do they take a generous action that offsets their partner’s misstep, re-aligning the partnership’s trajectory towards happiness and success? Or do they take a selfish action, taking their partner’s misstep as permission to take a misstep themselves? 28

爱情和事业中，伟大伙伴关系的标志在于双方如何应对对方的失误。他们会采取慷慨的行动来弥补对方的过失，从而重新调整关系的走向，使其朝着幸福和成功的方向发展吗？还是会采取自私的行动，将对方的失误视为自己犯错的借口？

Problems happen all the time. What matters is our reaction to them. Does it improve the future? Or does it make it worse?

问题时有发生，关键在于我们如何应对。这种应对方式是让未来变得更好，还是让未来变得更糟？

…

Similarly, successful individuals are not those who never commit a mistake but those who, after an error, take action to prevent it from occurring ever again.

同样，成功人士并非从不犯错的人，而是在犯错后采取措施防止错误再次发生的人。

How you act after a misstep is more important than the misstep itself. Missteps happen to everyone, but how you react to them is a strong indicator of the level of success that you will eventually achieve.

犯错之后你的应对方式比错误本身更重要。每个人都会犯错，但你如何应对错误，很大程度上决定了你最终能取得多大的成功。

Misstepping once is a bump in your trajectory to success. Mistepping twice means having decided to redirect such a trajectory towards mediocrity. 29

一次失误只是通往成功道路上的一个小坎坷。两次失误则意味着你已经决定将这条道路引向平庸。

ACTION:

行动：

Every time you skip a workout, do everything in your power – and then some more 30 – to ensure that you won’t skip the next practice.

每次错过一次锻炼，都要竭尽全力——甚至更多——确保下次不会错过锻炼。

Every time you arrive late at a meeting, every time you fail to complete a to-do item on your agenda that was supposed to be completed today, every time you fail someone’s trust, prevent it from happening again. This involves taking immediate action to change your environment and incentives .

每次你开会迟到，每次你没能完成今天应该完成的待办事项，每次你辜负了别人的信任，都要防止这种情况再次发生。这需要你立即采取行动，改变你的工作环境和激励机制。

Promising that the next time you won’t misstep is not enough. You need to take material action that ensures that you won’t.

仅仅承诺下次不会再犯同样的错误是不够的。你需要采取实际行动来确保自己不会再犯同样的错误。

Do whatever it takes to ensure you won’t misstep twice in a row.

务必采取一切必要措施，确保自己不会连续两次犯错。

#↩
Rule 58
规则58

Do not chase success; instead, become the kind of person that attracts success

不要追逐成功；相反，要成为吸引成功的人。

You do not follow success; success follows you. The difference is in attitude. As we have discussed, if your only goal is pursuing success at any cost, you will be tempted to take shortcuts to achieve it. This will prevent you from building solid foundations that can sustain success over the long term. Success without foundations is always short-lived (marriages without solid foundations produce divorces, careers without solid foundations produce frustrations, and so on).

你不是追逐成功，而是成功追随你。区别在于态度。正如我们之前讨论过的，如果你的唯一目标是不惜一切代价追求成功，你就会忍不住走捷径。这将阻碍你建立能够长期支撑成功的坚实基础。没有根基的成功总是短暂的（没有稳固基础的婚姻会导致离婚，没有稳固基础的事业会导致挫败感，等等）。

Instead, long-lasting success – the kind that continues to be satisfying after the initial bit, the kind that makes you sleep better at night – can only be achieved by building solid foundations.

相反，只有打好坚实的基础，才能获得持久的成功——那种在最初的满足感过后还能持续带来满足感的成功，那种能让你晚上睡得更安稳的成功。

Once you build such foundations, success will ensue. But if you chase success without first building its foundations, success will escape you.

一旦你打好这样的基础，成功自然会随之而来。但如果你不先打好基础就盲目追求成功，成功终将与你擦肩而过。

(In this book, I use the term “success” in its broadest meaning, mainly to indicate personal fulfillment and self-respect. You decide what success means for you.)

（本书中，“成功”一词的含义非常广泛，主要指个人成就感和自尊。至于成功对你而言意味着什么，则由你来定义。）

ACTION:

行动：

Imagine that, for the next year, you could not reap any reward from your success. You cannot extract any profit, any fame, nothing. That would be a great time to build some solid foundations for your success. For example, developing some skills, spending your time on personal practice, collecting honest feedback, and reflecting on what you really want.

想象一下，在接下来的一年里，你无法从成功中获得任何回报。你无法获得任何利润、名声，什么都得不到。那将是为你的成功打下坚实基础的绝佳时机。例如，培养一些技能，花时间进行个人练习，收集真诚的反馈，并认真思考你真正想要的是什么。

What would you be working on?

你会从事什么工作？

#↩
Rule 59
规则59

Play the long game

着眼长远。

All my books are a one-man effort. The only thing I do not do myself is the cover, for which I hire a professional artist. Everything else is just me – I have no editor, no proofreader, no marketer. I even do the typesetting. 31

我的所有书籍都是我独自完成的。唯一不是我自己做的是封面设计，我聘请了一位专业设计师。其他所有工作都由我一人包办——我没有编辑、没有校对、没有营销人员。甚至连排版都是我自己完成的。

Why am I doing everything myself? Because I’m playing a long-term game. You see, in the short term, learning doesn’t matter, only results. But in the long term, learning is everything that matters. And by doing everything myself, I can do more experiments and learn more. Moreover, this approach gives me opportunities to apply my learnings, increasing their value. 32

我为什么要事事亲力亲为？因为我着眼于长远。你看，短期内，学习并不重要，结果才是关键。但从长远来看，学习才是最重要的。通过亲力亲为，我可以进行更多实验，学习更多知识。此外，这种方法也让我有机会应用所学知识，从而提升其价值。

The longer your time frame, the more it pays to do more things yourself. You have more time to apply your learnings and for their outputs to compound.

时间跨度越长，亲力亲为就越有利。你有更多的时间运用所学知识，并让这些知识的成果不断累积。

Of course, this doesn’t mean to do everything. You still want to prioritize, delegate, and add things to your not -to-do list. But when it comes to the core skills of a role in which you believe you will spend decades, it might be worth spending some time doing most things yourself.

当然，这并不意味着事事都要亲力亲为。你仍然需要分清轻重缓急，合理分配任务，并将不做的事情列入待办清单。但是，对于你认为自己将长期从事的核心技能岗位而言，花些时间亲力亲为或许是值得的。

Not only will you develop skills but also gain insights about problems and opportunities. This might even become a competitive advantage, making your competencies rare and thus in high demand.

你不仅能提升技能，还能深入了解问题和机遇。这甚至可能成为你的竞争优势，使你的能力稀缺，从而备受青睐。

ACTION:

行动：

Which roles do you expect to cover for at least a decade in your personal or professional life?

在你的个人生活或职业生涯中，你预计会在哪些角色中扮演至少十年？

Pick one. Then, list down the skills that would provide a significant advantage in that role or make you unique (because you would be one of the few individuals possessing a special combination of skills relevant to that role).

选择一个职位。然后，列出在该职位上能提供显著优势或使你与众不同的技能（因为你将是少数拥有与该职位相关的特殊技能组合的人之一）。

Later, ask yourself which of those skills wouldn’t make sense to practice with a two-year time horizon but would make sense with a twenty-year time horizon.

之后，问问自己，哪些技能在两年的时间范围内练习没有意义，但在二十年的时间范围内练习则有意义。

Finally, consider finding ways to develop that skill, preferably through practice.

最后，考虑如何培养这项技能，最好是通过练习。

#↩

Work on your habits

培养好习惯

Rules 60 to 64

规则 60 至 64

“There is no [such list as the] 7 things successful people do before breakfast. Here is the real morning routine of successful people. They get up, and they show up. At some point, they do work that matters. The details are up to you.”

“并不存在所谓的‘成功人士早餐前必做的7件事’。成功人士真正的晨间习惯是这样的：他们起床，然后准时出现。在某个时间点，他们会做一些真正重要的工作。至于具体细节，就看你自己了。”

– James Clear, bestselling author 詹姆斯·克利尔，畅销书作家

Showing up every day isn’t easy.

每天坚持上班并不容易。

This chapter will help you do that.

本章将帮助你做到这一点。

Rule 60

规则 60

The standards you have today determine the life you will have in a few years

你今天所秉持的价值观决定了你几年后的生活水平。

“Most people, if they really look at how they’re living their life today, it’s based on a set of standards that they made choices about 10, 20, or 30 years ago.” – personal coach Tony Robbins

“大多数人如果认真审视自己今天的生活方式，就会发现它是基于他们大约10年、20年甚至30年前选择的一套标准。”——私人教练托尼·罗宾斯

A standard is a criterion you use to determine what is “acceptable.” For example, your standard for “a clean room” determines when you consider your bedroom messy and thus when you tidy it.

标准是你用来判断什么是“可接受的”的准则。例如，你对“干净的房间”的标准决定了你何时认为卧室凌乱，以及何时需要整理它。

Your standards determine what you perceive as problems to be addressed.

你的标准决定了你认为哪些问题需要解决。

The higher your standards, the more likely you will react to a negative situation and do something to improve it, instead of passively accepting it.

你的标准越高，就越有可能对负面情况做出反应并采取措施改善它，而不是被动地接受它。

The higher your standards, the greater your self-growth. 33

你的标准越高，你的自我成长就越大。

ACTION:

行动：

Pick one area of your life in which you would like to improve. It could be your romantic life, your social life, your career, your health – any area that interests you.

选择生活中你想改善的一个方面。它可以是你的爱情生活、社交生活、事业、健康——任何你感兴趣的领域。

Now, write down your standards for it. Remember: standards aren’t your goals. Instead, they are the levels below which you take action. For example, if you say that your standard for being healthy is “going to the gym three times per week,” but actually, over the last year, you only went three times per month, then your actual standard is “three times per month.”

现在，写下你对健康的标准。记住：标准不是你的目标，而是你采取行动的最低标准。例如，如果你说你保持健康的标准是“每周去健身房三次”，但实际上，过去一年你每月只去了三次，那么你实际的标准就是“每月三次”。

Now, take a post-it (or another form of reminder). Next, write down a more rigorous version of your standard (for example, if your standard was “going to the gym three times per month,” it becomes “going to the gym twice per week”). And finally, stick it somewhere visible, for example, on the mirror in your bathroom.

现在，拿一张便签纸（或其他提醒方式）。接下来，写下一个更严格的标准（例如，如果你的标准是“每月去健身房三次”，那就改成“每周去健身房两次”）。最后，把它贴在显眼的地方，例如浴室的镜子上。

Do everything you have to do to hold yourself to your new standard.

为了达到新的标准，你必须竭尽所能。

And if you fall below it, use the standard as a trigger to rebound higher.

如果跌破这个标准，就以这个标准为触发点，争取反弹得更高。

#↩
Rule 61
规则 61

Discipline is freedom

自律即自由

(– author and boxer Ed Latimore)

（——作家兼拳击手埃德·拉蒂莫尔）

School teaches students that discipline is coercion.

学校教导学生，纪律就是强制。

However, discipline only involves coercion when it is needed to serve someone whose interests are not aligned with yours. Instead, when discipline originates from your objectives, it leads to freedom. It is what prevents you from being coerced by others.

然而，只有当纪律是为了迎合那些利益与你不一致的人时，它才会包含强制手段。相反，当纪律源于你的目标时，它会带来自由。正是这种自由使你免受他人的胁迫。

- Having discipline with respect to your body (exercising & eating healthily) frees you from the coercion of age & diseases.

- 对自己的身体保持自律（锻炼和健康饮食）可以让你免受年龄和疾病的困扰。

- Having discipline with respect to your work (doing the important things that must be done) brings you the success that will free you from the coercion of your employer.

- 对工作保持自律（做好必须做的重要事情）会给你带来成功，使你摆脱雇主的胁迫。

- Having discipline with respect to your mind frees you from the coercion of your emotions.

- 保持思想上的自律，能使你免受情绪的胁迫。

If you have the wisdom to set a system that can deliver the results you want AND the discipline to apply it consistently, you will rapidly increase your value and capabilities to the point that you will soon be able to choose who you surround yourself with and what projects to work on.

如果你有足够的智慧建立一个能够带来你想要的结果的系统，并且有足够的自律性去持续地应用它，你就会迅速提高你的价值和能力，以至于你很快就能够选择与谁共事以及从事哪些项目。

ACTION:

行动：

Right now, on your to-do list of choice (it could also be a post-it on your fridge), write the following:

现在，请在您选择的待办事项清单上（也可以是贴在冰箱上的便签纸）写下以下内容：

- A first task which you will undertake daily. It could be to do 20 pushups, to write 1000 words for your blog/book, to call two prospective customers, anything related to one of your long-term goals.

- 你每天都要完成的第一项任务。它可以是做20个俯卧撑，为你的博客/书写1000字，给两个潜在客户打电话，任何与你的长期目标相关的任务都可以。

- Immediately below the first task, write the following task, which you will also undertake daily: “make the necessary adjustments to ensure that the first task is done daily.”

- 在第一项任务下方紧接着写下以下任务，你也将每天执行该任务：“做出必要的调整，以确保每天都能完成第一项任务。”

This second task will ensure that you will persist at the first one long enough for it to show its benefits and thus become a habit.

第二个任务将确保你能够坚持第一个任务足够长的时间，使其产生益处，从而养成习惯。

When you perform the first task, especially if it feels effortful, focus on visualizing its benefits. Performing this task isn’t a hurdle but an opportunity. Having to perform it isn’t coercion but how you save yourself.

当你执行第一项任务时，尤其当它让你感到吃力时，要专注于想象它的益处。执行这项任务不是障碍，而是一个机会。必须执行它不是强迫，而是你拯救自己的方式。

#↩
Rule 62
规则 62

Successful people, at some point in their life, committed to the hard choice

成功人士在人生的某个阶段，都会做出艰难的选择。

“Easy choices, hard life. Hard choices, easy life.”

“容易的选择，生活艰难；艰难的选择，生活轻松。”

– Four-time world weightlifting champion Jerzy Gregorek 四届世界举重冠军耶日·格雷戈雷克

When faced with a problem, we can usually take the hard choice (address the cause of the problem) or the easy one (find a shortcut or circumvent the problem).

面对问题时，我们通常可以选择艰难的抉择（解决问题的根源）或轻松的抉择（寻找捷径或绕过问题）。

The hard choice solves the problem and prevents it from reoccurring in the future, thus leading to an easier life.

艰难的选择可以解决问题，并防止问题在未来再次发生，从而使生活更加轻松。

The easy choice makes life easier only until the problem comes back. Then, it will be much harder. And because the problem has not been solved in a definitive way, it will come back.

简单的选择固然能让生活轻松些，但问题终究会卷土重来。到那时，一切都会变得更加艰难。而且，由于问题并未得到彻底解决，它还会再次出现。

Embrace hard choices. They will make your life easier.

勇敢做出艰难的选择。它们会让你的生活更轻松。

ACTION:

行动：

Think about one occurrence in which you made the hard choice. You feel good about that choice now, don’t you?

想想你曾经做出艰难抉择的那件事。现在你对当时的抉择感到满意，对吗？

Think about one circumstance in which you made the easy choice. Is it still possible to make the hard one?

想想你曾经做出轻松选择的那种情况。现在还有可能做出艰难的选择吗？

#↩
Rule 63
规则63

Taking a course of action makes it easier to take it again. For better or for worse

采取某种行动会使再次采取同样的行动变得更容易。无论好坏。

The worst thing about eating junk food today is that it makes you more likely to eat junk food tomorrow.

今天吃垃圾食品最糟糕的地方在于，它会让你明天更有可能继续吃垃圾食品。

The worst thing about mindlessly watching TV today is that it makes you more likely to mindlessly watch TV tomorrow.

今天漫无目的地看电视最糟糕的地方在于，它会让你明天更有可能漫无目的地看电视。

The worst thing about doing something bad for you is that it makes you more likely to do it again tomorrow.

做对自己有害的事最糟糕的地方在于，它会让你明天更有可能再次做同样的事。

…

I used to think about decisions in terms of trade-offs. For example, going to the gym would have the benefit of getting fitter and the downside of taking a couple of hours off my day that I could spend otherwise.

我过去常常从权衡利弊的角度来考虑决定。例如，去健身房的好处是能增强体质，缺点是会占用我一天中几个小时的时间，而这些时间我可以用来做其他事情。

I now think about decisions in terms of how they shape my future behavior. For example, the hidden cost of skipping today’s gym session is that it makes me more likely to skip the gym in the future.

我现在会从决策如何影响我未来的行为的角度来思考问题。例如，今天不去健身房的隐性成本是，它会增加我未来不去健身房的可能性。

…

The seeds you plant in your garden are the fruits you will harvest tomorrow.

你在花园里种下的种子，就是你明天将要收获的果实。

…

Most personality traits are skills: they can be trained.

大多数性格特征都是技能：它们可以通过训练获得。

Also, most personality traits are habits. For example, whether we are resilient, brave, kind, and honest largely depends on whether we acted resiliently, bravely, kindly, and honestly the last time we found ourselves in a similar situation. 34

此外，大多数人格特质都是习惯。例如，我们是否坚韧、勇敢、善良和诚实，很大程度上取决于我们上次遇到类似情况时是否表现出了坚韧、勇敢、善良和诚实。

Our decisions shape us much more than we give them credit. Actually, we constantly shape ourselves with our decisions. We just do not notice because we usually repeat the same choices over and over.

我们的决定对我们的影响远超我们的想象。事实上，我们一直在通过自己的决定塑造自己。我们只是没有意识到这一点，因为我们通常会重复同样的选择。

ACTION:

行动：

What is one thing which is bad for you in which you keep indulging? Try now to visualize how you will feel the next time you are tempted. Force yourself to contemplate how giving in would increase the chances of falling into a lifelong addiction. Visualize how your life would become if you would be doing that every day for the rest of your life. Imagine how you would feel. Focus on the disgust and regret.

你有什么明明知道自己有害却又总是沉溺其中的事物？现在试着想象一下，下次当你再次受到诱惑时，你会是什么感受。强迫自己思考，屈服于诱惑会如何增加你终身沉迷的风险。想象一下，如果你余生每天都这样做，你的生活会变成什么样子。想象一下你会是什么感觉。专注于那种厌恶和悔恨。

Then, visualize yourself renouncing that temptation. Contemplate how a life free from that bad habit would feel. Imagine all the things you would be able to do with the time, energy, and money saved. Visualize them. Imagine how you would feel. Focus on the joy and sense of self-respect.

然后，想象自己放弃这种诱惑。想想摆脱坏习惯的生活会是什么感觉。想象一下，省下来的时间、精力和金钱能让你做多少事情。把它们都想象出来。想象一下你的感受。专注于那种喜悦和自尊感。

The next time you find yourself in temptation, remember the disgust. Remember the regret. Then, make a choice you will be proud of.

下次当你面临诱惑时，想想那种厌恶感。想想那种后悔感。然后，做出一个让你引以为傲的选择。

#↩
Rule 64
规则64

Willpower is useless,
unless used for tweaking the environment

意志力毫无用处，除非它被用来调整环境。

Many think that willpower is what makes people power through adversities. That’s only partially true. 35 When willpower is used as THE solution to power through an unfavorable environment, it fails to produce sustainable results. You cannot stay long on a diet if your kitchen is always full of sweet temptations. Willpower does not resist a chronically bad environment. The environment always wins.

许多人认为意志力是人们克服逆境的关键。这种说法并不完全正确。当意志力被当作克服不利环境的唯一方法时，它无法产生持久的效果。如果你的厨房里总是摆满了诱人的甜点，你不可能长期坚持节食。意志力无法抵抗长期恶劣的环境。环境总是最终获胜。

Unless we use our willpower to change the environment.

除非我们运用意志力去改变环境。

Willpower is best used to create a short burst of activity whose purpose is not to achieve a result but to create the conditions for sustainable results. This includes using willpower to change your environment and your incentives.

意志力最有效的运用方式是激发短时间内的行动力，其目的并非达成最终结果，而是创造条件，从而获得可持续的结果。这包括运用意志力来改变你的环境和激励机制。

For example, using willpower to power through a diet will only work for a week or two. Instead, using willpower to give away the sweets in your house and shop for healthy food is an action that is more likely to bring sustainable results.

例如，仅凭意志力来坚持节食可能只能维持一两周。相反，用意志力把家里的甜食送人，并购买健康食品，这种做法更有可能带来持久的效果。

Similarly, using willpower to go to the gym twice might not ensure that next week you will still exercise. Instead, using willpower to hire a personal trainer who will hold you accountable (or call a friend asking him to do the same) is more likely to build the conditions for you to exercise regularly.

同样，仅仅依靠意志力去健身房两次并不能保证你下周还会继续锻炼。相反，依靠意志力聘请一位私人教练来督促你（或者打电话给朋友请他帮忙），更有可能为你创造规律锻炼的条件。

ACTION:

行动：

Pick one commitment you made to yourself but failed to sustain over time.

选择一项你曾对自己做出但最终未能坚持下去的承诺。

What action, taken this week, would tweak your environment or your incentives so that you will be more likely to hold to your commitment in the future?

本周采取哪些行动可以调整你的环境或激励机制，从而使你将来更有可能信守承诺？

#↩

Avoid the toxic

避免接触有毒物质

Rules 65 to 73

规则 65 至 73

The biggest regrets of my tens and twenties aren’t the things I didn’t do but the things I did even though they were bad for me.

我十几二十岁的时候最大的遗憾不是那些我没做过的事，而是那些我做了但对我有害的事。

I call these things toxic – toxic activities, toxic people, and toxic environments.

我称这些东西为有毒的——有毒的行为、有毒的人和有毒的环境。

I wish I had realized earlier that they were bad for me. But I couldn’t have. A defining feature of the toxic is that, more often than not, we realize that we are better off without it only after it’s not in our life anymore. For example, I only realized that my high school friends were toxic after I got out of high school and started making friends elsewhere. Similarly, some people don’t acknowledge how toxic their work environment is until they change jobs.

我真希望自己能早点意识到他们对我有害。但我不可能。有害关系的一个显著特征是，我们往往只有在失去它之后才会意识到，没有它我们会过得更好。例如，我直到高中毕业、开始结交新朋友后才意识到，我的高中朋友都是有害的。同样，有些人直到换工作后才意识到自己之前的工作环境有多么糟糕。

This chapter is about identifying what’s toxic and getting rid of it.

本章主要讲解如何识别有毒物质并清除它们。

Rule 65
规则65

Need is toxic

需求是有害的。

Drugs, alcohol, and cigarettes are toxic. They produce long-term damage to whoever consumes them and turn them into addicts.

毒品、酒精和香烟都是有毒的。它们会对食用者造成长期损害，并使人上瘾。

Some relationships are toxic, too. They damage the person having them, who in turn doesn’t abandon them as if they were addicted.

有些关系也是有害的。它们会伤害身处其中的一方，而当事人却不会像戒瘾一样彻底摆脱这种关系。

The cause behind toxic relationships is always neediness. Some might say it is poor judgment. However, that might be what makes people initiate a toxic relationship but isn’t what makes them remain in it. People who stay in one do so because they need it. In particular, they need the quick “fix” it gives them – the feeling of being loved or the support they get in a given domain, even if the relationship as a whole wrecks their lives.

有毒关系的根源总是需求。有人可能会说是判断力不足。然而，这或许是人们开始一段有毒关系的原因，却并非他们继续身陷其中的原因。那些留在一段关系中的人，是因为他们需要它。尤其需要的是它带来的快速“慰藉”——被爱的感觉，或是某个特定领域获得的支持，即便这段关系整体上会毁掉他们的生活。

Sometimes, toxic relationships ruin lives in a visible way, causing chronic stress, depression, health problems, and money issues. Other times, toxic relationships wreck lives invisibly, leading to mediocrity and stagnation. This happens when the toxic partner (be it a lover or a friend) absorbs all your time and energy, part of which you could have used to develop yourself or solve your problems. In this case, while the relationship itself seems fulfilling, the rest of your life becomes a wreck, as you have no more time or energy to direct towards it. This is the worst kind of toxic relationship. It makes it seem like the partner is the only island of comfort and relief in the sea of problems you are drowning in, hiding the fact that they are the very cause of your sinking.

有时，有害的关系会以显而易见的方式摧毁生活，导致慢性压力、抑郁、健康问题和经济困境。而有时，有害的关系则会在无形中摧毁生活，使人变得平庸停滞。这种情况发生在有害的伴侣（无论是恋人还是朋友）耗尽你所有的时间和精力时，而这些时间和精力原本可以用来提升自我或解决自身问题。在这种情况下，虽然关系本身看似充实，但你的生活其他方面却一团糟，因为你没有时间和精力投入其中。这是最糟糕的有害关系。它让你觉得伴侣是你身陷困境的汪洋大海中唯一的慰藉和避风港，却掩盖了他们才是你沉沦的罪魁祸首这一事实。

ACTION:

行动：

Is there any colleague, friend, or lover with whom you have a toxic relationship?

你和同事、朋友或爱人之间是否存在有害的关系？

If your best friend were in this relationship instead of you, would you advise them to quit it?

如果你的好朋友代替你陷入这段感情，你会建议他们分手吗？

BONUS:

奖金：

How would you behave if everyone would stay by your side? If their loyalty were unquestionable? If you didn’t have to care about what they think?

如果所有人都留在你身边，你会怎么做？如果他们的忠诚毋庸置疑，如果你不必在意他们的想法？

The difference between your answer to the last question and your current behavior is approval-seeking.

你对上一个问题的回答和你现在的行为之间的区别在于，你是在寻求认可。

…

Is there something you desire to do but are ashamed of?

你有没有想做但又羞于启齿的事情？

Whose judgment do you fear?

你惧怕谁的审判？

Why do you depend on their judgment?

你为什么依赖他们的判断？

What will you regret more on your deathbed, having lost their favor or never having done that thing you desired to do?

临终之际，你会更后悔失去他们的宠爱，还是从未做过自己想做的事？

Is there any relationship in which you think you are making “win-win” compromises, but you are actually making “lose-win” choices?

是否存在这样一种关系：你认为自己在做出“双赢”的妥协，但实际上却做出了“双输”的选择？

For example, a romantic partner or a boss to whom you are giving much more than you’re getting in return, not because you like giving but because you feel you must for the relationship to continue?

例如，你对伴侣或老板付出的远比得到的多，不是因为你喜欢付出，而是因为觉得为了维持这段关系你必须这样做？

#↩
Rule 66
规则66

Treat your addictions by getting options

通过多种方式来治疗你的成瘾问题。

In the context of this chapter, I will use the term “addictions” to refer to a broader set of actions than just smoking, drinking, gambling, and doing drugs.

在本章中，我将使用“成瘾”一词来指代比吸烟、饮酒、赌博和吸毒更广泛的行为。

Addictions are anything you keep doing over extended periods even though it makes your life worse .

成瘾是指你长期坚持做某件事，即使它会让你的生活变得更糟。

This includes watching too much TV, playing video games too much , eating too much sugar, sleeping too little , going out with toxic friends , entering relationships with toxic partners , reactively checking your email or phone more than once per hour , working a job that destroys you , and in general any compulsive behavior.

这包括看电视太多、玩电子游戏太多、吃糖太多、睡眠太少、和有害的朋友出去玩、和有害的伴侣建立恋爱关系、每小时查看电子邮件或手机超过一次、从事一份会毁掉你的工作，以及一般的任何强迫行为。

“How much” and “why” are important factors here. For example, watching TV is not bad per se. However, watching too much TV is bad, especially if done instead of facing the problems you should be addressing. The same goes for playing video games, eating sugar, checking your phone/email, and so on – the dose matters.

“多少”和“为什么”是这里的重要因素。例如，看电视本身并没有错。但是，看电视看得太多就不好，尤其是在用看电视来逃避应该解决的问题时。玩电子游戏、吃糖、查看手机/邮件等等也是如此——剂量很重要。

If it’s bad for you and yet you keep doing it, then you are addicted to it. Do not focus on the medical definition of addiction. Do not focus on what is exact. Focus on what will help you. Acknowledging which habits of yours are making your life worse and treating them as if they were medical addictions is the way to get rid of them.

如果某件事对你有害，而你却仍然继续做，那么你已经上瘾了。不要纠结于成瘾的医学定义，也不要纠结于具体细节，而应该关注什么对你有帮助。承认哪些习惯正在让你的生活变得更糟，并像对待药物成瘾一样对待它们，才是摆脱它们的方法。

The problem with addictions is that they take time, energy, and money that you could instead use for your personal development and growth. People who complain about not having time are usually addicted to some activity that is siphoning off their time from productive endeavors.

成瘾的问题在于它会消耗时间、精力和金钱，而这些原本可以用于个人发展和成长。那些抱怨没时间的人，通常都沉迷于某种活动，这些活动正在吞噬他们原本可以用于高效工作的时间。

Here are some subtle forms of addiction:

以下是一些不易察觉的成瘾形式：

– Addiction to busywork: activities that do not add value to your life.

沉迷于无意义的忙碌：那些对你的生活没有价值的活动。

– Toxic relationships. Usually, this happens to those who lack options for partners. They would quit the toxic relationship if they knew that they could have another partner who would make them feel better. But because they do not have readily available options, they keep spending time with those hurting them.

——有毒的关系。这种情况通常发生在那些缺乏伴侣选择的人身上。如果他们知道自己可以找到另一个让自己感觉更好的伴侣，他们就会结束这段有毒的关系。但由于他们没有现成的选择，他们只能继续和那些伤害自己的人在一起。

– Working for a company or boss that sucks our energy without giving enough back. Usually, this happens to those who lack options for another job. If they knew that other companies would be glad to hire them, they would quit their current job. But because they do not have an offer on their hands, they refuse to abandon their current employer.

——为一家榨干你精力却不给你任何回报的公司或老板工作。这种情况通常发生在那些没有其他工作选择的人身上。如果他们知道其他公司乐意聘用他们，他们早就辞职了。但由于没有其他公司的offer，他们不愿离开现在的雇主。

– Working a draining job because we need the salary to pay for our high expenses. If we had less debt (or fewer liabilities) or needed less prestige, we would have the option to direct our career towards a lower-paying but healthier job. But because we decided to exchange our options for the possibility of purchasing something that puts shackles on us, we now depend on a high salary.

我们之所以从事一份令人精疲力竭的工作，是因为我们需要高薪来支付高昂的开销。如果我们负债更少（或责任更轻），或者对名望的要求不那么高，我们本可以选择一份薪水较低但更健康的工作。但因为我们为了追求某种束缚我们的东西而放弃了其他选择，如今我们不得不依赖高薪。

The point is: non-clinical addictions derive from a lack of options.

关键在于：非临床成瘾源于缺乏选择。

The way out of such addictions is to develop options for yourself.

摆脱这种成瘾问题的办法是为自己培养其他选择。

ACTION:

行动：

Make a list of the activities and relationships with which you regularly engage, even though they have a negative impact on your life.

列出你经常参与的活动和人际关系，即使它们对你的生活产生了负面影响。

Consider treating them as addictions.

考虑将它们视为成瘾问题进行治疗。

For each, ask yourself: how can I have something else going on that would provide a better option?

对于每件事，问问自己：我怎样才能做点别的事，从而提供更好的选择？

For example:

例如：

– Watching too much TV / playing too many videogames : this often occurs when you do not have much going on in your life. Call some friends, browse for events in your city, pick up a book, start volunteering, etc. You will notice that these activities bring you energy rather than consuming it. (If you’re an introvert, you might be thinking, “for me, going out with friends is an activity that consumes energy.” If this is the case, you might be going out with the wrong friends, in too large groups, in the wrong places, doing the wrong activities, or not learning how to enjoy social interactions. Let your preferences in the choice of the activities be heard. Propose to meet in a quiet place, doing an activity you like. If they’re good friends, they will be okay with it. As a strong introvert myself, I guarantee you that meeting with the right friends in the right places is an energy-generating activity. I wish I had understood this earlier in my life: when going out was energy-consuming, it was because I was going out with the wrong friends or in the wrong setting.)

——看电视/玩电子游戏太多：这种情况通常发生在你生活中没什么事可做的时候。给朋友打个电话，看看你所在城市有哪些活动，读读书，开始做志愿者等等。你会发现这些活动会给你带来能量，而不是消耗能量。（如果你是个内向的人，你可能会想：“对我来说，和朋友出去玩会消耗能量。” 如果是这样，你可能和不合适的朋友出去玩，或者参加人数太多的活动，或者去不合适的地方，或者做了不合适的活动，又或者你没有学会如何享受社交互动。要让别人听到你对活动的偏好。提议在一个安静的地方见面，做你喜欢的事情。如果他们是好朋友，他们会同意的。我自己也是个非常内向的人，我可以向你保证，和合适的朋友在合适的地方见面绝对是一种能让你充满活力的活动。我真希望自己早点明白这一点：以前出去玩会消耗能量，是因为我和不合适的朋友出去玩，或者去了不合适的场合。）

– Eating unhealthily : make sure that you have readily available healthy options. This includes storing healthy food & healthy snacks at home, having a list of restaurants and fast foods that provide healthy options, and following a few classes or videos on how to cook tasty healthy food. Do it now so that when you’re tired and hungry, you have readily available options with minimum effort.

——避免不健康的饮食习惯：确保你随时都能吃到健康的食品。这包括在家中储备健康食品和零食，列出提供健康餐食的餐厅和快餐店清单，以及学习一些烹饪美味健康食物的课程或视频。现在就开始行动，这样当你感到疲惫饥饿时，就能轻松获得健康食品，无需花费太多精力。

– Going to sleep too late : this usually happens to people who have a life they do not want to wake up into. Use the pieces of advice in this book to build yourself a life and a morning routine you actually want to wake up into.

——睡得太晚：这种情况通常发生在那些不想面对自己理想生活的人身上。运用本书中的建议，打造你真正想要的生活和晨间习惯。

– Going out with toxic friends : this often happens when toxic friends are all the friends you have. If your only alternative is staying home, going out with toxic friends might seem the best choice. Instead, find yourself other options. Look for social events in your town. Contact people with whom you haven’t been in contact during the last ten years. If you are unable to make new friends, buy a book on how to do so. Seriously, that’s a skill everyone can learn.

——和损友出去玩：这种情况通常发生在你只有损友的时候。如果你唯一的选择是待在家里，那么和损友出去玩似乎成了最佳选择。但你应该寻找其他出路。看看你所在城市有哪些社交活动。联系那些你过去十年都没联系过的人。如果你实在无法结交新朋友，那就买一本关于如何交朋友的书。说真的，这是每个人都能学会的技能。

– Entering relationships with toxic partners : people usually enter and remain into toxic relationships when they lack other options. If it is your case, perhaps you’re too shy to meet other people who might like you. Focus your energy on getting out of your comfort zone and attending gatherings where you can meet new people. Volunteering works wonderfully and also allows you to do some good. Or perhaps, you do not have decent options for partners because, even if you went out and met new people, you would not be attractive enough for them. If this is your case, work on yourself and read a few books that explain how to develop those qualities that would make you a suitable mate (but avoid books promising shortcuts).

——陷入有害关系：人们通常会在缺乏其他选择时才会陷入并维持有害关系。如果你也面临这种情况，或许是因为你太害羞，不敢去认识其他可能喜欢你的人。你应该把精力放在走出舒适区，参加一些可以结识新朋友的聚会上。做志愿者是个不错的选择，还能让你做一些有益的事情。或者，也许你根本没有合适的伴侣选择，因为即使你走出去认识了新朋友，你对他们来说也缺乏吸引力。如果是这样，那就努力提升自己，读一些关于如何培养成为理想伴侣所需品质的书籍（但要避免那些承诺走捷径的书籍）。

– Working a job that destroys your soul : there are many reasons people end up in a job they do not like, but there is a single reason they do not quit: they became dependent on it. Perhaps, they rely on the salary. Perhaps, they depend on the prestige and status it provides. Or perhaps, they depend on the adrenaline they get from working at it. In any case, the solution is simple but hard: find out what you are dependent on and either lower your need for it or find yourself other options that can provide a similar payoff. For example, if you rely on your salary because your lifestyle requires it, consider getting rid of your most expensive habits and possessions. Alternatively, find yourself other sources of income (including other jobs). I’m not saying it’s easy. But staying addicted is not good for your life and health. Perhaps, you will consider your options and then decide that staying at your current job is the best choice. That’s okay. At least, knowing that you had options and yet chose to stay at your job means that it’s your choice rather than something that happened to you. (If you do decide to stay at the job you don’t like, remember that making it better is an option too. Learning a new skill and negotiating your salary and tasks are great places to start.)

——从事一份让你身心俱疲的工作：人们最终从事一份自己不喜欢的工作的原因有很多，但他们不辞职的原因却只有一个：他们已经对这份工作产生了依赖。或许，他们依赖的是薪水；或许，他们依赖的是工作带来的声望和地位；又或许，他们依赖的是工作带来的刺激感。无论如何，解决办法看似简单却很难：找出你依赖的是什么，然后降低对它的依赖，或者寻找其他能带来类似回报的选择。例如，如果你依赖薪水是因为你的生活方式需要它，那么不妨考虑戒掉你最昂贵的习惯和物品。或者，寻找其他收入来源（包括其他工作）。我并不是说这很容易。但长期沉迷于某项工作对你的生活和健康有害。或许，你会权衡各种选择，最终决定继续留在目前的工作岗位上。这也没关系。至少，你知道自己有其他选择，却仍然选择留下，这意味着这是你自己的选择，而不是被迫做出的决定。 （如果你决定继续做这份你不喜欢的工作，记住，改善工作也是一种选择。学习一项新技能，以及协商你的薪资和工作内容，都是很好的开始。）

#↩
Rule 67
规则67

Life is about cultivating independence.

人生在于培养独立自主的能力。

“For a relationship to be healthy, both people must be willing and able to both say no and hear no” – bestselling author Mark Manson

“一段健康的关系，双方都必须愿意并且能够说‘不’，也能听取‘不’”——畅销书作家马克·曼森

In the previous section, I talked about the damages produced by toxic relationships.

在上一节中，我谈到了有害关系造成的危害。

Why do people choose to be in toxic relationships? Because they aren’t able to be independent.

人们为什么会选择身处有害的关系中？因为他们无法独立。

If someone cannot carry their own weight, they will rely on others, even if these others are toxic. Hence, needy people attract toxic relationships.

如果一个人无法自立，就会依赖他人，即使这些人是有害的。因此，有依赖性的人往往会吸引有害的关系。

Independence is the solution.

独立才是解决之道。

Being independent does not mean being alone. Instead, it means being comfortable with being alone, when it so happens that you are alone.

独立并不意味着孤独。相反，它意味着当你恰好独处时，能够坦然接受独处。

The moment you are independent, you will be able to choose the people you allow into your life. If you discover that someone has a negative impact on your life, you will be able to say goodbye to them, because you do not need them.

当你经济独立后，你就能自主选择允许哪些人进入你的生活。如果你发现某人对你的生活产生了负面影响，你就可以和他们说再见，因为你不再需要他们。

I have seen this in my life. My relationships weren’t particularly good until I learned to be comfortable spending time alone with myself. Once I did, my relationships improved significantly.

我亲身经历过这种情况。在我学会享受独处时光之前，我的人际关系一直不太好。一旦我做到了这一点，我的人际关系就显著改善了。

If you are okay with being alone with yourself, you will always have a better option than spending time with a toxic person: spending it with yourself. So, you won’t get hurt and limited by them.

如果你能享受独处的时光，那么比起和有毒的人相处，你永远都有一个更好的选择：那就是独处。这样，你就不会受到他们的伤害和限制。

That will give you time to work on yourself. As a result, you will become a better person who can attract better friends and partners.

这样你就有时间提升自己。结果，你会成为一个更好的人，从而吸引到更好的朋友和伴侣。

I would go so far as saying that life is about cultivating independence, for so much good emerges from it.

我甚至可以说，人生在于培养独立性，因为独立性会带来很多好处。

Again: this does not mean being alone. It means being comfortable with the possibility of being alone. It gives you a worthy option without obliging you to take it.

再次强调：这并不意味着要独处。而是要坦然接受独处的可能性。它为你提供了一个值得考虑的选择，但并不强迫你接受。

ACTION:

行动：

Does any relationship in your life drain more energy than it provides? If yes, it is time to consider terminating it or at least establishing some firm boundaries.

你生活中是否有某些关系消耗你的精力多于它带给你的精力？如果是，那么是时候考虑结束这段关系，或者至少要划清界限了。

If you find it challenging to do or even consider, you are not independent yet. Developing your independence should be your priority.

如果你觉得做某件事甚至考虑这件事都很困难，那么你还没有真正独立。培养独立能力应该是你的首要任务。

If you do not have a way to sustain yourself or a place to live, invest as much effort as possible into acquiring them. Carry your own weight.

如果你没有谋生手段或住所，就要尽一切努力去获得这些。要自食其力。

The next step is developing options. Try to meet as many people as possible by participating in events in your city.

下一步是拓展人脉。尽量多参加所在城市的活动，结识更多的人。

Becoming confident in your capacity to attract friends and romantic partners is a prerequisite for being able to reject those who are not worth your time.

对自己吸引朋友和恋爱对象的能力充满信心，是能够拒绝那些不值得你浪费时间的人的先决条件。

Having options is the prerequisite for saying no to toxic relationships.

拥有选择权是拒绝有害关系的先决条件。

#↩
Rule 68
规则68

To win negotiations, build independence

要赢得谈判，就要建立独立性。

The most important factor in negotiations is the willingness to walk away.

谈判中最重要的因素是放弃谈判的意愿。

The more easily you can walk away, the more likely the negotiation will end on your terms. Your counterpart will have to make concessions just to prevent you from leaving.

你越容易抽身离开，谈判就越有可能按照你的条件结束。你的对方为了不让你离开，就不得不做出让步。

Conversely, the more you need to conclude the deal, the more likely the negotiation will end on your counterpart’s terms. Therefore, you will have to make concessions just to prevent them from leaving.

反之，你越是急于达成交易，谈判就越有可能以对方的条件结束。因此，你不得不做出让步，才能避免对方离开。

If negotiations are determined by the ability to walk away, then it becomes imperative for you to build such an ability for yourself. This is achieved by having options available.

如果谈判的成败取决于能否中途退出，那么你必须培养这种能力。而做到这一点的关键在于拥有多种选择。

The more options you have outside of the negotiation at hand, the better you will fare during it.

在当前谈判之外，你拥有的选择越多，你在谈判过程中就越有利。

ACTION:

行动：

Think about a negotiation you might have to enter soon (are you about to buy a house or a car? Are you about to negotiate your salary?). If nothing comes to mind, think about a recent negotiation you’ve participated in.

想想你近期可能要进行的谈判（比如买房买车？或者谈薪资？）。如果一时想不出什么例子，那就想想你最近参与过的谈判。

Do you have (or did you have) alternatives? If not, what could they be? What would you have to do now to get some for yourself?

你是否有（或曾经有）其他选择？如果没有，可能是什么？你现在需要做些什么才能获得这些选择？

For example, before negotiating your salary, spend a few hours researching your value in the marketplace. If you decided to work for another company, would they hire you? For how much?

例如，在协商薪资之前，花几个小时调查一下你在市场上的价值。如果你决定为另一家公司工作，他们会聘用你吗？薪资会是多少？

In the unfortunate event that your analysis would reveal that no company would hire you, your next action point becomes to develop the competencies and proofs of competence that will make you a desirable hire.

如果不幸的是，你的分析表明没有公司会雇用你，那么你的下一步行动就是培养能力和证明能力，使你成为理想的员工。

#↩
Rule 69
规则69

Success isn’t being on top of a hierarchy,
it is standing outside all hierarchies

成功不在于身居高位，而在于超越所有等级制度。

( – Nassim Nicholas Taleb)

（——纳西姆·尼古拉斯·塔勒布）

Being part of a hierarchy (by choice) comes with responsibilities towards that hierarchy. For example, meetings to attend, ideas to profess, taboos to respect, and people to spend time with.

自愿加入某个等级制度意味着要对该等级制度承担责任。例如，参加会议、表达观点、遵守禁忌以及与相关人员共事。

The more we depend on a hierarchy, the less free we are. Even if we are at its top. Especially if we are at its top.

我们越依赖等级制度，就越缺乏自由。即便我们身处等级制度的顶端，尤其如此。

True success lies in developing personal independence so that we do not need any hierarchy. Even if we happen to become part of any, if we are truly independent, we will not care about doing something that might endanger our position within the hierarchy.

真正的成功在于培养个人独立性，从而摆脱对任何等级制度的依赖。即使我们身处某个等级制度之中，如果我们真正独立，就不会在意去做任何可能危及自身地位的事情。

The freedom of being independent is the difference between a stressful life and an enjoyable one.

独立自主的自由，决定了你是过着充满压力的生活，还是过着充满乐趣的生活。

ACTION:

行动：

Think about a hierarchy you are a part of. Perhaps you’re at its top, or at its bottom, or in the middle. It doesn’t matter.

想想你身处的某个层级结构。也许你处于顶端，也许处于底端，也许处于中间位置。这都无关紧要。

How does being part of the hierarchy restrict your behavior and create obligations? How does it limit your life?

身处等级制度之中，你的行为会受到哪些限制，你的义务又会受到哪些限制？它会如何限制你的生活？

How would your life change for the better if you didn’t depend on that hierarchy anymore? What options would become available to you?

如果你不再依赖那种等级制度，你的生活会发生哪些积极的改变？你会有哪些选择？

#↩
Rule 70
规则70

Integrity is the highest form of loyalty

正直是忠诚的最高形式。

In his book “The 7 Habits of Highly Successful People”, bestselling author Stephen Covey talks about loyalty and integrity.

畅销书作家史蒂芬·柯维在他的著作《高效能人士的七个习惯》中谈到了忠诚和正直。

“Integrity is a higher value than loyalty. Or better put, integrity is the highest form of loyalty. Integrity means being integrated or centered on principles, not on people, organizations, or even family. You will find that the root of most issues people deal with is “is it popular (acceptable, political), or is it right?” When we prioritize being loyal to a person or group over doing what we feel to be right, we lose integrity. We may temporarily gain popularity or build loyalty, but downstream, this loss of integrity will undermine even those relationships.”

正直比忠诚更重要。或者更确切地说，正直是忠诚的最高形式。正直意味着以原则为中心，而非以人、组织甚至家庭为中心。你会发现，人们面临的大多数问题的根源在于“这样做是否受欢迎（是否合乎情理、是否符合政治），还是是否正确？”当我们把对某人或某个群体的忠诚置于我们认为正确的事情之上时，我们就失去了正直。我们或许能暂时获得人气或建立忠诚，但从长远来看，这种正直的丧失甚至会破坏这些关系。

Having integrity makes others trust you. This is good because if people trust you, they will show you their best side.

正直的品格能赢得他人的信任。这很好，因为如果人们信任你，他们就会展现自己最好的一面。

Trust derives from being able to predict how a person will react. If people know you will respond to a given situation, they will trust you. If you have integrity and faultlessly follow your principles, people know that you will always act according to them. They will be able to predict your actions. Therefore, they will trust you and show you their best side.

信任源于能够预测一个人的反应。如果人们知道你会如何应对某种情况，他们就会信任你。如果你正直诚信，始终恪守原则，人们就知道你会言行一致。他们能够预测你的行为，因此会信任你，并向你展现他们最好的一面。

If, instead, people perceive that you act with loyalty to people rather than principles, they will not trust you. They will always think in the back of their mind, “What if he likes or needs another person more than myself? Will he betray me?”

相反，如果人们觉得你忠于人而非忠于原则，他们就不会信任你。他们会一直暗自想：“如果他更喜欢或更需要别人怎么办？他会背叛我吗？”

They will show you their worst side, the fearful one.

他们会向你展现他们最阴暗、最恐惧的一面。

ACTION:

行动：

Develop integrity. First, let people know what your principles are. Secondly, whenever you make a choice, base it on your principles. Because you did the first step, the second one will be easier. If you make clear to people that you are loyal to your principles more than to them, making a decision based on your principles will not feel like a betrayal – neither to you nor to them.

培养正直品格。首先，要让别人知道你的原则是什么。其次，无论何时做选择，都要以你的原则为依据。因为你已经完成了第一步，第二步就会更容易。如果你让别人明白，你忠于原则胜过忠于他们，那么基于原则做出的决定就不会让你感到背叛——无论对你还是对他们来说都是如此。

If instead, you skip the first step and let people think that you are loyal to them unconditionally , you will think that they expect you to take your decision with them in mind (and you are probably correct in thinking so).

相反，如果你跳过第一步，让人们认为你对他们无条件忠诚，你就会认为他们希望你在做决定时考虑到他们（而且你的想法很可能是正确的）。

Remember: whenever you feel uncomfortable acting on your principles, the chances are that it is because you haven’t been clear with the people around you about your principles.

记住：每当你觉得坚持自己的原则会让你感到不舒服时，很可能是因为你还没有向周围的人清楚地表达你的原则。

If you act with integrity, loyal to your principles, people will trust you more, not less.

如果你为人正直，忠于自己的原则，人们会更加信任你，而不是更加不信任你。

#↩
Rule 71
规则71

Extraordinary people
杰出人士
are extraordinarily selective
都极具选择性

“If you want to live an exceptional and extraordinary life, you have to give up many of the things that are part of a normal one.” – author Srinivas Rao

“如果你想拥有非凡的人生，就必须放弃许多普通人生中的一部分。”——作家斯里尼瓦斯·拉奥

The amount of time and energy you can spend in your life is limited. You need to choose what to spend it on.

你一生中能投入的时间和精力是有限的。你需要选择把它们花在什么事情上。

Everyone chooses how to spend their time, but how many make this choice intentionally? How many contemplate the influence of their actions on themselves before deciding what to do?

每个人都可以选择如何度过自己的时间，但有多少人是经过深思熟虑后做出这种选择呢？又有多少人在决定做什么之前会思考自己的行为会对自身产生怎样的影响呢？

…

As seen in the second chapter of this book, compounding is an incredibly impactful phenomenon. By restricting the number of activities to spend your time on, you iterate on them faster, thus increasing their compounding rate, which in turn will produce even greater value to you.

正如本书第二章所述，复利是一种影响极其深远的现象。通过限制你投入时间的活动数量，你可以更快地迭代完成这些活动，从而提高它们的复利速度，进而为你创造更大的价值。

ACTION:

行动：

Think about how you spent your time last week. What activity are you the least likely to be proud of in a few years? Remove it from your schedule.

想想你上周都做了些什么。几年后，你最不可能为哪项活动感到自豪？把它从你的日程安排中移除。

You often do not have to remove an activity completely, only its least useful parts. For example, having read a useless book doesn’t mean you should not read anymore, but that you should improve your book selection process. The same applies to the friends with whom you spend time. If you could only meet with 50% of your friends, which ones would you spend time with?

你通常不必完全放弃一项活动，只需剔除其中最无用的部分即可。例如，读了一本没用的书并不意味着你就不应该再读书了，而是应该改进你的选书方式。这同样适用于你花时间相处的朋友。如果你只能和一半的朋友见面，你会选择和哪一半呢？

#↩
Rule 72
规则72

Do not despise what you need

不要轻视你所需要的东西。

“If you secretly despise wealth, it will elude you.” – Naval Ravikant

“如果你内心鄙视财富，它就会离你而去。”——纳瓦尔·拉维坎特

Many despise those who have what they desire. Perhaps, they hate these individuals because they have what they want, that’s envy. Or perhaps, they despise them because of some stereotype. For example, some people despise those with a successful career because, too often, having a successful career is associated with involvement in office politics or neglecting one’s family.

许多人鄙视那些拥有自己想要的东西的人。或许，他们憎恨这些人仅仅是因为这些人拥有了自己想要的东西，这是嫉妒。又或许，他们鄙视这些人是因为某种刻板印象。例如，有些人鄙视事业成功的人，因为在他们看来，事业成功往往意味着参与办公室政治或忽视家庭。

However, despising those who have what you desire is problematic.

然而，鄙视那些拥有你所渴望之物的人是有问题的。

Imagine the following scenario. If you thought that everyone with a successful career is a bad person, you would naturally want to avoid being seen as a career-seeker. You would avoid doing anything that “career-seekers” do, including things needed for professional success that aren’t bad. For example, spending time with your boss to discuss priorities or behaving confidently in meetings. You would end up without a fulfilling career, even though you could have had it without compromising your ethics.

想象一下这样的场景：如果你认为所有事业成功的人都是坏人，你自然会想要避免被视为求职者。你会避免做任何“求职者”会做的事情，包括那些对职业成功至关重要但并非坏事的事情。例如，花时间与老板讨论工作重点，或者在会议上表现得自信。最终，你可能无法获得一份令人满意的职业，即使你原本可以在不违背自身道德的情况下获得成功。

Imagine another scenario. If you thought that the rich were bad people, you would naturally want to avoid being seen as one. So, you would not do “what rich people do,” including what got them rich – for example, investing, even though there are ethical ways to invest.

设想另一种情况。如果你认为富人都是坏人，你自然会想要避免被视为富人。因此，你不会去做“富人做的事”，包括让他们致富的方式——例如投资，即使投资也有合乎道德的方式。

The trick is to be specific. Never despise people for who they are, but only for their specific behaviors . For example, do not despise people with successful careers. Instead, say, despise those who stab their colleagues in the back. This way, you will be able to stay true to your ethics without needlessly limiting your opportunities.

关键在于具体。不要因为一个人的身份而鄙视他，而应该只针对他的特定行为。例如，不要鄙视那些事业成功的人，而应该鄙视那些背后捅刀子的人。这样，你既能坚守自己的道德准则，又不会不必要地限制自己的发展机会。

Do not despise salespeople. Instead, despise those who deceive their clients.

不要轻视销售人员，而要轻视那些欺骗客户的人。

Do not despise rich people. Instead, despise those who get rich by putting others at risk.

不要鄙视富人，而要鄙视那些靠危害他人而致富的人。

Do not despise extroverts. Instead, despise the disrespectful and the tactless.

不要轻视外向的人，而要轻视那些不尊重他人、缺乏分寸的人。

Despising people makes you avoid not unethical behaviors but also ethical ones (if they are exhibited by someone you do not like). Instead, despising behaviors (rather than people) allows you to adopt the behaviors which are good while avoiding those which are bad.

厌恶他人会让你避免的不仅是不道德的行为，还有合乎道德的行为（如果这些行为是由你不喜欢的人表现出来的话）。相反，厌恶行为（而不是厌恶人）会让你采纳良好的行为，同时避免不良的行为。

If you hate those who have what you want, you will prevent yourself from doing the ethical things that will get you what you want.

如果你憎恨那些拥有你想要的东西的人，你就会阻止自己去做那些能让你得到你想要的东西的合乎道德的事情。

“It’s not who you are that holds you back; it’s who you think you’re not.” – Thibault (@Kpaxs on Twitter)

“阻碍你的不是你是谁，而是你认为自己不是谁。”——蒂博（推特用户@Kpaxs）

ACTION:

行动：

Think about a category of people you do not want to be associated with.

想想你不想和哪一类人扯上关系。

Do they have something you desire?

他们那里有你想要的东西吗？

If yes, make a list of their behaviors that helped them achieve that.

如果答案是肯定的，请列出帮助他们实现这一目标的行为。

Then, examine each item in the list one by one . Is the behavior inherently unethical? Or are there ways to express that behavior ethically? If so, should you consider adopting it

然后，逐一审视清单上的每一项。这种行为本身是否不道德？或者是否存在合乎道德的表达方式？如果存在，你是否应该考虑采纳？

#↩
Rule 73
规则73

The Silver Rule is better
银律比黄金律更好
than the Golden Rule

The Golden Rule is as follows: “treat others as you wish others would treat you.”

黄金法则如下：“己所不欲，勿施于人。”

It seems a very nice code of conduct until you realize that people’s preferences might differ from yours.

这看起来似乎是一条非常好的行为准则，直到你意识到人们的喜好可能与你不同。

As much as you might think you know what others need, the truth is that you don’t. Moreover, what is good for one person might be harmful to another.

即使你自认为很了解别人的需求，但事实并非如此。而且，对一个人有益的东西，对另一个人可能有害。

Instead, the so-called Silver Rule is universal: “do not do unto others as you would not have them do unto you.”

相反，所谓的“白银法则”是普遍适用的：“己所不欲，勿施于人”。

The Silver Rule recognizes the sovereignty of the individual. Moreover, it follows one of the most important principles, one doctors swear upon, the Hippocratic Oath: “First do no harm.”

银律承认个人的自主权。此外，它遵循医生们宣誓遵守的最重要的原则之一——希波克拉底誓言：“首先，不伤害病人。”

Every intervention you make to another person’s life will have side effects. Most often, you cannot predict what they will be. Unless you are an ER doctor operating on an unconscious patient, before helping, ask. Ask what they might need. Ask if they want help. And if they decline, do not insist. At most, tell them you will be there in case of need. But do not help unless they tell you they want your help and in what way

你对他人生活的每一次干预都会产生副作用。而且大多数情况下，你无法预知这些副作用是什么。除非你是急诊室医生，正在为昏迷病人做手术，否则在提供帮助之前，请先询问。问问他们可能需要什么。问问他们是否需要帮助。如果他们拒绝，不要强求。最多，你可以告诉他们，如果需要，你会随时提供帮助。但除非他们明确表示需要你的帮助以及需要的方式，否则不要轻易伸出援手。

ACTION:

行动：

The next time you want to help someone, ask them first. Uncover their real needs. If you help them, ensure that you do not make them more dependent on external help.

下次你想帮助别人时，先问问他们的需求。了解他们真正的需要。如果你帮助他们，务必确保不要让他们更加依赖外界的帮助。

Help them for their sake, not yours.

帮助他们是为了他们好，而不是为了你自己。

In a previous chapter of this book, we saw how people who insist on being part of the solution should not be trusted. Do not insist on being part of the solution.

本书前一章已经讲到，那些坚持要成为解决方案一部分的人不可信。所以，不要坚持要成为解决方案的一部分。

#↩

Make yourself antifragile

让自己变得反脆弱

Rules 74 to 77

规则74至77

Antifragile, a term coined by Nassim Taleb, indicates what gets stronger in response to usage and variation. Think about our muscles: they love being used! The more we use them, the stronger they get. So, they are antifragile. Compare that to the fragile, like a car: the more we use it, the more it risks breaking down.

反脆弱（Antifragile）一词由纳西姆·塔勒布（Nassim Taleb）提出，指的是事物在使用和变化中变得更加强大。想想我们的肌肉：它们喜欢被使用！我们使用得越多，它们就越强壮。因此，它们是反脆弱的。与之形成对比的是脆弱的事物，比如汽车：我们使用得越多，它发生故障的风险就越大。

If you think about it, lifting weights is a form of variation: we vary the load on our muscles. Therefore, we can define the antifragile as what benefits from variation. Our muscles love some degree of variation, whereas for the fragile, the less variation, the better.

仔细想想，举重本身就是一种变化：我们通过改变肌肉的负荷来达到锻炼效果。因此，我们可以将“反脆弱”定义为能够从变化中获益的事物。我们的肌肉喜欢一定程度的变化，而对于脆弱的个体来说，变化越少越好。

The same applies to people. Some are fragile in the sense that in some domains, such as their work, they are hurt by variation. This is the case of an employee who sees any change as a threat. Conversely, other people are antifragile. For them, most changes are opportunities, so they welcome them. For the antifragile, change becomes almost a competitive advantage.

这同样适用于人。有些人比较脆弱，因为在某些领域，比如工作中，变化会伤害到他们。例如，有些员工会把任何变化都视为威胁。相反，另一些人则具有反脆弱性。对他们来说，大多数变化都是机遇，因此他们乐于接受变化。对于反脆弱者而言，变化几乎成了一种竞争优势。

If you haven’t read Taleb’s book, Antifragile, I strongly advise you to do so, for there is much more to it than I can talk about in a few pages. Here I had to make some simplifications. That said, I share here a few practical applications of this concept.

如果你还没读过塔勒布的《反脆弱》这本书，我强烈建议你去读一读，因为书中的内容远非我这几页纸所能涵盖。在这里，我不得不做一些简化。即便如此，我还是想分享一些这个概念的实际应用。

#↩
Rule 74
规则74

Trigger overcompensation

触发过度补偿

Right after some physical exercise, we feel tired. But, the day after, we feel more energetic and physically and emotionally stronger.

运动后我们会感到疲倦，但第二天就会感觉精力充沛，身心都更加强壮。

Physical exercise consists of being fatigued now in order not to be fatigued later.

体育锻炼的目的是为了避免日后再次感到疲劳。

Similarly, learning consists of feeling confused now to avoid being confused later.

同样，学习也包括现在感到困惑，以便以后避免困惑。

In general, in biological domains, the long-term effects generate by an activity are the opposite of the short-term ones. This is because of overcompensation mechanisms.

一般来说，在生物领域，一项活动产生的长期效应与短期效应相反。这是由于过度补偿机制造成的。

ACTION:

行动：

The next time you feel weak, hit the gym.

下次感到虚弱的时候，就去健身房。

The next time you find yourself tired, do some exercise.

下次感到疲倦时，就做些运动吧。

The next time you feel confused, learn that you need to learn.

下次当你感到困惑时，要明白你需要学习。

Then, observe the reaction the day after. Notice how you feel better.

然后，观察第二天的反应。注意你感觉是否好转。

The next time you exercise or learn, try to remind yourself of the last time you did and how you felt much better the day after. Practice seeing the long-term in the short-term.

下次锻炼或学习时，试着回想一下上次锻炼或学习后的感受，以及第二天感觉有多好。练习在短期目标中着眼长远。

#↩
Rule 75
规则75

Secure survival
在优化性能之前，确保生存
before optimizing performance

The skier winning the ski championship isn’t the fastest skier. It’s the fastest one of those who didn’t break a leg.

赢得滑雪锦标赛冠军的滑雪运动员并不是速度最快的，而是那些没摔断腿的人中速度最快的。

The most successful investor isn’t the most brilliant investor. It’s the most brilliant one of those who didn’t go bankrupt.

最成功的投资者并非最聪明的投资者，而是那些没有破产的投资者中最聪明的那一个。

The employee that gets promoted to CEO isn’t the best-performing employee. It’s the best-performing one of those who didn’t burn out.

被提拔为CEO的员工并非业绩最好的员工，而是业绩最好且没有精疲力竭的员工中的一员。

In general, performance is subordinate to survival.

总的来说，生存才是首要考虑因素。

Performance is important, yes, but only if you don’t “blow up” first.

表现固然重要，但前提是你不会先“崩溃”。

ACTION:

行动：

Train the hardest you can while avoiding major injuries.

在避免严重受伤的前提下，尽你所能地进行高强度训练。

Work the hardest you can without burning out or sacrificing your personal life.

尽你所能努力工作，但不要让自己筋疲力竭或牺牲个人生活。

Take risks with an upside without taking risks whose downside might represent a game over.

承担有收益的风险，但不要承担可能导致游戏结束的风险。

Which other applications of this principle might apply to your life?

这一原则还有哪些应用可以适用于你的生活？

#↩
Rule 76
规则76

Hit the sweet spot

击中最佳点

On the one hand, it’s risky not to take risks. The world constantly changes and progresses, and someone who doesn’t try the new will soon fall behind.

一方面，不冒险是有风险的。世界瞬息万变，不断进步，不去尝试新事物的人很快就会落后。

On the other hand, it’s also risky to take risks. Lives ruined, permanent injuries, and broken reputations all started with taking risks.

另一方面，冒险本身也存在风险。人生被毁、终身残疾、名誉受损，这一切都始于冒险。

So, should you take risks or not?

那么，你该不该冒险呢？

You should distinguish between calculated risks whose consequences you can recover from and recklessness whose consequences might permanently debilitate you. There is a sweet spot where you expose yourself to the former but not the latter, and that’s a good place to aim. 36

你应该区分经过深思熟虑的风险（其后果可以承受）和鲁莽行为（其后果可能永久性地损害你的身心健康）。存在一个最佳平衡点，既能让你承担前者的风险，又能避免后者的风险，这才是你应该努力的方向。

ACTION

行动

What’s your sweet spot? For example, if you practice a sport, be playful with risks with high upside and low downside (for example, going 1% harder or trying a new move in a safe environment) but careful with high-downside risks (for example, going 10% harder or trying a dangerous move in an uncontrolled environment).

你的最佳状态是什么？例如，如果你练习一项运动，可以尝试高收益低风险的冒险（例如，在安全的环境下增加 1% 的难度或尝试新动作），但要谨慎对待高风险（例如，在不受控制的环境下增加 10% 的难度或尝试危险动作）。

As another example, as an investor, never go “all-in” on a single investment, no matter how high its expected returns are. You want to ensure that you won’t go bankrupt if it goes badly. That said, you probably do not want to keep all your money in the bank either. Instead, I would consider a portfolio of uncorrelated investments, some safe and some more aggressive.

再举个例子，作为投资者，无论预期收益有多高，都不要把所有资金都投入到单一投资中。你需要确保即使投资失败也不会破产。话虽如此，你可能也不想把所有钱都存在银行里。相反，我会考虑构建一个由不相关投资组合组成的投资组合，其中一些投资稳健，一些投资则更具风险。

#↩
Rule 77
规则77

Consider yourself a container

把自己想象成一个容器

Early in my career, I was told that my presentations were boring.

在我职业生涯早期，有人告诉我我的演讲很无聊。

I could have taken the feedback as targeted towards my general persona, as if people said I was boring. If I had, my reaction would probably have been defensive (“you didn’t get it!”). I would have protected my ego but learned nothing from the feedback. Or perhaps my reaction would have been to lose all my confidence – not good either.

我本可以把这些反馈理解为针对我整体人格的评价，比如别人说我很无趣。如果真是这样，我的反应很可能是辩解（“你们根本没听懂！”）。我会维护自己的自尊，但却无法从反馈中学到任何东西。或者，我的反应可能是彻底失去自信——这也不好。

Instead, I redirected the feedback to my mental patterns. I asked myself, “Which of my mental patterns caused the presentation to be boring?” Then, I understood that I had been boring because too much text was on my slides (my mental pattern of putting too much information). By redirecting feedback towards my mental patterns, I learned from the feedback and became a better presenter. I ended up presenting at the world’s largest conference in my field.

相反，我把反馈转向了我的思维模式。我问自己：“我的哪些思维模式导致演讲枯燥乏味？” 然后，我意识到，之所以枯燥乏味，是因为幻灯片上的文字太多（这是我习惯性地塞入过多信息）。通过将反馈转向我的思维模式，我从反馈中学习，并成为了一名更优秀的演讲者。最终，我得以在业内规模最大的全球会议上进行演讲。

We have already seen this principle in Rule 35, “attribute feedback to the specific.” Here, I want to highlight the prerequisite for being able to do so. If you consider yourself an immutable ego, you won’t be able to learn from negative feedback. This is because your only options are to reject the feedback or let it destroy you. Instead, if you consider yourself a container of mental patterns (beliefs, scripts, reactions), you can redirect negative feedback to one of your mental patterns and let the feedback destroy the pattern in question without hurting you.

我们在规则35“将反馈归因于具体事物”中已经看到过这个原则。在这里，我想强调做到这一点的前提条件。如果你把自己看作一个不可改变的自我，你就无法从负面反馈中学习。这是因为你唯一的选择要么是拒绝反馈，要么是任由它摧毁你。相反，如果你把自己看作一个容纳各种心理模式（信念、脚本、反应）的容器，你就可以将负面反馈重定向到你的某个心理模式，让反馈摧毁该模式，而不会伤害到你。

The prerequisite for learning is considering yourself a container of mental patterns.

学习的前提是把自己视为一个容纳各种思维模式的容器。

…

What does this have to do with antifragility? Well, the antifragile is what benefits from usage, variation, and feedback. The opposite is the fragile, which is what cannot benefit from them.

这和反脆弱性有什么关系呢？反脆弱性是指能够从使用、变化和反馈中获益的事物。与之相反的是脆弱性，它无法从中获益。

Reflecting on Taleb’s book Antifragile , I noticed that the fragile is monolithic – it is either fully intact or fully broken. Instead, the antifragile can be “partially broken.” In particular, it is possible that one of its components breaks but not the whole. That is often what triggers an antifragile reaction and makes the whole stronger. For example, think about biological species. They are antifragile because if a famine kills 10% of the animals, the fittest individuals survive and reproduce. The result is that the next generation will be fitter and stronger. But this can only apply if it’s possible that some but not all species members die.

反思塔勒布的著作《反脆弱》，我注意到脆弱的概念是整体性的——要么完全完好，要么完全破碎。而反脆弱的概念则可以是“部分破碎”。具体来说，它可能只是某个组成部分发生了改变，但整体并未受损。这往往是引发反脆弱反应、增强整体强度的因素。例如，想想生物物种。它们之所以具有反脆弱性，是因为即使饥荒导致10%的动物死亡，最适应环境的个体也能生存下来并繁衍后代。结果是，下一代会更加适应环境，更加强壮。但这只有在物种成员可能部分而非全部死亡的情况下才成立。

The same applies to you. You can only be antifragile if it is possible that feedback destroys part of you without excessively harming you. For this to happen, you need to think of yourself as a container of mental patterns and identify with the container, not with the patterns themselves.

这同样适用于你。只有当反馈有可能摧毁你的一部分，但又不会对你造成过度伤害时，你才能做到反脆弱。要做到这一点，你需要把自己看作是一个容纳各种思维模式的容器，并认同这个容器，而不是模式本身。

The exercise below will clarify this concept and help you apply it to your life.

下面这个练习将帮助你理解这个概念，并帮助你将其应用到生活中。

ACTION:

行动：

Here are some examples of how the principle above can apply to your situation. Underline those relevant to you, then write down how to implement them.

以下是一些上述原则如何应用于你的情况的例子。请在与你相关的部分划线，然后写下如何实施。

- Mastery. Pick one skill of yours (for example, delivering engaging presentations) . Which mental patterns of yours are put to use when you engage in that skill (e.g., your tone of voice, your storytelling style, your slide designs)? Is there any pattern with which you identify that you cannot let go even if you were told it was holding you back? If so, wouldn’t it be better if you identified with the container (being a great presenter regardless of the style used) rather than with the mental patterns themselves (a particular way of presenting) ?

- 精通。选择你的一项技能（例如，发表引人入胜的演讲）。当你运用这项技能时，你会采用哪些思维模式（例如，你的语气、你的叙事风格、你的幻灯片设计）？是否存在某种你无法摆脱的模式，即使有人告诉你它会阻碍你？如果是这样，与其执着于思维模式本身（某种特定的演讲方式），不如将注意力集中在“容器”（无论采用何种风格都能成为一名优秀的演讲者）上，岂不是更好？

- Investing. Write down the assets in your portfolio (for example, this and that stock) . Are any of those part of your identity? If so, you might disregard information revealing that they are too risky. Instead, consider identifying with being a great investor (the container) rather than with specific stocks.

投资。写下你投资组合中的资产（例如，这只股票和那只股票）。其中哪些是你身份认同的一部分？如果是，你可能会忽略那些揭示它们风险过高的信息。相反，你应该将身份认同放在“优秀投资者”这个概念上（即“容器”），而不是具体的股票上。

In general, whenever you consider your identity monolithic, you also make it fragile. Feedback stops being an opportunity for improvement and becomes instead a threat to avoid.

总的来说，当你把自己的身份视为单一整体时，它也会变得脆弱。反馈不再是改进的机会，而变成了需要避免的威胁。

Instead, whenever you identify with a container of patterns, you become antifragile. Feedback helps you get rid of what was holding you back.

相反，当你认同某种模式时，你就会变得具有反脆弱性。反馈能帮助你摆脱阻碍你前进的因素。

To become antifragile, stop being monolithic.

要想变得反脆弱，就不要做铁板一块。

#↩

Be fair

要公平。

Rules 78 to 79

规则78至79

There are many reasons to be fair.

公平的理由有很多。

One is that it is the right thing to do. Another is karma – not intended as a mystic force, but the very material fact that people remember how you treated them, which in turn influences how they treat you.

其一是这样做是正确的。其二是因果报应——并非指某种神秘力量，而是指人们会记住你如何对待他们，而这反过来又会影响他们如何对待你这一事实。

But there’s one more reason to be fair, and this chapter covers it.

但公平地说，还有另一个原因，本章将对此进行阐述。

Rule 78
规则78

Above all, be fair

最重要的是，要公平。

You might know me as a writer, but my “day job” is training managers. And much of becoming a great manager can be summarized as, “above all, be fair.” This is because it’s impossible to be fair if one sets ambiguous objectives, doesn’t provide frequent feedback, keeps others in the dark, and won’t explain decisions. Conversely, if you are truly committed to being a fair manager and assume responsibility for any feeling of unfairness between your subordinates, naturally you will have to do everything great managers do.

你或许知道我是一名作家，但我的“日常工作”是培训经理人。成为一名优秀经理的关键可以概括为“最重要的是，要公平”。这是因为，如果目标含糊不清、不提供频繁的反馈、对他人隐瞒信息、不解释决策，就不可能做到公平。反之，如果你真心致力于成为一名公平的经理，并愿意承担起消除下属之间任何不公平感的责任，那么你自然会做到优秀经理人所做的一切。

The same applies to social relationships. Being fair to your friends or spouse requires you to be honest and proactive in your communication and in your other actions. Commit to fairness, and the right actions will follow.

这同样适用于人际关系。公平对待朋友或伴侣，意味着你在沟通和其他行动中都要诚实且积极主动。秉持公平原则，正确的做法自然会随之而来。

ACTION:

行动：

First, pick a group of people that you commit to being fair. It could be your team, your colleagues, your customers, your spouse, your friends, etc.

首先，选择一群你承诺公平对待的人。可以是你的团队、同事、客户、配偶、朋友等等。

Then, think about previous times when they felt you treated them unfairly. Whether you did treat them unfairly doesn’t matter – what matters is whether they felt like you treated them unfairly.

然后，想想他们之前是否觉得你对他们不公平。你是否真的对他们不公平并不重要——重要的是他们是否觉得你对他们不公平。

What could you have done differently to prevent them from feeling like that? Could you have been clearer before it’s too late? Could you have been more proactive in your communication? What else?

你本可以做些什么来避免他们有这种感觉？你本可以在为时已晚之前把话说得更清楚些吗？你本可以更积极主动地沟通吗？还有其他什么方法吗？

Next, think about your current engagements with them (things you delegated to them, things they delegated to you, things you agreed to do together, promises you made to each other, and so on.) Is there any chance you and they have a different understanding of your agreement? If so, can you take action today to clarify the misunderstanding?

接下来，想想你目前与他们之间的互动（你委托给他们的事情、他们委托给你的事情、你们共同同意做的事情、你们彼此做出的承诺等等）。你和他们对你们的协议是否存在不同的理解？如果存在，你今天能否采取行动来澄清误解？

#↩
Rule 79
规则79

Too often, the real problem is not what happened but how it was communicated

很多时候，真正的问题不在于发生了什么，而在于如何传达这件事。

Everyone makes mistakes. Your friends and colleagues know that – they make mistakes too. Usually, they will forgive you, unless you did not sincerely demonstrate being sorry.

人都会犯错。你的朋友和同事都知道这一点——他们也会犯错。通常情况下，他们会原谅你，除非你没有真心实意地表示歉意。

An immediate and sincere apology is often enough to prevent any resentment, especially if joined by a genuine, material, and effective effort to repair the damage done, if any.

及时真诚的道歉通常足以消除怨恨，尤其是当同时采取真诚、实质性和有效的措施来弥补造成的损害（如果有的话）时。

Sometimes, the mistake is not even yours. You are simply the conveyor of negative information. In this case, you do not have to apologize. But it is your responsibility to communicate that information as fast and honestly as possible to those affected – especially if delaying has any probability of making the situation worse for them.

有时候，错误甚至并非出自你之手。你只是负面信息的传递者。在这种情况下，你无需道歉。但你有责任尽快、诚实地将信息传达给受影响的人——尤其是在拖延可能会使他们的处境雪上加霜的情况下。

If you communicate the bad news proactively and sincerely, any emotional reaction the recipient will have will be directed at the bad news but not at you. Conversely, if you hold on to the information, people will resent you.

如果你主动且真诚地传达坏消息，对方的任何情绪反应都会指向坏消息本身，而不是你。相反，如果你把消息藏起来，人们会怨恨你。

Any withheld information from a relationship is a risk weighting on it.

任何对一段关系隐瞒的信息都会增加这段关系的风险。

ACTION:

行动：

Think about the last time someone withheld information from you. Would you have been mad at them if they had communicated it to you proactively?

想想上次有人对你隐瞒信息是什么时候。如果他们主动告诉你，你会生气吗？

Now think about the last time you were upset at someone for more than a few minutes. Was it about what they did or about how they communicated it to you?

现在想想你上一次因为某人而生气超过几分钟是什么时候？是因为他们做了什么，还是因为他们跟你沟通的方式？

#↩

Be effective

有效

Rules 80 to 85

规则 80 至 85

If I had to condense to four words my advice for being more effective, it would be “act on the bottleneck.”

如果我必须用四个字来概括我提高效率的建议，那就是“解决瓶颈问题”。

A bottleneck is the one constraining factor or problem preventing efforts from generating significant results. For example, imagine you work for a mediocre company selling a mediocre product. That means that no matter the efforts you put into your current job, you are unlikely to get any significant pay raise. In that case, your company’s and their product’s mediocrity are your bottlenecks. Unless you address them (e.g., by moving to another company), your condition won’t change much. Therefore, it pays to focus on the bottleneck.

瓶颈是指阻碍努力产生显著成果的唯一制约因素或问题。例如，假设你在一家平庸的公司工作，销售一款平庸的产品。这意味着无论你为目前的工作付出多少努力，你都不太可能获得任何显著的加薪。在这种情况下，你所在公司及其产品的平庸之处就是你的瓶颈。除非你解决这些瓶颈（例如，跳槽到另一家公司），否则你的处境不会有太大改变。因此，集中精力解决瓶颈是值得的。

In fact, some of the most effective people I know are constantly laser-focused on identifying and removing bottlenecks, one after the other.

事实上，我认识的一些最有效率的人，总是全神贯注地去发现并逐一消除瓶颈。

This chapter is about becoming more effective by prioritizing well.

本章讲述的是如何通过合理安排优先级来提高效率。

#↩
Rule 80
规则 80

Working hard without checking assumptions is a form of laziness

不经核实就埋头苦干是一种懒惰的表现。

This was probably one of the most painful revelations of my life. It was so painful that I underwent years of denial before internalizing it.

这或许是我人生中最痛苦的领悟之一。它如此痛苦，以至于我花了数年时间才最终接受它。

How can hard work be lazy? After all, hard work is how results are achieved.

努力工作怎么会是懒惰呢？毕竟，努力工作才是取得成果的途径。

This is correct, but not all hard work brings results. Therefore, a question must always precede hard work: will doing this bring me closer to my objectives? Am I working hard to achieve an outcome or to avoid doing something else?

没错，但并非所有的努力都能带来结果。因此，在努力工作之前，必须先问自己一个问题：这样做能让我更接近目标吗？我努力工作是为了达成某个结果，还是为了逃避做其他事情？

Am I doing the most impactful work I can be doing? Or am I doing the hard work I am the most comfortable with?

我是否在做我能做的最有意义的工作？还是我只是在做我最擅长的、最辛苦的工作？

Often, we make choices that are physically exhausting but emotionally lazy. We just keep doing things the most acceptable or comfortable way. Other times, we work hard not because it will bring us closer to our objectives but because it allows us to signal sacrifice and commitment. We think it’s virtuous, but it is lazy.

我们常常做出一些体力消耗巨大却又情感上偷懒的选择。我们只是不断地选择最容易被接受或最舒服的方式来做事。有时，我们努力工作并非为了实现目标，而是为了展现自己的牺牲和奉献。我们认为这是美德，但实际上却是懒惰。

That’s not to say that all hard work is a form of laziness. Of course not. But hard work for the sake of hard work is.

这并不是说所有的努力工作都是懒惰。当然不是。但为了努力工作而努力工作，那就是懒惰。

ACTION:

行动：

Work hard for a short burst. Then stop. Test your assumptions. Did they prove right? Is there a more effective way? What would it be?

短时间内全力以赴，然后停下来。检验你的假设。它们是否正确？是否有更有效的方法？会是什么？

Then, work hard again for another burst. Then stop again. Question again. And so on.

然后，再次努力，再爆发一次。然后再次停下来。再次提问。如此反复。

#↩
Rule 81
第81条规则

Pareto prioritize

帕累托优先级

20% of your clients produce 80% of your revenue.

20% 的客户贡献了 80% 的收入。

20% of the books you read contain 80% of the things you learned.

你读过的书中，有 20% 包含了你所学到的 80% 的知识。

20% of the actions you take at work produce 80% of the value of your work.

你在工作中采取的 20% 的行动，创造了你工作价值的 80%。

Italian mathematician Vilfredo Pareto noticed the following pattern: 20% of the members of a group produce 80% of the impact. It is not a strict rule, but a pattern that you might find applies to many aspects of your life.

意大利数学家维尔弗雷多·帕累托注意到这样一个规律：群体中20%的成员产生了80%的影响。这并非一条铁律，而是一种你可能在生活许多方面都会发现的规律。

The implication is clear: focus your efforts on the 20% of activities that produce the 80% of the returns.

这意味着：将精力集中在能带来 80% 回报的 20% 的活动上。

ACTION:

行动：

Make a list of your friends and circle the 20% of names that produced the best memories.

列出你的朋友名单，圈出其中给你留下最美好回忆的 20% 的名字。

Then, add a few action items to your to-do list to reconnect with these important people and reduce interactions with your other friends (spend less time with them, agree to meet them less often, and so on).

然后，在你的待办事项清单中添加一些行动项目，以便与这些重要的人重新建立联系，并减少与其他朋友的互动（减少与他们相处的时间，减少与他们见面的次数等等）。

Finally, repeat the exercise with books on your to-read list, chores you must make at home, and so on.

最后，用你的待读书单、你必须在家做的家务等等重复这个练习。

(The most attentive readers might have noticed that a few rules – less than five – are repeated twice in this book. This is because I believe they are so important that they are worth repeating twice, although in a different form. Better to repeat the important than to say something less important.)

（最细心的读者可能已经注意到，本书中有几条规则——不到五条——重复了两次。这是因为我认为它们非常重要，值得重复两次，尽管形式有所不同。与其重复一些不太重要的内容，不如重复重要的内容。）

#↩
Rule 82
第82条规则

Go via negativa

通过否定

You might have heard some of the following advice. “To solve your headache, take this pill.” Or “this new smart fridge has a calendar display on its door, it’s an improvement.”
