你可能听过以下一些建议：“想缓解头痛，就吃这种药。”或者“这款新型智能冰箱门上带有日历显示屏，这算是一项改进。”

In the modern world, there is this idea that solving a problem requires adding something new. However, adding something unnatural often carries unpredictable consequences. In the examples above, the headache pill might have a side effect. The “smart” fridge might leave your meat exposed to heat after it failed to restart following a software update. 37

在现代社会，人们普遍认为解决问题需要引入新的事物。然而，引入非自然的事物往往会带来难以预料的后果。例如，上述的止痛药可能存在副作用。“智能”冰箱在软件更新后可能无法重启，导致肉类暴露在高温下。

Instead, to solve one’s headache, we often just need to remove the unnatural: the pills, the late nights spent in front of a screen, the sedentary lifestyle, the modern diet.

相反，要解决头痛问题，我们通常只需要去除不自然的因素：药物、熬夜看屏幕、久坐不动的生活方式、现代饮食。

Similarly, a better fridge costs less, consumes less energy, and is less prone to breakdowns. This is achieved by removing unnecessary electronics.

同样，一台更好的冰箱价格更低、能耗更少、故障率也更低。这是通过去除不必要的电子元件实现的。

Often, removing the unnatural brings improvements.

通常情况下，去除不自然的因素会带来改善。

This is called the “via negativa” approach, a concept that became popular after Nassim Taleb published his bestselling book Antifragile. 38

这被称为“否定之路”方法，这一概念在纳西姆·塔勒布出版畅销书《反脆弱》后开始流行。

An earlier chapter explained Warren Buffett’s “not-to-do list” technique. It is based on doing more of what’s important by reducing the number of things you are working on. This is a good example of via negativa.

前文已解释过沃伦·巴菲特的“不做清单”技巧。该技巧的核心在于通过减少待办事项的数量，将更多精力投入到真正重要的事情上。这正是否定式思维的一个很好的例子。

ACTION:

行动：

Think about a chronic problem you have. Could the presence of something unnatural be its cause? (For example, an eating habit, a lifestyle habit, a new device, or some external pressure to act in a certain way.)

想想你长期存在的某个问题。它是否可能与某些非自然因素有关？（例如，某种饮食习惯、生活习惯、新添置的设备，或者迫使你采取某种行动的外部压力。）

Can you remove it?

你能把它取下来吗？

(Disclaimer: this is not medical advice; consult your doctor. Also, use some common sense. For example, most medicines are unnatural, but they are probably needed if you have a particular or severe condition. It’s not that the unnatural is always bad. Instead, it’s that the unnatural is a prime candidate for a reflection about whether it would be good to remove it.)

（免责声明：本文并非医疗建议；请咨询医生。此外，请运用常识。例如，大多数药物并非天然成分，但如果您患有某种特定或严重的疾病，则可能需要服用。并非非天然成分就一定不好。而是非天然成分恰恰值得我们思考是否应该去除。）

#↩
Rule 83
第83条规则

Your problems aren’t different

你的问题也没什么不同。

During middle and high school, I was skinny. Even worse: I had skinny legs and skinny arms but some belly fat. Prompted by some friends, I went to the gym a couple of times but did not see any improvement. So, I quit.

中学时期，我非常瘦。更糟糕的是：我的腿和胳膊都很细，但肚子上却有点赘肉。在朋友的鼓励下，我去过几次健身房，但并没有什么效果。所以，我就放弃了。

Of course, the solution was simple: exercising for a few months combined with healthier eating habits. Today, I know this. But I didn’t know it then. Or perhaps I knew but did not want to acknowledge it to myself. I believed my problem was different. Genetics, perhaps. That would explain why I was skinny, why I could not lift much, and why my muscles were not growing.

当然，解决方法很简单：坚持锻炼几个月，再加上更健康的饮食习惯。今天我明白这一点。但当时我并不明白。或许我其实明白，只是不愿承认。我当时觉得我的问题另有隐情。也许是基因问题。这样就能解释我为什么这么瘦，为什么举不起什么重物，为什么肌肉不长了。

A problem I couldn’t solve was a great way to take responsibility off me.

我无法解决的问题，成了推卸责任的绝佳途径。

A few years later, under social pressure from my colleagues, I finally joined the gym again. This time, I went regularly: three times per week for several months. After a while, the miracle happened: my muscles started growing and my belly started receding.

几年后，在同事们的劝说下，我终于又开始去健身房了。这次我坚持了下来，每周三次，持续了好几个月。过了一段时间，奇迹发生了：我的肌肉开始增长，肚子也开始缩小。

My problem was like everyone else’s. Its solution, too, was like everyone else’s.

我的问题和其他人的问题一样，解决方法也和其他人的问题一样。

I learned a new rule: do not think that your problem is different unless you have already applied the solution that works for anyone else for at least three months in a row.

我学到了一条新规则：除非你已经连续三个月应用了对其他人有效的解决方案，否则不要认为你的问题与众不同。

Believing that your problem is different is like believing that your version of how the world works is more important than the way the world actually works. There is a word for this: narcissism. And it is toxic.

认为你的问题与众不同，就如同认为你对世界运行方式的理解比世界实际运行的方式更重要。这种现象有一个词可以形容：自恋。而且，它非常有害。

ACTION:

行动：

Is there any problem of yours that you think is unique to you?

你觉得你遇到的问题有哪些是独一无二的？

How would you advise someone else to solve that problem?

你会建议别人如何解决这个问题？

Schedule some regular sessions in your calendar – at least once per week and at least for the next three months – in which you will try to apply the solution that works for everyone else. Until you do that, assume your problem isn’t different

在你的日程安排中安排一些固定的时间——至少每周一次，并且至少持续三个月——在这些时间里，尝试应用对其他人都有效的解决方案。在此之前，假设你的问题也一样。

#↩
Rule 84
第84条规则

you are the source
of most of your problems

你自身就是你大部分问题的根源。

The problems you face over and over tend to share a root cause: you.

你反复遇到的问题往往都有一个共同的根源：那就是你自身。

Well, not you , but one or more of your mental patterns. Perhaps, a belief you hold keeps you from addressing your chronic problems. Or, in some cases, an addiction of yours absorbs time and energy that could be better spent addressing your chronic problems.

并非是你本人，而是你的一种或多种思维模式。或许，你持有的某种信念让你无法正视长期存在的问题。又或许，你的某种成瘾行为消耗了你本可以用来解决长期问题的时间和精力。

Either way, it is your responsibility to find out which mental patterns prevent you from addressing your problems and find a way to get rid of such mental patterns.

无论如何，你都有责任找出哪些思维模式阻碍你解决问题，并找到摆脱这些思维模式的方法。

ACTION:

行动：

Think about a problem you have faced repeatedly over the past year. In other words, a problem you have failed to address so far.

想想过去一年里你反复遇到的一个问题。换句话说，一个你至今未能解决的问题。

What beliefs of yours are preventing you from addressing the problem? Which mental patterns of yours are consuming the time and energy you could use to solve your problems?

是什么信念阻碍了你解决问题？是什么思维模式消耗了你本可以用来解决问题的时间和精力？

Write them down, both the bad mental patterns and their consequences.

把不良思维模式及其后果都写下来。

Alternatively, what are you scared would happen if you solved the problem? Could it be that you would not enjoy some consequences of being “the kind of person who solved this problem”? Could some beliefs of yours make you think that the problem is not worth solving? In this case, think about how your life would be in 10 years if that problem is left unaddressed. It’s worth solving it, isn’t it?

或者，你担心如果解决了这个问题会发生什么？是不是因为你害怕自己无法享受“解决问题的人”所带来的某些好处？是不是你的某些固有观念让你觉得这个问题不值得解决？如果是这样，不妨想想，如果这个问题一直得不到解决，十年后你的生活会是什么样子。这个问题值得解决，不是吗？

Again, write down your conclusions. Unless you write them down, your mind won’t take them seriously. No, you’re not different. Your mind, too, needs to see yourself writing it down.

再次强调，把你的结论写下来。除非你写下来，否则你的大脑不会认真对待它们。没错，你和其他人的大脑一样，也需要看到自己把它们写下来。

#↩
Rule 85
第85条规则

Pick your environment

选择你的环境

Four factors will disproportionately influence your career:

以下四个因素将对你的职业生涯产生尤为显著的影响：

- How well you perform at the task written in your job description.

- 你完成工作描述中所列任务的表现如何。

- How well you perform at the tasks that are not written in your job description and yet are beneficial to your boss or company.

- 你如何出色地完成工作职责中未列出的、但对你的老板或公司有益的任务。

- How conducive to your growth is the culture within your team and company. 39

你的团队和公司文化对你的个人成长有多大帮助？

- How fast the company, industry, and country you work in are growing.

- 你所在的公司、行业和国家的发展速度。

The issue is that most people focus all their efforts on the first factor. They don’t pay attention to the other three and leave them to chance.

问题在于，大多数人把所有精力都集中在第一个因素上，而忽略了其他三个因素，任其听天由命。

That’s a shame. It’s like having to do four bicycle races and choosing to do three of them uphill.

真可惜。这就像要参加四场自行车比赛，却选择其中三场都是上坡赛一样。

This doesn’t mean that you must work for a fast-growing company in a fast-growing industry. It means that whether you do should be a deliberate choice.

这并不意味着你必须为一家快速发展的公司或一个快速发展的行业工作。而是说，是否这样做应该是一个经过深思熟虑的选择。

ACTION:

行动：

Are your current job, boss, or organization bottlenecks to your personal or professional ambitions? What about your town or country? Your clients?

你目前的工作、老板或组织是否阻碍了你的个人或职业发展？你的城市或国家呢？你的客户呢？

If you replied yes to any of the above, consider whether you are okay with it. Of course, there is nothing wrong with being okay with a bottleneck, but it must be a deliberate choice. And if you aren’t okay with it, schedule an action to explore other options.

如果您对以上任何问题回答“是”，请考虑您是否能够接受这种情况。当然，接受瓶颈本身并没有错，但这必须是经过深思熟虑的选择。如果您无法接受这种情况，请安排时间探索其他解决方案。

#↩

Recondition yourself

重新调整自己

Rules 86 to 90

规则 86 至 90

I believe that we, humans, have free will. However, I do not think that our free will is absolute. For example, a first-time smoker has a better capacity to decide to quit smoking than someone who has been smoking for decades.

我相信人类拥有自由意志。然而，我认为我们的自由意志并非绝对的。例如，一个初次吸烟者比一个吸烟几十年的人更有可能下定决心戒烟。

Therefore, I believe that free will is both infinite and limited, in the same way that the horizon is both infinite (if we keep walking) and limited (in a single instant of time, if we stand still).

因此，我认为自由意志既是无限的又是有限的，就像地平线既是无限的（如果我们一直走下去），又是有限的（在某一瞬间，如果我们停下来）。

More precisely, I believe that in a given instant of time, we only have the free will to take some steps, not all. Therefore, some journeys of self-improvement cannot simply consist of deciding to change our habits from today to tomorrow. Instead, they must start with reconditioning ourselves to increase our capacity to take larger steps tomorrow.

更确切地说，我认为在某一特定时刻，我们只有自由意志去采取某些行动，而非全部。因此，一些自我提升的旅程不能仅仅局限于决定从今天到明天改变习惯。相反，它们必须从重新调整自身状态开始，从而增强我们明天采取更大行动的能力。

This chapter is about applying this principle.

本章将探讨如何应用这一原则。

Rule 86
第86条规则

there is a space
刺激和反应之间存在空间
between stimulus and response

Victor Frankl was a survivor of the concentration camps of Nazi Germany. In his biography, Frankl noted that even if the Nazis took his liberty to do what he wanted, they never took his freedom to think what he wanted. “Between stimulus and response, man has the freedom to choose,” he wrote.

维克多·弗兰克尔是纳粹德国集中营的幸存者。在他的自传中，弗兰克尔指出，即使纳粹剥夺了他做任何事的自由，也从未剥夺他思考的自由。“在刺激和反应之间，人拥有选择的自由，”他写道。

Sometimes we have little influence on the events that externally impact us. Still, we always have a great deal of influence on how they will internally impact us and how we react.

有时，我们对外部事件的影响微乎其微。然而，我们始终能够很大程度上影响这些事件对我们内心的影响以及我们的反应。

“But,” you might reply, “sometimes the impulse to react in a certain way is so strong that I do not have a choice.” By believing you do not have a choice, you end up having no choice. Forcing yourself to react differently to a given stimulus just once will show you that alternatives are possible.

“但是，”你可能会回答，“有时候，想要做出某种反应的冲动如此强烈，以至于我别无选择。” 如果你认为自己别无选择，最终你真的就真的没有选择。强迫自己对某种刺激做出不同的反应，哪怕只有一次，也会让你明白，还有其他选择。

If you still find it impossible, then the chances are that your environment or your incentives are coercing you into a specific reaction. In this case, focus your energy and willpower on changing them. Once your environment and incentives support you in acting differently, and you do so, you will be able to witness on your own skin the benefits of a different, more positive reaction.

如果你仍然觉得无法做到，那么很可能是你的所处环境或自身利益在迫使你做出某种特定的反应。在这种情况下，你需要集中精力和意志力去改变它们。一旦你的环境和利益支持你采取不同的行动，并且你也确实这样做了，你就能亲身感受到这种更积极的反应所带来的益处。

Do this a couple of times, and it will be very difficult for you to go back to the old, negative reaction.

这样做几次之后，你就很难再回到以前那种消极的反应了。

ACTION:

行动：

Practice the above. The next time that a stimulus hits you, observe your reaction. Recognize that your response is only one of many possibilities. Try to change it.

练习以上方法。下次当你受到刺激时，观察你的反应。要意识到你的反应只是众多可能性之一。尝试改变它。

If it doesn’t work, observe others. Study their reactions and recognize that they are only possibilities.

如果行不通，就观察其他人。研究他们的反应，并认识到这些反应仅仅代表几种可能性。

If you manage to see this in others, soon, you will be able to see it in yourself.

如果你能够看到别人身上的这种特质，那么很快，你就能在自己身上看到这种特质。

BONUS: some quotes by Viktor Frankl

附赠：维克多·弗兰克尔的一些语录

“When we are no longer able to change a situation, we are challenged to change ourselves.”

“当我们无法改变现状时，我们面临的挑战是改变自己。”

“Success, like happiness, cannot be pursued; it must ensue, and it only does so as the unintended side effect of one’s personal dedication.”

“成功和幸福一样，无法刻意追求；它必须自然而然地到来，而且它只能作为个人奉献的意外收获。”

“Those who have a ‘why’ to live can bear with almost any ‘how.’”

“那些知道自己活着的意义的人，几乎可以忍受任何‘生存方式’。”

“Ultimately, man should not ask what the meaning of his life is, but rather must recognize that it is he who is asked. In a word, each man is questioned by life; and he can only answer to life by answering for his own life; to life, he can only respond by being responsible.”

“归根结底，人不应该问自己生命的意义是什么，而应该意识到是自己被问到了这个问题。简而言之，每个人都受到生命的质问；他只能通过对自己的生命负责来回答生命；他只能通过承担责任来回应生命。”

“It did not really matter what we expected from life, but rather what life expected from us.”

“重要的不是我们对生活有什么期待，而是生活对我们有什么期待。”

#↩
Rule 87
第87条规则

It is your responsibility to recondition yourself to the situations which evoke negative emotions in you

你有责任重新调整自己，以适应那些会引发你负面情绪的情境。

“To be emotional means to react to a present situation according to a past conditioning.” – yogi Gregor Maehle

“情绪化意味着根据过去的经验对当下的处境做出反应。”——瑜伽士格雷戈尔·梅勒

Emotions are conditioning that persists in our brain from our past interactions with someone or something. When we see again something we have already encountered, we react with the same emotion we felt during the last few interactions with that something.

情绪是过去与人或事物互动后，在大脑中形成的条件反射。当我们再次遇到曾经接触过的事物时，我们会像之前几次接触时那样，产生相同的情绪反应。

The way not to act emotionally is to intentionally recondition yourself: to have new, positive interactions with the things currently evoking negative emotions in you, so that the next time they will evoke positive ones instead.

避免情绪化行事的方法是刻意地重新训练自己：与那些目前让你产生负面情绪的事物进行新的、积极的互动，这样下次它们就会让你产生积极的情绪。

The first way to recondition yourself is to expose yourself, in a controlled manner, to the cues that trigger an undesirable emotional state. For example, let’s say that broccoli disgusts you, and you want to change that. You could start eating broccoli cooked with ingredients you like (say, butter and garlic). You could do that in a situation you enjoy (say, with your romantic partner or watching your favorite TV series). You could do it in a safe situation (say, with a glass of wine next to you to drink shortly after eating the broccoli, to “wash your mouth”). In any case, the objective is to expose yourself in such a way that the negative emotion is either limited or overwhelmed by positive ones. This way, your brain registers an “it’s not that bad after all” overall emotion that will override whatever negative feeling you used to have.

重塑自我的第一步，就是在可控的环境下，让自己接触那些会引发不良情绪的刺激因素。例如，假设你讨厌西兰花，而你想改变这种想法。你可以开始吃用你喜欢的食材（比如黄油和大蒜）烹制的西兰花。你可以在自己喜欢的场合这样做（比如和伴侣一起，或者一起看你最喜欢的电视剧）。你也可以在安全的环境下这样做（比如，吃完西兰花后，旁边放一杯酒，用来“漱口”）。总之，目标是以一种能够限制或压制负面情绪的方式让自己接触到这些刺激因素。这样，你的大脑就会接收到一种“其实没那么糟糕”的整体情绪，从而取代你之前所有的负面感受。

In particular, I found that simply forcing myself to put in my mouth one spoon of some food which is safe for me but am disgusted by, and then keep chewing it trying to find explanations for why most other people say it’s good is usually enough for me to learn to enjoy new foods (for example: “the texture is terrible, and the smell is awful, but the taste is not so bad”).

尤其是我发现，只要强迫自己吃一勺对我来说安全但令我反感的食物，然后不断咀嚼，试图找出大多数人认为它好吃的原因，通常就足以让我学会享受新的食物（例如：“口感很糟糕，气味也很可怕，但味道还不错”）。

The second way to recondition yourself is to stop direct exposure, spend some time working in a safe environment to build your skills and confidence, and only then expose yourself to whatever used to scare you. For example, you might have a negative feeling associated with public speaking. Read a few books on the subject, watch a few videos of great speakers, then practice in front of a mirror, and finally, dress appropriately for the speaking event you are about to attend. Hopefully, the preparation will reduce any anxiety you might feel. In most cases in which people feel bad in a situation enjoyed by others, it is because they did not learn the skills needed to enjoy it, not because of their personality.

第二种重塑自我的方法是停止直接接触，先花些时间在一个安全的环境中练习，提升技能和自信，然后再让自己接触那些曾经让你恐惧的事物。例如，你可能对公开演讲有负面情绪。可以先读几本相关的书籍，观看一些优秀演讲者的视频，然后在镜子前练习，最后，根据即将参加的演讲场合着装得体。希望这些准备工作能够减轻你的焦虑。大多数情况下，人们在别人乐在其中的场合感到不适，是因为他们没有掌握享受这种场合所需的技能，而不是因为他们的性格问题。

Depending on the context, only one of the two methods described above might be applicable. What is important to remember is that past conditionings are your responsibility to change.

根据具体情况，上述两种方法可能只有一种适用。重要的是要记住，改变过去的思维定式是你的责任。

ACTION:

行动：

What is one situation in which you want to change how you react?

你希望在哪种情况下改变自己的反应方式？

Choose one of the two methods described above (usually, only one of them applies to any given context) and use it.

从上述两种方法中选择一种（通常，在任何给定情况下，只有一种方法适用），并使用它。

#↩
Rule 88
第88条规则

You will only change once you desire the actions that bring change

只有当你渴望采取带来改变的行动时，你才会改变。

Personal coach Tim Robbins observed that a decision to change is only a decision if it is immediately followed by action; otherwise, it’s just a wish. I agree. Desiring the outcome of change isn’t enough to achieve it; one must also desire to do the actions that will bring that outcome.

私人教练蒂姆·罗宾斯曾指出，改变的决定只有在立即付诸行动时才能称之为决定；否则，它仅仅只是一种愿望。我对此表示赞同。仅仅渴望改变的结果并不足以实现它；一个人还必须渴望采取能够带来该结果的行动。

For example, I’ve observed that nearly everyone wants to get fit. However, only those upset when the gym is closed actually get fit. These are the people who don’t only feel good when they look at themselves in the mirror and notice the results of having gone to the gym but also while they exercise at the gym. Again, everyone feels good about a positive outcome; but only those who feel good about the actions required to achieve it will actually achieve it. Similarly, lasting change happens when one desires new habits, not just the outcomes that new habits would bring.

例如，我观察到几乎每个人都想健身。然而，只有那些在健身房关门时感到沮丧的人才会真正去健身。这些人不仅在照镜子看到自己健身的成果时感到愉悦，而且在健身房锻炼时也感到愉悦。同样，每个人都会对积极的结果感到高兴；但只有那些对实现结果所需的行动感到满意的人才能真正实现目标。类似地，持久的改变发生在人们渴望养成新习惯的时候，而不仅仅是渴望新习惯带来的结果。

ACTION:

行动：

Think about some changes you wish to achieve. How do you feel about the thought of yourself having achieved them?

想想你希望实现的一些改变。想到自己实现了这些改变，你感觉如何？

And how do you feel about the thought of doing the necessary actions to achieve that result?

那么，对于采取必要行动来实现这一目标，你有什么感受？

If you answered anything but “great!” to the second question, that is probably your bottleneck. To achieve your wishes, you will likely have to recondition how you feel about the actions that will get you there. The rest of this chapter is about how to do that.

如果你对第二个问题的回答不是“太棒了！”，那很可能就是你的瓶颈所在。为了实现你的愿望，你可能需要重新调整你对那些能帮助你达成目标的行动的看法。本章的其余部分将探讨如何做到这一点。

#↩
Rule 89
第89条规则

For change to happen,
要实现变革，就必须改变
incentives have to be changed
激励机制。

The saying goes, “if you spot a change in behavior, look for the change in incentives.”

俗话说，“如果发现行为发生变化，就要寻找激励机制的变化。”

Sometimes we are surprised by the unprecedented behavior of someone we used to know. For years they behaved in a given way, and suddenly, shockingly, they changed their ways.

有时，我们会对曾经认识的人的反常行为感到惊讶。多年来，他们一直以某种方式行事，但突然之间，令人震惊的是，他们改变了方式。

“They showed their true colors,” some would say. However, there might be another explanation. Perhaps they didn’t change, but their incentives did.

有人会说：“他们露出了真面目。”然而，或许还有另一种解释。也许他们本身并没有改变，只是他们的动机变了。

If someone acts differently from their past behavior, the chances are that this time, they had different incentives. If they had had the incentives they have now, they would have previously acted the way they just did. But because they didn’t have them, they used to behave otherwise.

如果某人的行为与以往不同，很可能是因为这次他们的动机不同。如果他们过去也拥有现在的动机，他们也会采取刚才那样的行动。但正因为过去没有这些动机，他们才会采取不同的行为。

This is why we cannot confidently say that a frail person is gentle. They might be aggressive at heart but unconsciously inhibit their aggressiveness to avoid ending up in fights they would lose. We can only confidently say of a physically strong person that they are gentle, because they do not use their strength despite having the ability to do so.

这就是为什么我们不能肯定地说体弱者温柔。他们内心可能具有攻击性，但会无意识地压抑这种攻击性，以避免陷入必败的争斗。我们只能肯定地说体格强壮者温柔，因为他们即使有能力，也不会使用自己的力量。

Similarly, it might occur that people who never liked something suddenly find themselves enjoying it. This is common after dating a new partner who enjoys that thing. This is because a new incentive unconsciously entered their life: doing what allows them to spend quality time with their partner. This shift in preferences is genuine to the extent the new incentive has been unconsciously internalized. If the person genuinely enjoys spending time with their new partner, they will also genuinely enjoy some of the things their partner likes. This phenomenon does not apply to all preferences, but it does apply to at least some.

同样，有些人可能原本不喜欢某样东西，却突然发现自己喜欢上了它。这种情况在与喜欢这类事物的新伴侣交往后尤为常见。这是因为他们的生活中不知不觉地出现了一个新的激励因素：做那些能让他们与伴侣共度美好时光的事情。这种偏好的转变之所以真实，取决于这种新的激励因素是否已被他们潜意识地内化。如果一个人真心享受与新伴侣相处的时光，他们也会真心喜欢伴侣喜欢的某些事物。这种现象并非适用于所有偏好，但至少适用于某些偏好。

The influence incentives can have on our behavior is profoundly underestimated. We might think we have a given personality trait only to find ourselves with a novel trait the day our incentives change.

激励机制对我们行为的影响被严重低估了。我们可能认为自己具有某种性格特征，但一旦激励机制发生变化，我们就会发现自己展现出另一种全新的性格特征。

It doesn’t mean that we do not have a personality. It means that our personality is only one of the inputs determining our behavior. Incentives are another such input – often, a powerful one.

这并不意味着我们没有个性。而是说，个性只是决定我们行为的众多因素之一。激励机制是另一个重要的因素——而且往往是一个强有力的因素。

We might think that a mental pattern of ours is part of our personality when, in reality, it is part of our incentives.

我们可能认为某种思维模式是我们性格的一部分，但实际上，它是我们动机的一部分。

To change our habits, incentives are one of the easiest attack points. Change your incentives, and you might change your habits.

要改变习惯，激励是最容易切入的切入点之一。改变你的激励机制，或许就能改变你的习惯。

ACTION:

行动：

Is there any bad habit of yours that you are incentivized to keep? In this case, can you remove the incentive? Or can you add a negative incentive, such as a “punishment” that happens to you if you practice the bad habit?

你是否有某种坏习惯，而你又因为某种原因想要继续保持？在这种情况下，你能消除这种诱因吗？或者你能增加一种负面的诱因，例如，如果你继续保持这个坏习惯，就会受到“惩罚”吗？

Is there any good habit you want to introduce in your life? Can you add some positive incentive to it? For example, good coffee to be drunk after completing a task you do not like doing.

你想在生活中养成什么好习惯？你能给它加一些积极的激励措施吗？例如，完成一项你不喜欢的任务后，喝一杯好咖啡作为奖励。

Note that the incentive could be something already in your routine – you just need to link it to the task you do not like doing and then deny yourself the incentive if you do not complete the task. For example, you might already drink coffee every morning. But you can tell yourself, “I will drink the coffee only after having completed 50 pushups,” if that is the daily habit you want to introduce in your life.

请注意，激励因素可以是您日常生活中已有的东西——您只需要将其与您不喜欢做的任务联系起来，然后如果您没有完成该任务，就不要给自己奖励。例如，您可能已经每天早上喝咖啡。但您可以告诉自己，“只有在完成50个俯卧撑之后我才能喝咖啡”，如果您想在生活中养成这个习惯的话。

ADVANCED ACTION:

高级行动：

Make a list of your personality traits. Then, for each, ask yourself: have I ever found myself in a situation where I acted in accordance with my trait even when it would have been more beneficial to me not to do so? In other words, is there any personality trait that has been costly ?

列出你的所有性格特征。然后，针对每一种特征，问问自己：我是否曾经遇到过这种情况：明明不这样做对我更有利，但我却按照自己的性格特征行事？换句话说，是否存在某种性格特征让我付出了代价？

Doubt of any traits for which the answer to the question above is negative.

对于上述问题答案为否定的任何特质，都存在疑问。

(If you perform this exercise honestly and earnestly, you might find yourself calling into question most of your personality traits. It’s normal.)

（如果你诚实认真地完成这项练习，你可能会发现自己开始质疑自己的大部分性格特征。这是正常的。）

#↩
Rule 90
规则90

Where incentives are encoded matters

激励机制的编码方式至关重要。

You probably know someone who’s been a heavy smoker for years and only stopped once a medical exam showed that their health had deteriorated. Why didn’t they stop before?

你可能认识一些烟瘾很大的人，他们抽烟很多年，直到体检发现健康状况恶化才戒烟。他们为什么之前不戒烟呢？

Before the doctor’s report, they knew about the risks of smoking but did not experience them. At that time, the health incentives to stop smoking were encoded in their cortex – the walnut-shaped part of our brain responsible for cognition. Here, incentives can only provide knowledge but cannot influence habits. However, after the emotionally charged experience of listening to the doctor telling them that their health deteriorated due to smoking, the health incentives to stop smoking became also encoded in other brain structures, those responsible for deciding which actions to take. Here, incentives could finally influence habits.

在医生出具报告之前，他们虽然知道吸烟的危害，但并未亲身经历过。那时，戒烟的健康激励机制被编码在他们的大脑皮层——大脑中负责认知功能的核桃状区域。在这里，激励机制只能提供知识，而无法改变习惯。然而，在经历了医生告知他们吸烟导致健康恶化的强烈情绪冲击之后，戒烟的健康激励机制也被编码到大脑的其他结构中，即负责决定采取何种行动的区域。此时，激励机制终于能够影响他们的习惯了。

Where in the brain incentives are encoded matters.

大脑中激励机制编码的位置很重要。

ACTION:

行动：

If you don’t feel compelled to act upon an incentive, you probably didn’t experience its outcomes yet. In this case, focus on engineering an experience in which you will get first-hand exposure to the incentive so that you feel it.

如果你感觉不到有动力去采取行动，那很可能是因为你还没有体验到它带来的好处。在这种情况下，你应该努力创造一种体验，让你能够亲身感受到这种好处。

How can you get to experience as soon as possible a taste of the rewards of achieving your goals?

如何才能尽快体验到实现目标所带来的成就感？

#↩

Learn to be happy

学会快乐

Rules 91 to 92

规则91至92

Barring children and adults living in tragic circumstances, I believe happiness is a skill. It can be learned.

除了生活在悲惨环境中的儿童和成人之外，我认为幸福是一种技能，是可以学习的。

However, differing from some philosophies, I also believe this is not just about how one interprets events. It is also about taking proactive action to create the conditions for us to be happy.

然而，与某些哲学观点不同，我认为这不仅仅关乎如何解读事件，还关乎采取积极主动的行动来创造让我们幸福的条件。

Rule 91
规则91

Happiness is a direction

幸福是一种方向

If only there were something that would make us happy forever.

如果世上真有什么东西能让我们永远幸福就好了。

As lovely as it would be, this is not how the human brain works. Our brain evolved to bias us towards action. Biologically, happiness is a reward for actions that improve our life. And as with all incentives, it has to be temporary. It has to leave its receiver wanting for more.

虽然这听起来很美好，但这并非人脑的运作方式。我们的大脑进化是为了让我们倾向于行动。从生物学角度来看，幸福是对那些改善我们生活的行为的奖励。而且，正如所有激励措施一样，它必须是暂时的。它必须让接受者渴望更多。

Therefore, happiness doesn’t relate to a state but to a transition. It’s about having just solved our problems, not about having solved our problems long ago. So, it is self-deceiving to believe in the existence of something that can make us happy forever.

因此，幸福并非一种状态，而是一种转变。它关乎我们刚刚解决问题，而非很久以前就解决了问题。所以，相信存在某种能让我们永远幸福的东西，是一种自欺欺人的想法。

Happiness is not a place we can reach and rest in. Instead, happiness is a direction we can walk along. If we progress toward something which increases our self-respect, we are happy. If we don’t, we feel sadness or anxiety.

幸福并非我们可以抵达并停留的终点，而是一个我们可以前行的方向。如果我们朝着提升自尊的方向前进，我们便会感到幸福；反之，则会感到悲伤或焦虑。

We shouldn’t wish for a permanent state of happiness that would relieve us from having to take action. Instead, we should wish for the opportunity to continuously take actions that make us happy.

我们不应该渴望一种永久的幸福状态，从而免于行动。相反，我们应该渴望有机会不断采取让我们快乐的行动。

There is no way that we can be both happy for long and rest. Sustained happiness requires constant action. Embracing this will make the walk easier.

我们不可能既长久快乐又安逸。持续的快乐需要不断的行动。接受这一点，会让前行之路更加轻松。

ACTION:

行动：

If you truly believed that sustained happiness requires constant action, what actions would you take today?

如果你真心相信持续的幸福需要不断的行动，那么你今天会采取哪些行动？

#↩
Rule 92
规则92

Happiness is self-respect

幸福就是自尊

Some people describe themselves as happy while engaging in addictive activities. For example, drunk people on a Friday night generally describe themselves as happy. However, those people would also describe themselves as unhappy shortly thereafter – usually when the hangover symptoms surface or when faced on the following day with a life they do not enjoy living. Because “drinking to have fun” is comparable to borrowing happiness from the day after, I call addictive activities happiness loans .

有些人沉迷于某些成瘾行为时会感到快乐。例如，周五晚上喝醉的人通常会觉得自己很开心。然而，这些人很快就会感到不快乐——通常是在宿醉症状出现时，或者第二天面对自己不喜欢的生活时。由于“喝酒寻欢作乐”类似于从第二天借用快乐，我把这些成瘾行为称为“快乐贷款”。

But let’s talk about longer-lasting forms of happiness – the kind of happiness that might make us smile when remembering the past or when looking at ourselves in the mirror.

但我们来谈谈更持久的幸福——那种让我们在回忆过去或照镜子时会心一笑的幸福。

Happiness follows having collected evidence that we are someone we can respect. You might not find it true right now, especially if you’re young. But as you age, you will probably find it increasingly accurate.

幸福源于积累了足够的证据，证明自己是值得尊敬的人。你现在或许并不认同这一点，尤其如果你还年轻。但随着年龄的增长，你可能会越来越认同这种说法。

There are a few exceptions, but generally, people want to be someone they can respect. They feel happy if there is evidence that they are such a person and feel unhappy otherwise.

虽然也有一些例外，但总的来说，人们都希望成为值得尊敬的人。如果能证明自己是这样的人，他们会感到高兴；反之，则会感到不快乐。

When faced with a choice, go with the option that will increase your self-respect. If you manage to do it consistently, not only will you be happier, but you will also act in a way that benefits you in the long term through stronger relationships and a more powerful self – one that can solve problems.

面对选择时，选择能提升你自尊的选项。如果你能始终如一地做到这一点，不仅会更快乐，还能通过更牢固的人际关系和更强大的自我——一个能够解决问题的自我——在长远来看对你大有裨益。

ACTION:

行动：

For the next week, get yourself to take at least one action per day that increases your self-respect. That could be to do a few pushups and crunches just after waking up, to refuse to eat that unhealthy snack, or whatever activity you think would be the appropriate choice for this exercise.

接下来的一周，每天至少做一件能提升你自尊的事情。比如，起床后做几个俯卧撑和仰卧起坐，拒绝吃不健康的零食，或者任何你认为适合这项练习的活动。

After one week, think back about the actions you took. How do you feel about them now? And how do you feel about yourself?

一周后，回想一下你采取的行动。你现在对这些行动有何感想？你对自己又有何感想？

#↩

Know yourself

了解自己

Rules 93 to 94

规则93至94

Rule 93

规则93

Know and accept your rules

了解并接受你的规则

The rules you read so far apply to most people. There are other rules which are just as important, but I could not include them here as they only apply to a few people. For example, the following are rules that apply to me but not to most other people.

你目前读到的规则适用于大多数人。还有一些同样重要的规则，但由于它们只适用于少数人，所以我无法在此一一列举。例如，以下规则适用于我，但不适用于大多数人。

– If I do not get some quiet time in the morning, I spend the rest of the day in a nervous state.
– If I drink coffee after 4 PM, I don’t sleep well.
– Going out with large groups of friends drains my energy.

– 如果早上没有安静的独处时间，我一整天都会感到焦虑不安。– 如果下午4点以后喝咖啡，我就睡不好。– 和一大群朋友出去玩会耗尽我的精力。

These rules are definitely not universal. But they are rules nevertheless, in the sense that if I do not follow them, I will suffer consequences. And the earlier I acknowledge them and act accordingly, the better.

这些规则当然不是普世适用的。但它们仍然是规则，因为我如果不遵守，就会承担后果。而且，我越早意识到这些规则并采取相应行动，就越好。

ACTION

行动

We all have personal rules that dictate our reactions. What are yours? Any that wish didn’t exist? Would it be better if you accepted them and acted accordingly .

我们每个人都有自己的行为准则来指导我们的反应。你的准则是什么？有没有哪些准则是你希望它们不存在的？如果你接受它们并按照它们行事，会不会更好？

#↩
Rule 94
规则94

Do not overcompensate

不要矫枉过正

Each of us has strengths and weaknesses. Strengths are obviously good, but they can become a liability if we use them too much to overcompensate for our weaknesses .

我们每个人都有优点和缺点。优点固然是好事，但如果我们过度依赖优点来弥补缺点，它们反而会变成缺点。

For example, I used to be bad at prioritization. So, I overcompensated by working hard (a strength of mine). That caused me to spend my energies on the wrong things and hampered my professional development. Instead, I could have spent my efforts on the right things, getting much more out of my determination.

例如，我以前不擅长分清轻重缓急。所以，我过度努力地工作（这是我的强项），结果导致我把精力浪费在了错误的事情上，阻碍了我的职业发展。其实，我本可以把精力放在正确的事情上，从而让我的决心发挥更大的作用。

Of course, it’s not that working hard is bad. But it is bad when it prevents us from working smarter. And if we do not work smart, we will work hard on the wrong things and waste our potential. Instead, we should regularly review if we use our strengths to overcompensate. And if we do, we should address our weaknesses so that we can put our strengths to more effective use.

当然，努力工作本身并没有错。但如果努力工作阻碍了我们更高效地工作，那就错了。如果我们不善于高效工作，就会把精力浪费在错误的事情上，白白浪费自己的潜力。因此，我们应该定期反思自己是否过度依赖优势来弥补不足。如果确实如此，我们就应该着手解决自身的弱点，以便更有效地发挥优势。

As another example, I used to play basketball with a boy so tall that he could just score by using his height. This worked well until he got promoted to higher leagues, where size alone isn’t enough to score. But because he never developed his skills, he couldn’t score anymore and soon got cut from his team.

再举个例子，我以前和一个个子特别高的男孩一起打篮球，他光靠身高就能得分。这招一直很管用，直到他升入更高级别的联赛，光靠身高已经不够了。但他一直没练好球技，得分能力下降，很快就被球队淘汰了。

Again, the lesson is to use our strengths, but never forget to also improve on the weaknesses that can limit our potential.

再次强调，我们要发挥自身优势，但永远不要忘记改进那些可能限制我们潜能的弱点。

ACTION:

行动：

Pick an area of your life, for example, your career or your romantic life.

选择你生活中的一个领域，例如你的事业或你的感情生活。

What are your strengths and weaknesses?

你的优势和劣势是什么？

Of your strengths, which are you using to overcompensate for your weaknesses?

你利用自身的哪些优势来弥补自身的劣势？

Of your overcompensated weaknesses, which have you not tried to improve for years?

在你那些过度弥补的弱点中，有哪些是你多年来一直没有尝试改进的？

Which actions could you schedule now to strengthen them? Note that you do not have to bring your weaknesses from an “F” to an “A.” It’s okay to develop them just enough so that they won’t hamper your long-term potential.

现在你可以安排哪些行动来加强这些能力？请注意，你不必将弱点从“F”提升到“A”。只需加以改进，使其不影响你的长期发展潜力即可。

#↩

Main principles

主要原则

Rules 95 to 97

规则95至97

This chapter summarizes some of the overarching principles covered in the 94 rules shared so far.

本章总结了迄今为止分享的 94 条规则中涵盖的一些总体原则。

Rule 95

规则95

Ruthlessly prioritize

无情地确定优先事项

We have discussed bottlenecks, points of leverage, and Pareto distributions.

我们已经讨论了瓶颈、杠杆点和帕累托分布。

If there is a bottleneck, efforts can only bring marginal results – unless, of course, they are directly aimed at getting rid of the bottleneck.

如果存在瓶颈，那么努力只能带来微乎其微的结果——除非，当然，这些努力是直接针对消除瓶颈而进行的。

If you want to improve a metric by 10%, working harder is an option. But if you want to improve it by 10 times, you will have to find a point of leverage. For example, if I want to sell 10% more books, I can spend a few more hours promoting them, but if I want to sell 10 times as much, I will have to get myself featured on a top podcast or newspaper.

如果你想让某个指标提高10%，努力工作是一种选择。但如果你想让它提高10倍，你就必须找到一个切入点。例如，如果我想让书的销量提高10%，我可以多花几个小时做推广；但如果我想让销量提高10倍，我就必须让自己登上顶级播客或报纸的版面。

If Pareto’s law applies (the 20% of people/books/actions are responsible for 80% of the impact), it doesn’t make sense to distribute your time equally across all options. Instead, focus on what generates the most impact.

如果帕累托法则适用（20%的人/书籍/行为造成了80%的影响），那么将时间平均分配给所有选项是没有意义的。相反，应该专注于那些能产生最大影响的事情。

ACTION:

行动：

Proactively look for bottlenecks, points of leverage, and Pareto distributions. Then, write down actions that directly address them. These go into your to-do list. Any other action goes into your not -to-do list.

主动寻找瓶颈、杠杆点和帕累托分布。然后，写下直接针对这些问题的行动方案。这些方案列入待办事项清单。任何其他行动方案都列入不做事项清单。

#↩
Rule 96
规则96

Maximize compounding loops

最大化复利循环

“All returns in life – whether in wealth, relationships or knowledge – come from compound interest” – entrepreneur and philosopher Naval Ravikant.

“人生中的所有回报——无论是财富、人际关系还是知识——都来自复利”——企业家兼哲学家纳瓦尔·拉维坎特。

Let’s illustrate compound interest with a simple example.

让我们用一个简单的例子来说明复利。

If you invest $100 in an investment that returns 10% per year, after one year, you will have $110 – a return of $10. However, after ten years, you will have $259. That is an average return of $25.9 per year – more than twice the one-year return.

如果你投资 100 美元，年回报率为 10%，一年后你将拥有 110 美元——收益为 10 美元。然而，十年后你将拥有 259 美元。这意味着平均每年 25.9 美元的回报率——是第一年回报率的两倍多。

Such is the power of compounding : the returns from the first year generate their own returns in the second year; these returns generate their own additional returns in the third year, and so on, with a snowballing effect.

这就是复利的力量：第一年的收益在第二年产生新的收益；这些收益在第三年又产生额外的收益，依此类推，产生滚雪球效应。

Compounding takes place when returns are value-producing assets. The landmark trait of great investors and professionals is to invest in value-producing assets early on, judging them not for the returns they can bring today but for the returns that their returns can generate.

当收益来自能够创造价值的资产时，复利效应就会发生。优秀投资者和专业人士的标志性特征是尽早投资于能够创造价值的资产，他们评判这些资产的标准不是看它们当下能带来的收益，而是看它们未来的收益潜力。

Of course, this applies not only to investments but also to friends, relationships, and skills. Their returns compound too – friends bring more friends, skills bring more opportunities which in turn bring more skills, and so on.

当然，这不仅适用于投资，也适用于朋友、人际关系和技能。它们的收益也会累积——朋友带来更多朋友，技能带来更多机会，而机会反过来又会带来更多技能，如此循环往复。

In fact, the compounding effect exists in many areas of your life.

事实上，复利效应存在于你生活的许多方面。

For example:

例如：

- Your health: the more you move and are flexible, the more likely you are to exercise and thus get stronger and more agile (or retain those qualities as you age). If you did not do any sport for years, exercising for one minute a day will build the muscles, breath, and flexibility to exercise for two minutes a day, which will benefit you even more, and so on until you will be in great shape.

- 你的健康：你的活动量越大，身体越灵活，就越有可能进行锻炼，从而变得更强壮、更敏捷（或者随着年龄增长保持这些素质）。如果你多年没有运动，每天锻炼一分钟就能增强肌肉力量、改善呼吸和提高柔韧性，让你有能力每天锻炼两分钟，从而获得更大的益处，如此循环往复，直到你拥有良好的体型。

- Your network: each new customer is a new person you add to the group of people who know your products or services and can recommend them. If each customer has, say, a 10% chance of recommending you, then each customer can, in a way, be seen as an investment with a 10% return. 40 This compounds rapidly.

- 你的关系网：每增加一位新客户，就意味着你又增加了一位了解你的产品或服务并可能推荐它们的人。假设每位客户有 10% 的概率推荐你，那么从某种意义上说，每位客户都可以被视为一项投资，带来 10% 的回报。这种收益会迅速累积。

- Your knowledge: reading a book on a given subject will give you the tools to read a more advanced book on the same subject, which in turn will allow you to read an even more advanced book, and so on.

- 你的知识：阅读一本关于某一主题的书将为你提供阅读同一主题更高级书籍的工具，而这反过来又将使你能够阅读更高级的书籍，依此类推。

- Your know-how: learning to play soccer in primary school allows you to play on a young team, which gives you the skills to transition to a better club, where the coach will teach you even more advanced skills, which will allow you access to even better coaches, and so on.

- 你的知识技能：在小学学习踢足球可以让你加入一支青年队，这让你掌握了过渡到更好俱乐部的技能，在那里教练会教你更高级的技能，这将使你有机会接触到更好的教练，以此类推。

- In relationships: meeting a person once allows for limited kinds of interaction (small talk, casual sex, etc.). Instead, repeatedly meeting a person opens the doors to more rewarding interactions (deep conversations, intimacy), which might in turn lead to more rewarding activities that were previously precluded (e.g., starting a family together).

在人际关系中：初次见面只能进行有限的互动（闲聊、随意性行为等）。相反，反复见面则能开启更有意义的互动（深入交谈、亲密关系），而这些互动反过来又可能促成之前无法实现的更有意义的活动（例如，共同组建家庭）。

Compounding starts slow. The returns of the first week are not a good indication of the weekly returns you will get in a few years. Don’t let the small initial returns discourage you. Do things that snowball. It’s worth it.

复利增长并非一蹴而就。第一周的收益并不能准确反映几年后的每周收益。不要因为最初的小额收益而气馁。要坚持做那些能产生滚雪球效应的事情。这绝对值得。

ACTION:

行动：

Pick an area of your life you would like to improve. Is there any part of it that compounds? If so, act towards it. The earlier you do, the more its benefits will compound.

选择生活中你想改善的一个方面。其中是否存在具有累积效应的部分？如果是，那就采取行动。行动越早，带来的益处就越大。

An example: I want to publish a book. What compounds? Two things come to mind. First, my writing skills. The more I write, the better I write, and the better I write, the more I write – a virtuous circle. Second, my audience. The more people read me, the more people talk about my writings, and the more people will read me in the future. Hence, I should begin working on my writing skills and building an audience as soon as possible, without worrying if my writing isn’t great yet or if the absolute improvement is little at the beginning. With time and action, they’re bound to improve – first slowly, then fast.

举个例子：我想出版一本书。什么会促进写作进步呢？我想到了两点。首先是我的写作技巧。我写得越多，写得就越好；写得越好，我就会写得越多——这是一个良性循环。其次是我的读者群。读我文章的人越多，谈论我文章的人就越多，将来也会有更多的人读我的文章。因此，我应该尽快开始提升写作技巧并积累读者群，不必担心我的写作水平目前不够好，或者一开始进步不大。随着时间的推移和实践的积累，我的写作技巧和读者群一定会提高——起初缓慢，然后迅速。

#↩
Rule 97
规则97

Iterate

迭代

Almost everything can represent a step forward if you learn something from it.

几乎任何事，只要能从中吸取教训，都可以成为进步的一步。

If you want to take advantage of this important principle, you should structure your life so that you can take as many steps forward as possible. This implies actions such as the below.

如果你想运用这一重要原则，就应该合理安排自己的生活，尽可能多地向前迈进。这意味着要采取以下行动。

ACTIONS:

行动：

– Try as many new things as possible. This doesn’t necessarily mean trying very different things, such as working one year as a baker and another as an office employee. It could also mean spending a career as a baker while trying every day some variation on your recipes or on how you sell your products.

尽可能多地尝试新事物。这并不一定意味着要尝试截然不同的工作，例如一年做面包师，一年做办公室职员。它也可以指你从事面包师这个职业，但每天都尝试对配方或产品销售方式进行一些调整。

– Make sure that you can survive your mistakes. Never go all in. This doesn’t mean avoiding risks. Instead, it means to hit the sweet spot represented by risks with low downside and high upside, risks you can recover from. It means setting some boundaries to protect your health and personal life so that you can give it all within the limits you have set .

确保你能承受犯错的后果。切勿孤注一掷。这并非意味着规避风险，而是要找到风险的最佳平衡点，即风险的下行风险低、收益高，且你能从中恢复过来。这意味着要设定一些界限来保护你的健康和个人生活，这样你才能在自己设定的限度内全力以赴。

– Make sure you learn as much as possible as fast as possible. Set frequent feedback loops. Practice your practice. Ask yourself after each session, “What should I do to get more feedback from what I am doing?”

确保尽可能快地学习尽可能多的知识。建立频繁的反馈机制。反复练习。每次练习后都问问自己：“我应该怎么做才能从我的练习中获得更多反馈？”

– Ensure you are not mindlessly doing “more of the same.” Remember, what got you here won’t get you there. And working hard without checking your assumptions is a form of laziness. Get better at spotting busywork and use your negative emotions (such as frustration) as a signal that a change is due.

确保你没有盲目地重复“同样的事情”。记住，让你走到今天的方法并不会带你走向未来。埋头苦干而不去检验你的假设，其实是一种懒惰。要学会识别那些无意义的重复劳动，并将你的负面情绪（例如沮丧）视为需要做出改变的信号。

– Do not seek perfection, maximum efficiency, and full control. Their maximum sustainable level is lower than 100%. Instead of perfection, seek progression.

不要追求完美、最高效率和完全控制。它们的最高可持续水平低于100%。与其追求完美，不如追求进步。

– Iterate on what you think you want, what you think its costs are, and how you can better pay them.

反复思考你想要什么，你认为它的成本是多少，以及如何更好地支付这些成本。

– Use trial and error to find out what is necessary.

通过反复试验找出必要条件。

– Focus on momentum before impact. You’re attempting too big of a first step if you cannot achieve momentum. Iterate until you find a step small enough to get you moving forward.

——在取得进展之前，要先关注动量。如果你无法获得足够的动量，那么你一开始就试图迈出太大的一步。反复尝试，直到找到一个足够小的、能让你前进的步伐。

– Use trial and error to calibrate your compasses (your objectives and values).

– 通过反复试验来校准你的指南针（你的目标和价值观）。

Embrace iteration.

拥抱迭代。

#↩

Conclusions

结论

Rules 98 to 100

规则98至100

Rule 98
规则98

Life is about resisting erosion

生命就是抵抗侵蚀。

The passage of water carves valleys drip after drip. Such is the power of time.

水滴冲刷，雕琢出山谷。这就是时间的力量。

Objects, such as houses, also get weaker and worn out by the passage of time.

物体，例如房屋，也会随着时间的推移而变得脆弱和破旧。

Living beings, in contrast, fight the erosion of time. Animals and plants constantly build new cells to replace those lost and die when they cannot do it anymore.

与此相反，生物体则对抗着时间的侵蚀。动植物不断地生成新的细胞来替换失去的细胞，当它们无法再进行这种替换时，就会死亡。

A philosopher by the pseudonym of Thibault 41 proposed that life is about resisting erosion. What is alive resists erosion. And what doesn’t resist erosion, we can consider it dead.

一位笔名为蒂博的哲学家提出，生命的本质在于抵抗侵蚀。凡是有生命的，都能抵抗侵蚀。而凡是无法抵抗侵蚀的，我们就可以认为它是死的。

But physical erosion is not the only kind of erosion. Our environment, especially our social environment, shapes who we are. In many instances, it erodes our personality. Like water flowing in a river smoothens the rocks it touches, our family, friends, and colleagues smoothen the rough edges of our personality. They erode our unique preferences, skills, and dreams.

但侵蚀并非唯一的侵蚀形式。我们的环境，尤其是社会环境，塑造了我们。在很多情况下，它会侵蚀我们的个性。正如河水流过磨平了岩石，我们的家人、朋友和同事也会磨平我们个性中的棱角。他们会逐渐侵蚀我们独特的喜好、技能和梦想。

The people who feel alive and radiate energy wherever they go learned to resist this erosion. They build back the parts of their personality which make them, them. Of course, there are occurrences in which they limit their idiosyncrasies to thrive in environments with strong social norms. But they know which parts of themselves not to compromise. And they focus their energies there, so that instead of being eroded by their environment, they shape it.

那些无论走到哪里都充满活力、散发着能量的人，都学会了抵抗这种侵蚀。他们重建了构成自身独特个性的那些部分。当然，为了在社会规范严谨的环境中生存，他们有时也会克制自己的个性。但他们知道哪些方面不能妥协，并将精力集中于此，这样一来，他们不是被环境侵蚀，而是塑造环境。

Being alive means resisting our environment and eventually shaping it.

活着就意味着抵抗环境，并最终塑造环境。

ACTION:

行动：

Prevent your body from getting eroded. Exercise. Use your time to resist time. Shape your environment (your desk, your schedule) so that your body emerges stronger, not weaker, from being immersed in it.

防止身体衰老。锻炼身体。利用时间对抗时间。调整你的环境（你的办公桌、你的日程安排），让你的身体在沉浸其中后变得更强壮，而不是更虚弱。

Prevent your personality from getting eroded. Use the knowledge you acquired through this book to identify which mental patterns of yours are a disadvantage, and you should therefore smoothen, and which are an advantage, and you should therefore harden.

防止你的个性被侵蚀。运用你从本书中获得的知识，识别出哪些思维模式是你的劣势，因此你应该加以改进；哪些思维模式是你的优势，因此你应该加以强化。

Shape your dreams instead of allowing others to shape them.

自己塑造梦想，而不是让别人塑造你的梦想。

#↩
Rule 99
规则99

Life is about becoming someone we respect

人生在于成为我们尊重的人。

For every person I’ve met in my life so far, the following two statements have been true.

到目前为止，我一生中遇到的每个人都符合以下两个条件。

Those who live a life they respect are happy.

那些过着自己尊重的生活的人是幸福的。

Those who live a life they don’t respect are unhappy.

那些过着自己不尊重的生活的人是不快乐的。

Sure, one can be temporarily happy or unhappy. Here, I’m talking about long-lasting pervasive happiness.

当然，人可能会暂时感到快乐或不快乐。但我在这里指的是持久的、普遍的幸福感。

If happiness is a priority of yours, then living like a person you would respect must also become your priority.

如果你把幸福放在首位，那么做一个你会尊重的人也必须成为你的首要任务。

ACTION:

行动：

The next time you need to make a choice, use self-respect as a compass.

下次当你需要做出选择时，要以自尊为指南针。

Take the choice that would result in you respecting yourself more.

做出能让你更尊重自己的选择。

If you manage to do so consistently, you’ll open the doors to a life of independence and happiness.

如果你能坚持这样做，你就能打开通往独立幸福生活的大门。

#↩
Rule 100
规则100

You own your own life

你掌控着自己的人生

Here we are, after 99 rules. Probably, you immediately applied some of them with excellent results. Other rules, you thought were not relevant to your life and decided not to use them.

好了，我们已经讲完了99条规则。或许你已经立即应用了其中一些，并且取得了显著成效。而另一些规则，你觉得与你的生活无关，所以决定不去使用。

It’s okay. You ultimately decide what is good for you. You own your own life.

没关系。最终，你自己决定什么对你好。你的人生由你掌控。

No matter what people tell you – including me with this book – you have the responsibility to make the decisions that will matter in your life. You own your choices and their consequences.

无论别人怎么说——包括我通过这本书告诉你的——你都有责任做出对你人生至关重要的决定。你要为你的选择及其后果负责。

This is exciting. It means that you can shape your life much more than you may have believed. It is also scary. It means that even if you decline to make a choice or follow someone else’s advice or expectation, you are responsible for the outcome. It’s your life. You are responsible for it, even if you let someone else choose for you. Even when you do not make a decision.

这令人兴奋。这意味着你可以比你想象的更有能力塑造自己的人生。但这也令人恐惧。这意味着即使你拒绝做出选择，或者不听从他人的建议或期望，你仍然要为结果负责。这是你的人生。你对此负有责任，即使你让别人替你做决定，即使你根本没有做出决定。

Remember, “bad decisions in life arise from having optimized for the wrong variable.” Do not optimize your life for other people. Do not optimize it for comfort. Do not optimize it for status. Do not optimize it for success. Do not optimize it for your current self. Instead, optimize your life for long-term self-respect.

记住，“人生中糟糕的决定往往源于选择了错误的优化目标。”不要为了迎合他人而优化人生，不要为了追求舒适而优化人生，不要为了追求地位而优化人生，不要为了追求成功而优化人生，也不要为了迎合当下的自己而优化人生。相反，要为了长久的自尊而优化人生。

Life is too long to be lived for the short term.

人生苦短，不应只顾眼前利益。

Life is too unique to be lived as others would.

人生独一无二，不能照搬别人的生活方式。

About the Author

作者简介

An automotive engineer by training, after having led large teams and consulted for large multinationals, Luca quit his corporate job to become an independent researcher and author.

卢卡是一名受过专业训练的汽车工程师，在领导过大型团队并为大型跨国公司提供咨询服务后，他辞去了公司的工作，成为了一名独立研究员和作家。

Luca dedicates his career to researching the topic of emerging behavior and communicating his findings and their implications.

卢卡毕生致力于研究新兴行为这一课题，并传播他的研究成果及其意义。

After having lived in Spain, Germany, Kazakhstan, and Singapore, Luca recently moved back to his hometown of Turin (Italy). He spends his days consulting, teaching, and conducting his independent research from his home, a coffee bar, or a park.

卢卡曾在西班牙、德国、哈萨克斯坦和新加坡生活过，最近搬回了他的家乡意大利都灵。他每天在家、咖啡馆或公园里从事咨询、教学和独立研究工作。

Luca also consults corporations, startups, and individuals on behavioral change and antifragile operations. Once per year, he teaches a Risk Management module at Genoa University. He also regularly holds private workshops for entrepreneurs, operations managers, plant managers, and CEOs / COOs. His course Antifragile Organizations runs a few times a year.

卢卡还为企业、初创公司和个人提供行为改变和反脆弱运营方面的咨询服务。他每年在热那亚大学讲授一次风险管理课程。此外，他还定期为企业家、运营经理、工厂经理和首席执行官/首席运营官举办私人研讨会。他的“反脆弱组织”课程每年举办数次。

The Control Heuristic, 2 nd edition

控制启发式，第 2 版

The book was featured in the EconTalk podcast.

“Luca’s book was so helpful to my work. Opened my eyes up to some more reasons why change is so hard.”

At a first look, human behavior appears as an inexplicable mess. Why do we behave irrationally? Why do I behave irrationally? Why is it so hard to change? What is happiness, and why does it seem to escape us?

乍看之下，人类行为似乎是一团难以解释的混乱。为什么我们会做出非理性的行为？为什么我会做出非理性的行为？为什么改变如此困难？幸福是什么，为什么它似乎总是与我们擦肩而过？

The brain can only be understood as a distributed entity. The key to understanding it is to look at how the different brain regions interact with each other, how misunderstandings become illusions, and how selfish interests become irrational behaviors.

大脑只能被理解为一个分布式的整体。理解大脑的关键在于观察不同脑区如何相互作用，误解如何演变为错觉，以及自私的利益如何演变为非理性行为。

The Control Heuristic offers a new perspective to answer these questions and provides a guiding light to shed the darkness of the subconscious resistances that prevent us from behaving like the man or woman we want to be.

控制启发式为我们提供了一个新的视角来回答这些问题，并为我们指明了方向，驱散了潜意识中阻碍我们成为我们想成为的人的阻力的黑暗。

The World Through a Magnifying Glass

透过放大镜看世界

– Geiger T.

“Loved The World Through a Magnifying Glass – this analogy NAILS IT.”
– Emerson Spartz, NYT Bestseller Author

This book is for parents, friends, or anyone related to someone with Autism.

这本书是为自闭症患者的父母、朋友或任何与他们相关的人准备的。

This is for neurologists and psychologists to help them understand the world of ASD.

这是为了帮助神经科医生和心理学家了解自闭症谱系障碍的世界。

This book is for people on the Spectrum, to help them understand themselves.

这本书是为自闭症谱系人士编写的，旨在帮助他们更好地了解自己。

Some of the topics covered inside:

本书涵盖的部分主题包括：

  • The Magnifying Glass: a metaphor to understand perception under the Spectrum
    放大镜：理解光谱下感知的一种隐喻
  • Why people on the Spectrum are impaired in contextual fields (such as personal communication) and advantaged in mastering detailed fields (such as computer science).
    为什么自闭症患者在情境领域（例如人际沟通）存在缺陷，而在掌握细节领域（例如计算机科学）则具有优势。
  • Peripheral Functionality Blindness: the reason people on the Spectrum do not develop appropriate body language and facial expressivity.
    周边功能障碍：自闭症谱系人士无法发展出适当的肢体语言和面部表情的原因。
  • Prioritization by Specificity: the reason literal meaning is the only thing that matters for people on the Spectrum.
    按具体性进行优先排序：对于自闭症谱系人士来说，字面意义是唯一重要的事。
  • The High-Pass filter: a novel hypothesis for the Autism Spectrum Disorder, coherent with previous theories and experimental results.
    高通滤波器：自闭症谱系障碍的一个新假设，与之前的理论和实验结果相一致。

(Reading time is about 1h30)

（阅读时间约1小时30分钟）

The Power of Adaptation

适应的力量

“This guy! Luca is amazing. So insightful with common-sense applications of complexity and the ability to communicate clearly!!” – Bob Klapetzky

“这家伙！卢卡太棒了。他对复杂问题的洞察力非常敏锐，能用常识解释问题，而且沟通能力也很强！！”——鲍勃·克拉佩茨基

This book is for you if:

如果您符合以下条件，那么这本书适合您：

  • You like books dense with information, such as Taleb’s Antifragile.
    你喜欢信息量丰富的书籍，例如塔勒布的《反脆弱》。
  • You understand or are willing to accept that the world is dynamic and that understanding how something changes is more important than understanding how something works now.
    你理解或愿意接受世界是动态的，了解事物如何变化比了解事物现在如何运作更重要。
  • You do not like usual business / self-help books that provide solutions that only work in the short term.
    你不喜欢那些只能提供短期解决方案的普通商业/自助书籍。

“The Power of Adaptation” focuses on adaptation as the main force shaping the world as we know it. However, adaptation is an emergent process and thus cannot be understood with narratives, nor can it be acted upon directly. This book aims to describe the fundamental phenomena that weave together into what we perceive as adaptation and to provide a guide to help the readers practice the four behaviors that will help them harness, rather than fight, change.

《适应的力量》一书聚焦于适应，认为它是塑造我们所知世界的主要力量。然而，适应是一个涌现的过程，因此无法用叙事来理解，也无法直接对其采取行动。本书旨在描述构成我们所理解的适应的基本现象，并提供指导，帮助读者实践四种行为，从而驾驭而非对抗变化。

Best Practices for Operational Excellence

卓越运营的最佳实践

Inside:

里面：

  • The Four Principles of Operational Excellence.
    卓越运营的四大原则。
  • The Eight Best Practices of Operational Excellence.
    卓越运营的八项最佳实践。
  • How to roll out and sustain a change initiative.
    如何推行并维持一项变革举措。

“I’m a huge fan of High Output Management and Setting the Table […] Luca’s Best Practices for Operational Excellence took my management to the next level.

“我非常喜欢高产出管理和制定计划 […] Luca 的卓越运营最佳实践将我的管理水平提升到了一个新的高度。

It’s been almost a month since I started implementing the principles, but I can already say that I’ve noticed a significant improvement in my company’s morale […] That feels amazing.”

自从我开始实施这些原则以来已经快一个月了，但我已经注意到公司士气有了显著提升……这种感觉太棒了。”

– Molson Hart, Viahart CEO

——莫尔森·哈特，Viahart首席执行官

Teams Are Adaptive Systems

团队是适应性系统

If you manage teams, one of the hardest lessons you will have to learn is that your decisions are important not for their immediate result but for the future behaviors they make more likely in your subordinates.

如果你管理团队，你将要学习的最难的一课就是，你的决策之所以重要，不是因为它们的直接结果，而是因为它们会使你的下属在未来更有可能采取某些行为。

In my professional experience, I noticed that the best managers are those who understand that teams are adaptive systems.

根据我的职业经验，我发现最好的管理者都明白团队是一个适应性系统。

Teams do not act but react. They learn not from words and speeches but from their work environment. They respond to the incentives that are communicated through action, not words.

团队并非主动行动，而是被动反应。他们不是从言辞和演讲中学习，而是从工作环境中学习。他们对通过行动而非言语传达的激励做出反应。

When I see a manager struggling, it is often not because he doesn’t make the right decisions based on what he knows but because he cannot see the experiences that his subordinates are having and that shape their behavior.

当我看到一位经理陷入困境时，通常不是因为他没有根据自己的知识做出正确的决定，而是因为他看不到下属正在经历并影响他们行为的经历。

In this book, I will teach you to see what your subordinates see, to understand how they adapt to your actions. Once you understand the pressures to which they are subject, you will know what to do to shape their behavior and align their perceived incentives to what is good for the company and their professional development.

在这本书中，我将教你如何从下属的角度看待问题，了解他们如何适应你的行为。一旦你理解了他们所承受的压力，你就能知道如何引导他们的行为，并使他们的激励机制与公司利益和他们自身的职业发展保持一致。

This book is the game-changer that transforms team management from a messy and noisy activity to a simple set of cause-effect relationships.

这本书改变了游戏规则，它将团队管理从一项混乱嘈杂的活动转变为一系列简单的因果关系。

Better to assume regression to the mean – the phenomenon by which some trends are likely to disappear after some time. For example, if you toss a coin and get four heads in a row, it might mean that the coin is different, or it might mean that the coin wasn’t so different after all, and the particular trend observed was temporary and caused by luck or other transient circumstances.

最好假设存在均值回归现象——这种现象指的是某些趋势在一段时间后可能会消失。例如，如果你连续抛掷一枚硬币，出现四次正面，这可能意味着这枚硬币有所不同，但也可能意味着这枚硬币其实并没有那么不同，观察到的特定趋势只是暂时的，是由运气或其他短暂因素造成的。

Naval Ravikant inspired this, having said: “I realized that all these people that I was jealous of, I couldn’t just cherry-pick and choose little aspects of their life. I couldn’t say I want his body, I want her money, I want his personality. You have to be that person. Do you want to actually be that person with all of their reactions, their desires, their family, their happiness level, their outlook on life, their self-image? If you’re not willing to do a wholesale, 24/7, 100% swap with who that person is, then there is no point in being jealous.”

纳瓦尔·拉维坎特（Naval Ravikant）曾说过：“我意识到，我嫉妒的这些人，我不能只挑剔他们生活中的某些方面。我不能说我想要他的身材，我想要她的钱，我想要他的性格。你必须成为那样的人。你真的想成为那样的人吗？你想拥有他们的所有反应、欲望、家庭、幸福感、人生观和自我认知吗？如果你不愿意完全地、24/7、100%地与那样的人交换，那么嫉妒就毫无意义。”

Author Alexander Wolfe noted that (paraphrased) “People who don’t take risks don’t understand that it is better to risk and fail at something that resonates deep within than to do nothing”. To which I replied: “[That’s] the difference between external failure (proxy) and internal success (actual metric to consider).”

作家亚历山大·沃尔夫曾指出（大意是）：“不愿冒险的人不明白，与其什么都不做，不如去冒险去做那些能引起内心共鸣的事情，即使失败也比什么都不做要好。”对此，我回应道：“这就是外部失败（替代指标）和内部成功（真正需要考虑的衡量标准）之间的区别。”

[ ←11 ]
[←11]

This is not (only) a repetition of Goodhart’s law (“When a measure becomes a target, it ceases to be a good measure”). Goodhart focused on people gaming the system once a regulator introduced a policy. My heuristic is more general and works in single-player scenarios too. It is because the easiest way to improve an unweighted metric is often to include “low quality” items – items whose specific weight towards the ultimate goal is lower. E.g., in the example in the text, the easiest way to improve the number of followers is to attract those who won’t buy anything.

这并非（仅仅）是对古德哈特定律（“当一项指标成为目标时，它就不再是一项好的指标”）的重复。古德哈特关注的是监管机构出台政策后，人们如何钻制度的空子。我的启发式方法更具普适性，也适用于单人操作场景。这是因为，提高未加权指标最简单的方法通常是纳入“低质量”项目——即那些对最终目标权重较低的项目。例如，在文中的例子中，提高粉丝数量的最简单方法是吸引那些不会购买任何东西的人。

As a reminder, it consists of the following. First, write down the twenty-five most important things you should do. Next, circle the most important five. Finally, move these to your to-do list, and the other twenty to your not-to-do list (these twenty tasks would be busywork, which, by the way, is a proxy for real work).

再次提醒，具体步骤如下。首先，写下你应该做的二十五件最重要的事。接下来，圈出最重要的五件。最后，将这五件移到你的待办事项清单中，其余二十件移到你的不做事项清单中（这二十件任务属于琐事，顺便说一句，这可以看作是真正工作的替代品）。

[←16]

Some readers might have noticed some similarities between this list and the contents of Nassim Nicholas Taleb’s Incerto. That’s because the Incerto is, too, about how to spot and get rid of proxies (at least partially). Fooled by Randomness is about spurious correlations between proxies and real metrics; The Black Swan is about frequencies used as proxies for impact; Antifragile is about averages used as a proxy for distributions.

有些读者可能已经注意到这份清单与纳西姆·尼古拉斯·塔勒布的《不确定性》（Incerto）一书的内容有几分相似。这是因为《不确定性》也是关于如何识别并（至少部分地）摒弃代理变量。《随机漫步的傻瓜》（Fooled by Randomness）探讨的是代理变量与真实指标之间虚假的相关性；《黑天鹅》（The Black Swan）探讨的是频率被用作影响的代理变量；《反脆弱》（Antifragile）探讨的是平均值被用作分布的代理变量。

I cannot think of any great leader that didn’t have them both, hence why I stated they are required. But are they really sufficient? I believe so (perhaps with the addition of some requirements of not having some negative traits). Of course, most great leaders are also charismatic communicators, but I believe that this is a skill which is acquired post-hoc , as a product of leading, not before leading.

我想不出有哪位伟大的领导者不具备这两项特质，所以我才说它们是必备的。但它们真的足够吗？我认为足够（或许还需要一些其他条件，比如不能有某些负面特质）。当然，大多数伟大的领导者也都是极具魅力的沟通者，但我认为这种技能是在领导之后习得的，是领导经验的产物，而不是在领导之前就具备的。

Of course, there might be boundaries not to cross (e.g., “you cannot do this”) or processes to follow (e.g., “you have to fill this form”). But only mention them if not following them would imply a bad outcome. Instead, if these boundaries are just personal preferences, do not mention them.

当然，可能存在一些不可逾越的界限（例如，“你不能这样做”）或需要遵循的流程（例如，“你必须填写此表格”）。但只有当不遵守这些界限会导致不良后果时才需要提及。相反，如果这些界限仅仅是个人偏好，则无需提及。

A better approach than saying “no” to your boss’ requests is to reply with “ok boss, I can do that, but I will have to postpone something else. What of the tasks on my plate should be delayed?”
比直接拒绝老板的要求更好的方法是回复说：“好的老板，我可以做，但我需要推迟其他事情。我手头上的哪些任务需要推迟呢？”
Not only it is a more constructive approach than refusing a new task, but it also has the added benefits of letting your boss know all the things you are doing, of which he might only be partially aware.
这不仅比拒绝新任务更具建设性，而且还能让老板了解你正在做的所有事情，而他可能只部分了解这些事情。

[ ←25 ]
[←25]

Outcome is a lagging indicator, and personal growth is a leading one. As explained elsewhere in this book, using lagging indicators as bases for judgment always leads to bad decisions, whereas using leading indicators leads to good ones.

结果是一个滞后指标，而个人成长是一个领先指标。正如本书其他章节所述，以滞后指标作为判断依据总是会导致错误的决策，而以领先指标作为判断依据则会导致正确的决策。

[ ←26 ]
[←26]

External karma heavily relies on chances and coincidences. Therefore, it might be a human confabulation for random events. Instead, internal karma is a more concrete and reproducible processes.

外在业力很大程度上依赖于机遇和巧合。因此，它可能是人类对随机事件的一种臆造。相反，内在业力则是一个更为具体且可重复的过程。

[←27]

What I describe is obvious, but worth stating anyway, given its importance and how often we forget it in our daily life.

我所描述的事情显而易见，但鉴于其重要性以及我们在日常生活中经常忘记它，仍然值得一提。

[ ←28 ]
[←28]

This is not an invitation to ignore missteps but to react to them constructively, in a way that benefits the partnership’s long-term success rather than one’s fleeting emotions. For example, between an aggressive remark and keeping one’s mouth shout there is a generous piece of constructive feedback that doesn’t start from “I’m right and you’re wrong,” but from, “How can we make this work in the long term?”

这并非鼓励大家对失误视而不见，而是鼓励大家以建设性的方式应对，从而促进合作关系的长期成功，而非受制于一时的情绪。例如，与其恶语相向，不如提出更具建设性的反馈，这种反馈并非以“我是对的，你是错的”开头，而是以“我们如何才能让这段关系长期发展下去？”开头。

[ ←29 ]
[←29]

Note: misstepping twice is a common symptom of having failed to address a root problem. Striving to avoid making the same mistake twice in a row is a great way to stay focused on taking care of root problems.

注意：两次犯同样的错误是未能解决根本问题的常见表现。努力避免连续两次犯同样的错误是专注于解决根本问题的有效方法。

[←30]

Too often, we underestimate what’s in our possibilities. Let me give you an example. Wherever you are now – sitting at home, on the bus, etc. – raise your left hand as much as possible.

我们常常低估了自身的可能性。让我举个例子。无论你现在身在何处——在家、在公交车上等等——尽可能多地举起你的左手。

Now, raise it a bit more.

现在，再把它抬高一点。

You didn’t actually raise it as much as possible the first time, did you?

你第一次并没有尽可能地提高它的数值，对吧？

Something more was possible.

还有更多可能性。

(I adapted this example from a talk by Seth Godin)

（这个例子改编自塞思·戈丁的演讲）

I do get some feedback from readers, though. And starting with my ninth book, I had early readers. Still, I reviewed all feedback and final edits were mine.

我确实会收到一些读者的反馈。从我的第九本书开始，我就有了早期读者。不过，我还是认真审阅了所有反馈，最终的修改也是由我完成的。

In my book “The Control Heuristic,” I dedicate a full chapter to the topic of willpower, arguing that it is a confabulation for what would have caused us to power through a situation in which we would have expected ourselves to quit. In the present book, I instead use the term “willpower” in its common usage.

在我的著作《控制启发式》中，我用整整一章的篇幅探讨了意志力这一主题，并论证了意志力不过是我们为了弥补某种缺陷而编造出来的，它驱使我们坚持完成了原本认为自己应该放弃的处境。而在本书中，我将采用“意志力”一词的常用含义。

[ ←36 ]
[←36]

Two recommended readings on the topic are Taleb’s Antifragile (2012) and my book Ergodicity (2020).

关于这个主题，推荐阅读两本书：塔勒布的《反脆弱》（2012 年）和我的著作《遍历性》（2020 年）。

Jed Trott noted that “90% of things which are labeled smart should instead just be called connected . It is a better description of the tradeoff.”

杰德·特罗特指出，“90%被贴上‘智能’标签的产品，其实应该直接称为‘互联’产品。这样更能准确地描述两者之间的权衡取舍。”

I would add that the principle applies to both appliances and pundits.

我还要补充一点，这个原则既适用于电器，也适用于评论员。

I recommend it highly.

我强烈推荐。
